<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Health commissioner questions timing of expanded drug program  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - An expansion of the state's program to help senior
citizens pay for prescription drugs is a good idea whose time may not have yet
come, Gov. George Pataki's health commissioner says.
<P>
	   Dr. Antonia Novello said Monday she has a quarter-century experience with
the federal government and thinks the state could end up being penalized if it
boldly develops its own expanded drug program at this time.
</P>
<P>
	   She noted that President Clinton has called for a $195 billion program for
Medicare prescription benefits over the next decade. It might make sense, she
told a joint state Assembly-Senate hearing Monday on the 2000-01 state budget,
to get an idea of what Washington has in mind before New York acts.
</P>
<P>
	   "New York should wait to see what the feds do first before we act, because
our experience shows that when we have moved forward with a program which is
then followed by a federal program, our state has been penalized," she said.
</P>
<P>
	   If history is any guide, Washington will adopt on a national scale much of
what New York has been doing for 12 years with its "extremely wonderful"
prescription program, Novello said. New York shouldn't struggle to set up its
own expanded version of a prescription program, only to then take potentially
costly steps to conform the state program with the national one, she said.
</P>
<P>
	   "Knowing the feds, it's best to let them put it first," Novello said.
</P>
<P>
	   A Novello spokesman, John Signor, said later the commissioner also told
lawmakers that if the Legislature and governor go ahead with a more ambitious
state drug plan, her department would try to work with Washington to minimize
the changes that would be necessary if a federal program follows.
</P>
<P>
	   Novello spent a quarter century in Washington with the U.S. Public Health
Service and as U.S. surgeon general before joining the Pataki administration.
</P>
<P>
	   Pataki's proposed budget calls for funding the state's pharmaceuticals
program - Elderly Pharmaceutical Insurance Coverage or "EPIC" - to increase by
about $30 million to $148 million in fiscal 2000-01. Enrollment would also rise
from the current 112,000 to 122,500 by March 31, 2001.
</P>
<P>
	   Pataki's budget proposal anticipates that more people will enroll in the
EPIC program, not that eligibility requirements would be expanded.
</P>
<P>
	   The state Senate, meanwhile, has proposed expanding the income limits on
EPIC to double the eligibility pool to 229,900 senior citizens statewide. Senate
Majority Leader Joseph Bruno said the state should spend $125 million out of its
share of the settlement with the tobacco companies to help pay for the expanded
program.
</P>
<P>
	   State Sen. Kemp Hannon, a Nassau County Republican who chairs the Senate
health committee, suggested at the budget hearing Monday that the Legislature
could enact its own EPIC expansion and then tailor it to whatever Washington
adopts.
</P>
<P>
	   John McArdle, a spokesman for Bruno, also indicated that the Senate was not
inclined to delay expanding the prescription program.
</P>
<P>
	   "We believe very strongly that providing seniors with immediate relief is
critical and we will not wait for any lame duck president to act," McArdle said.
"We are going to act and we are going to make it our chief and primary budget
initiative."
</P>
<P>
	   Currently under EPIC, New Yorkers age 65 and older who make $18,500 a year
as an individual or $24,400 a year as a couple, are eligible for
state-subsidized cuts in prescription drug costs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
