<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pataki, Bruno exchange Valentine's wishes, for now  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   LATHAM, N.Y. (AP) - Gov. George Pataki and state Senate Majority Leader
Joseph Bruno are over their Republican spat - not that either acknowledged one
in the first place.
<P>
	   Pataki spoke Monday of Bruno's significant role and accomplishments during
the governor's two terms. Asked if he wants Bruno to continue to lead the
Senate's Republican majority, Pataki said: "It's not my decision, but I like
him."
</P>
<P>
	   Bruno wouldn't be outdone.
</P>
<P>
	   "Valentine's Day is a day of love and togetherness," said Bruno at a ribbon
cutting for a plant at the Plug Power plant near Albany that develops fuel cells
with chemical reactions to power homes and cars.
</P>
<P>
	   "If this doesn't represent love and togetherness I don't know what does,"
Bruno said. "And what happens when people work together? Things like this."
</P>
<P>
	   Bruno said he is "proud to have partnered with our great governor, George
Pataki." Then Bruno noted several other "partners," including Democrats.
</P>
<P>
	   Top Republicans worried the Pataki-Bruno feud would detract from a unified
Republican front with the suddenly contentious New York presidential primary
less than a month away, sources said.
</P>
<P>
	   The state GOP leadership's choice, Pataki friend George W. Bush, is fighting
to regain momentum nationally and in New York state after losing to Arizona Sen.
John McCain in New Hampshire's primary in January.
</P>
<P>
	   And last week, Rep. Rick Lazio - drawing parallels with McCain - said he is
seriously considering the state Conservative Party's invitation to enter the
U.S. Senate race, but only if he also had the Republican nomination.
</P>
<P>
	   Pataki on Monday repeated his strong support for New York City Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani for Senate.
</P>
<P>
	   Since late January, Pataki and Bruno, of Rensselaer County, have been
fighting over whether the state should pick up the counties' share of a new
health insurance program, plus other policy issues and perceived or actual
slights.
</P>
<P>
	   Most dramatically, those slights included the firing of at least three
Bruno-sponsored state workers in the Pataki administration in an action widely
interpreted by Bruno's members as a show of gubernatorial displeasure in Senate
Republicans. GOP senators also said the governor contacted them directly to ask
about Senate politics, instead of going through Bruno.
</P>
<P>
	   Pataki on Monday would not acknowledge any connection between a spat with
Bruno and the dismissals within his administration.
</P>
<P>
	   "This administration has made thousands of changes over the course of the
last five years and we're going to make thousands more," he said.
</P>
<P>
	   What aides described as a heated meeting last week between Pataki and Bruno
appeared to have helped clear the air somewhat, and staffers for both men
resumed arranging joint public appearances for the pair late last week. Monday
was the first such event. Neither camp on Monday would directly talk about the
reason for the rift.
</P>
<P>
	   Bruno and Pataki are state government's most powerful Republicans, and their
spat came at an important time governmentally, as well as politically.
</P>
<P>
	   This is the time of year when Pataki and Bruno try to reconcile their state
budget agendas for the next fiscal year in hopes of being allied in negotiations
against the Democratic state Assembly, though in current years that has not
always happened.
</P>
<P>
	   "I'm hoping that all the differences of opinion or political bumps in the
road are over so we can pass a budget on time, with substance," said Democratic
Assemblyman Paul Tonko of Amsterdam at Monday's event.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
