<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-15 00:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Giuliani steps up campaign pace  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - Stepping up his campaign pace in the face of
complaints from some Republican leaders, Rudolph Giuliani is blasting his Senate
rival's husband, President Clinton.
<P>
	   "A president who is so famous for feeling our pain, somehow doesn't feel the
pain of New Yorkers," Giuliani told a news conference Monday after meeting
privately with state GOP leaders.
</P>
<P>
	   In his fourth political stop in five days outside New York City, the mayor
replayed his Saturday criticism of the president's unwillingness to dip into the
nation's strategic oil reserves in the face of sharply rising fuel oil costs.
</P>
<P>
	   "Frankly, if he's not going to feel our pain, maybe if we create enough
political pain, he'll finally act," the mayor said.
</P>
<P>
	   Giuliani and Hillary Rodham Clinton are competing for the Senate seat being
vacated this year by Democrat Daniel Patrick Moynihan.
</P>
<P>
	   Also Monday, New York Gov. George Pataki sought to knock down speculation
that he was somehow looking to hurt Giuliani's chances by encouraging U.S. Rep.
Rick Lazio, a Long Island Republican, to renew his interest in the Senate race.
</P>
<P>
	   Lazio, with encouragement from state Conservative Party Chairman Michael
Long, a Pataki ally, has said he is again weighing an entry into the race for
the GOP and Conservative parties' nominations.
</P>
<P>
	   Maintaining he wants Lazio to remain on the sidelines, Pataki said Monday
that he would "like to see all Republicans get behind Mayor Giuliani. I think
that's the right thing to do."
</P>
<P>
	   "The governor has been very supportive," Giuliani said at his news
conference that did not include the governor.
</P>
<P>
	   In August, and under pressure from national party leaders, Pataki convinced
Lazio to put his Senate race plans on hold in favor of Giuliani. But since
then,Longhas become increasingly vocal with complaints that Giuliani, who
supports abortion and gay rights, is not conservative enough for Conservatives.
Long has said he is looking for an alternative candidate. Pataki and the mayor
have had an icy relationship in the past.
</P>
<P>
	   No Republican has won statewide office in New York since 1974 without having
both the GOP and Conservative ballot lines. Unlike other states, New York allows
votes on third-party lines to count for major party candidates.
</P>
<P>
	   Giuliani's visit to Albany on Monday came in the wake of criticism from some
Republican leaders that he was not paying enough attention to upstate New York,
a critical battleground in his race with the first lady.
</P>
<P>
	   "She's been all over," one upstate GOP leader, speaking on condition of
anonymity, grumbled after Monday's meeting.
</P>
<P>
	   After formally announcing her candidacy on Feb. 6, Clinton set off on a
four-day swing across upstate New York that took her from Buffalo to Albany.
Giuliani held political events in Buffalo on Thursday, suburban Westchester
County on Friday and on Long Island on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
	   In Albany, the mayor said he wasn't intentionally stepping up his political
pace.
</P>
<P>
	   "We're doing the best that we can, given the fact that I have
responsibilities as the mayor of New York City," Giuliani said before hurrying
back to the city to perform a Valentine's Day wedding.
</P>
<P>
	   The heating oil issue seemed tailor-made for Giuliani given that the highest
price hikes have come in New York state and the Northeast since the OPEC nations
cut production. Thus far, despite pressure from a bipartisan group that includes
Sen. Charles Schumer, a New York Democrat, President Clinton has refused to dip
into the oil reserves.
</P>
<P>
	   On Monday, Hillary Clinton said she favored dipping into the reserves with a
swap system under which U.S. oil companies would be able to borrow from the
stockpile and make larger donations back to it at a later date.
</P>
<P>
	   Brooke Anderson, a spokeswoman for the Clinton administration's Energy
Department, said Monday that "the administration is not actively considering
using the strategic petroleum reserves in the current context."
</P>
<P>
	   She said the administration has been providing extra money to the poor to
help pay their heating oil bills and is trying to help heating oil distributors
with possible cash-flow problems. She said Energy Secretary Bill Richardson
would be meeting Wednesday in Boston with officials from the heating oil
industry and others to discuss the problem.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
