<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-15 00:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> State consolidates pheasant breeding  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - Hunters and animals rights activists have each taken
shots at a cost-saving consolidation of New York's pheasant breeding program.
<P>
	   For decades, New York has raised ring-necked pheasants for the benefit of
hunters - most recently at state-run game farms near Batavia and in Ithaca.
</P>
<P>
	   But the Batavia-area John White Game Farm was closed in January to ease the
drain on the state's troubled Conservation Fund, which pays for the program.
Gov. George Pataki is seeking a one-time $700,000 appropriation in his budget
proposal to upgrade Reynolds Game Farm, the remaining Ithaca-based pheasant
raising operation.
</P>
<P>
	   Hunters and animals rights activists have both criticized the consolidation
moves - for very different reasons.
</P>
<P>
	   Hunters, like those represented by the New York State Conservation Council,
oppose closing the White farm. On the other side of the spectrum, the Fund for
Animals has criticized the plan to use $700,000 in general tax revenue instead
of money from the sports license-financed Conservation Fund to pay for the
Reynolds upgrade.
</P>
<P>
	   "This program uses hand-raised birds as targets for living amusement," said
the fund's Heidi Prescott. The state "should not be serving 'pheasant under
glass' at the public's expense."
</P>
<P>
	   State Department of Environmental Conservation spokeswoman Jennifer Post
said the pheasant program is part of the department's mission of providing and
protecting game species.
</P>
<P>
	   "This provides a type of hunting opportunity that wouldn't otherwise exist,"
she said. Closing the White farm and upgrading facilities at the Reynolds farm
will be more economical, according to Post.
</P>
<P>
	   Reynolds, next to Cornell University, is the last of seven state pheasant
farms. The requested $700,000 would go to roughly doubling the farm's
capacities. Pheasant production is expected to dip for one year during
construction, but rebound after that.
</P>
<P>
	   In recent years, New York state has raised some 40,000 pheasants annually
for release in areas accessible to hunters. Another 60,000 day-old chicks go to
4-H Clubs and hunters' groups, which raise and release the birds on their own.
</P>
<P>
	   The program costs the Conservation Fund about $700,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
	   The Pataki administration is looking to shore up that fund in the face of a
potential deficit, most notably through a proposed increases of up to $5 in
sports license fees. The closing of the White farm is expected to save the fund
$200,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
	   Dan Tone, chairman of the New York State Conservation Council's small game
committee, complained that with all the pheasants raised in one location, they
are more vulnerable to devastation by disease or disaster. And he added that
there are fears pheasant production will dip beyond the year promised by DEC,
meaning fewer birds in the wild.
</P>
<P>
	   "If people go out there and they're not going to find pheasants, they're
going to give up their hunting licenses," Tone said, noting that could crimp the
Conservation Fund even further.
</P>
<P>
	   That might be just fine by the Fund for Animals, which has a long-standing
opposition to hunting and the pheasant program. Prescott notes that few of the
domestically raised pheasants survive the winter. Those that are killed by
hunters often fall victims to other predators or cars.
</P>
<P>
	   State environmental officials reported 90,774 pheasants hunted in the
1998-99 season based on a telephone survey of hunters. That number is down from
earlier years because of fewer small game hunters and fewer wild birds, Post
said. The Fund For Animals, relying on data from the DEC, said there were
123,743 pheasants hunted in the 1996-97 season.
</P>
<P>
	   Other than fish, pheasants are the only animal the state stocks for the
sporting community, Post said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-02-15-00 0008 </TRAILER>
