<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-15 00:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> House pushes for ATM fee ban  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) - Legislation that would make it illegal for banks
to charge fees to non-customers who use their automated teller machines does not
have the support of several key state senators.
<P>
	   But House leaders on Monday said they will make a bipartisan push to outlaw
the so-called "convenience fees."
</P>
<P>
	   A similar bill passed the House last year but died in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
	   "It's a free-market issue and it's about consumer choice," said Sen. Brian
McDermott, D-Wallingford, co-chairman of the Legislature's Banks Committee.
"It's not up to us to regulate fees."
</P>
<P>
	   McDermott said he won't try to kill the bill in committee, but said he won't
try to pass it from his committee to the General Assembly unless there's
widespread support for it.
</P>
<P>
	   "I'm not going to force a vote for something people don't want," he said.
</P>
<P>
	   Senate Majority Leader George Jepsen, D-Stamford, said the Legislature would
be wise to wait and see whether courts rule that states can prohibit
federally-chartered banks from charging the fees.
</P>
<P>
	   Such cases are pending in California.
</P>
<P>
	   "It would be unfair if we were left with one set of rules to regulate state
banks, but not federal banks," Jepsen said.
</P>
<P>
	   The state Supreme Court ruled in December that Connecticut's banking
commissioner did not have the authority to ban the fees, which are levied when
customers use an ATM owned by a bank where they do not have an account.
</P>
<P>
	   The fees, typically ranging from $1 to $2, are in addition to the costs
often charged by the customer's own bank for using another bank's ATM.
</P>
<P>
	   Prior to the court decision, banks in the state had been banned from
charging the second fee. After the ruling, large banks such as First Union,
Fleet and BankBoston began charging non-customers the convenience fees. Other
smaller, state-chartered banks are not charging the fees.
</P>
<P>
	   The legislation would deal only with the convenience fees.
</P>
<P>
	   "This bill ensures that Connecticut's consumers will be fairly treated by
financial institutions by permitting only one, identified fee per bank
transaction," said Rep. Robert Landino, D-Westbrook, the other co-chairman of
the Banks Committee.
</P>
<P>
	   "This allows banks to be reasonably compensated for the cost of operating
ATMs and still gives banks the ability to earn a profit on each transaction,"
Landino said.
</P>
<P>
	   State Attorney General Richard Blumenthal, a leading critic of convenience
fees, said the charges are anti-competetive and unfair to customers.
</P>
<P>
	   "There is a fundamental principal of fairness that argues in favor of this
ban to double charges," Blumenthal said. "People deserve and need access to
their own money without being charged twice for it."
</P>
<P>
	   House Minority Leader Robert Ward, R-Northfield, agreed.
</P>
<P>
	   "It is bad policy to encourage customers to depend on ATMs and then start
charging fees," he said.
</P>
<P>
	   Jim Schepker, a spokesman for Fleet, said his company is gearing up to fight
the bill.
</P>
<P>
	   "We believe choice is important to consumers," he said. "Price controls
restrict choice and hurt competition. And that's bad for consumers."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
