<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-15 01:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> For better or for worse, real-life divorces find niche in court TV  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   NEW YORK (AP) - In two earlier incarnations, the TV show "Divorce Court"
used actors to play the separating spouses. Viewers now get the real thing,
complete with whining, tears and taunts.
<P>
	   The new "Divorce Court," a syndicated success midway through its first
season, provides a forum for ex-partners to lash out at each other publicly in
ways that might not be allowed during divorce proceedings in a real court.
</P>
<P>
	   "There are lots and lots of people who divorce amicably. They don't need to
be on a TV show," said the producer, Jill Blackstone. "Our show is about people
whose marriages have ended badly."
</P>
<P>
	   Presiding over the studio courtroom is Mablean Ephriam, not a real judge but
a savvy, quick-witted lawyer with more than 20 years experience in the family
courts of Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
	   Ephriam doesn't actually grant divorces; that happens elsewhere. But after
scolding, lecturing and sometimes comforting the participants, she rules on some
dispute - usually over money or property - that the couple mutually agreed would
be resolved on the show.
</P>
<P>
	   "When you hear the stories, you have trouble holding back the laughter, or
the tears, or the anger," Ephriam said in a telephone interview. "Some of the
stuff is just utterly ridiculous."
</P>
<P>
	   The prevalence of no-fault divorce in America means many couples split up
without a chance to go on public record with their gripes against their ex.
</P>
<P>
	   "The emotions, the hurt are still there, but no one listens in court
anymore," Ephriam said. "Our show is cathartic. ... It's good to let go of
emotions."
</P>
<P>
	   Blackstone said the show's appearance fee of $500 per guest is not a primary
motive for those volunteering. Some do so out of vanity or vengefulness, but
most simply want their day in court.
</P>
<P>
	   "They want to be heard - 'He did me wrong,' 'She did me wrong,"' Blackstone
said. "There's a drama in a failed relationship, a passion, and a pain, and
often a humor. It's something everyone can relate to."
</P>
<P>
	   Though they risk moments of nationally televised humiliation, the feuding
couples get a practical benefit - Ephriam's end-of-show ruling serves as a
binding settlement of a dispute that otherwise might have entailed legal costs.
</P>
<P>
	   In a crowded field of court shows, "Divorce Court" has done well for a
newcomer, trailing only "Judge Judy" and "Judge Joe Brown" in the latest ratings
of the genre. It is produced in Los Angeles by Twentieth Television, a division
of Fox.
</P>
<P>
	   The original "Divorce Court" aired in the 1950s, with then-obscure actors
such as Alan Alda and Jack Nicholson among the performers. A revival appeared in
the 1980s, again using actors as spouses.
</P>
<P>
	   Ephriam hopes her audience benefits from watching real-life marital woes.
</P>
<P>
	   "One advantage of the show, for those who are married and going through some
difficulty, is that they may see themselves," she said. "When you hear it from
somebody else, you think, 'Do I say that? Is that what I sound like?'
</P>
<P>
	   "People who are thinking of marriage might rethink constructively. Even
teen-agers - I hope they're learning you should check people out."
</P>
<P>
	   One couple from Virginia told Ephriam they watched the show together and
found it helped them appreciate each other more.
</P>
<P>
	   She herself is divorced but doesn't rule out another try.
</P>
<P>
	   "I believe very strongly in the institution of marriage," said Ephriam. "It
saddens me to see how people enter into a marital relationship without any
thought about what it is."
</P>
<P>
	   From the outset, "Divorce Court" has steered clear of alimony and child
custody cases. But Blackstone recalls a memorable custody dispute of a different
sort.
</P>
<P>
	   A couple came on the show hoping to resolve a complex financial dispute, but
the woman soon revealed her biggest concern: Beanie Babies.
</P>
<P>
	   When Ephriam ruled that a prized collection of the beanbag animals should be
split, the woman started whining that half a collection was worthless. In a
flash, the judge ruled that the whole collection would go to the man, and the
studio audience roared approval.
</P>
<P>
	   There are sadder cases. One woman contended her husband had cheated on her,
given her gonorrhea and run up big debts on her credit card by patronizing
phone-sex services. She was devastated when Ephriam ruled that those debts had
to be split 50-50.
</P>
<P>
	   Ephriam fought back tears during another show. A couple was quarreling over
how to divide items they bought for their first child, who had died within an
hour of birth.
</P>
<P>
	   "What are you people doing to yourselves?" the judge asked, reacting more
like a mother.
</P>
<P>
	   They stepped back for a moment, she recalled. Then both started conceding.
</P>
<P>
	   "I felt much better," she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
