<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-15 01:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Woman who lost house is getting it back, legislator says  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   NEW CITY, N.Y. (AP) - Rockland County Legislator Ryan Karben says the
circumstance involving a woman who lost her home over a $58 tax bill has a
positive ending.
<P>
	   The woman has her home back, and Rockland County has shown itself to be a
giving community, and finally, it's led Karben to take action to ensure a
similar incident does not happen again.
</P>
<P>
	   "This settlement is testament to the neighborly spirit of Rockland," Karben
said during a press conference Monday. "Common sense and compassion triumphed
over bureaucratic indifference."
</P>
<P>
	   He said he would introduce Mirielle's Law, a series of resolutions designed
to prevent another such foreclosure like that endured by Mirielle Leroy. Under
the plan, delinquent taxpayers would have to be notified by certified mail, and
a personal visit from the Finance Department would be required before any
owner-occupied home could be foreclosed on.
</P>
<P>
	   Leroy, who claimed she first heard about the foreclosure and auction of her
Spring Valley home when she received an eviction notice last month from the new
owner, said she was relieved.
</P>
<P>
	   "No one should ever have to go through what I went through," she said.
</P>
<P>
	   Leroy, a 38-year-old nurse with a 14-year-old daughter, emigrated from Haiti
17 years ago and bought the townhouse on Sharon Drive in 1996 for $114,000.
</P>
<P>
	   She never missed a mortgage payment, and her mortgage company paid the tax
bills from an escrow account - except one, a bill for $58.67 sent out in 1997 by
the Town of Ramapo. It represented what Leroy owed for receiving a few months'
worth of a veterans' tax exemption that applied to the previous owner but not to
her.
</P>
<P>
	   Town and county officials say at least four notices were sent to Leroy by
first-class mail, but she says she didn't receive them and assumed all taxes
were being paid by the mortgage company.
</P>
<P>
	   Despite the low amount of the unpaid bill - even with penalties, it grew to
only $270 - the county Legislature approved the foreclosure last year, and the
county went ahead with the auction in October.
</P>
<P>
	   Carlo Jean Pierre, of Wesley Hills, won the house with a $60,000 bid, took
title Jan. 11 and ordered Leroy, his tenant, to leave. He delayed the eviction
when he heard her explanation but insisted that if he just gave her the house
back, he would lose his anticipated profit.
</P>
<P>
	   Karben said he had arranged a complicated agreement:
</P>
<P>
	   -A state court will be asked to nullify the sale to Pierre, which Karben
said would happen quickly.
</P>
<P>
	   -The county will refund Pierre's $60,000 plus an estimated $2,000 in closing
costs.
</P>
<P>
	   -The mortgage company, Norwest, will pay Pierre $15,000, representing the
profit he could have made on the house.
</P>
<P>
	   -Community groups will pay Leroy's legal bills, amounting to nearly $2,000.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-02-15-00 0104 </TRAILER>
