<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chavez, Former Coup Leaders Feud  </HEADLINE>
   By BART JONES Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) -- They were brothers-in-arms, four junior military
officers who conspired for 10 years to overthrow Venezuela's government. One,
Hugo Chavez, eventually became president.
</P>
<P>
	   But now the former coup leaders are feuding, and their anger at Chavez's
alleged betrayal of the revolution they risked their lives for is threatening to
rupture the president's governing coalition just a year after he took office.
</P>
<P>
	   ``This is the beginning of the breakdown of the government of Chavez,'' said
retired Vice Adm. Mario Ivan Carratu Molina, who whisked then-President Carlos
Andres Perez to safety the night the military rebels stormed Miraflores
presidential palace.
</P>
<P>
	   Chavez's fellow coup leaders say the president is surrounding himself with
members of the corrupt oligarchy that their revolt was aimed at overthrowing --
the same people they blame for squandering the country's vast wealth oil,
leaving most Venezuelans impoverished.
</P>
<P>
	   They also claim Chavez is stifling democratic debate and that his
administration is becoming corrupt. The charges come from Chavez's former
intelligence chief -- the man who knew all the secrets and now is talking -- the
highly popular governor of powerful Zulia state in the heart of Venezuela's huge
oil industry, and the former head of Chavez's political party.
</P>
<P>
	   The allegations could be particularly damaging to Chavez because he rode a
wave of public disgust over rampant corruption to win the presidential race in
December 1998 and has made the fight against corruption a pillar of his
government.
</P>
<P>
	   In a nationally broadcast address Friday night, Chavez said a full
investigation into the corruption charges will be conducted and that he has
nothing to hide. His supporters say the other three coup leaders are attacking
him because they are jealous of his political success and want a bigger share of
power.
</P>
<P>
	   The three coup leaders used the eighth anniversary of the Feb. 4, 1992,
military rebellion to issue a warning that Chavez's ``peaceful revolution'' was
losing direction. They've called on him to fire his two closest political
allies, Congressional President Luis Miquilena and Foreign Minister Jose Vicente
Rangel, saying they are part of Venezuela's corrupt oligarchy and that they
don't stand up to Chavez.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The president is surrounded by a group of servants who simply bow their
heads and say, 'Yes, master,' '' retired Lt. Col. Yoel Acosta Chirinos, the
former head of Chavez's Fifth Republic Movement political party, was quoted as
saying in Sunday's edition of El Nacional newspaper.
</P>
<P>
	   Last Thursday, retired Lt. Col. Jesus Urdaneta, who resigned two weeks ago
as Chavez's intelligence chief after clashing with Rangel, handed over to the
national prosecutor evidence of 46 cases of alleged corruption in the Chavez
administration, including charges against Miquilena and Chavez.
</P>
<P>
	   Miquilena dismissed the allegations as groundless, and his supporters argue
that it is absurd to label him part of the country's corrupt oligarchy because
he spent seven years in prison during the 1950s dictatorship of Marcos Perez
Jimenez and is generally viewed as honest.
</P>
<P>
	   On Monday, the three former coup leaders met in Zulia to plot their next
move. Zulia's governor, retired Lt. Col. Francisco Arias Cardenas, is considered
the intellectual author of the 1992 coup and now says he has presidential
ambitions himself.
</P>
<P>
	   Meanwhile, Chavez met in the presidential residence in Caracas with
Miquilena and Fifth Republic leaders. Emerging from the meeting, Miquilena
insisted that the government is ``on solid ground'' and that the rebellion of
Chavez's former comrades-in-arms presents little threat to the president's
enormous popularity.
</P>
<P>
	   Chavez may be hard-pressed to give his former comrades a bigger role in his
government because he already was under fire from critics for appointing
soldiers to many top posts. To try to counteract worries that he wants to
install a military regime, he brought in high-profile, generally respected
civilians such as Miquilena and Rangel -- the very ones whose heads the former
coup leaders are clamoring for.
</P>
<P>
	   One newspaper columnist wrote that Chavez now has two choices: Cutting off
his left hand or his right.
</P>
<P>
	   Angela Zago, a university professor with close ties to all the coup leaders,
is worried they might take more extreme actions. If they believe their
revolutionary project has been permanently betrayed, she said, they could turn
to their allies in the military to stage another revolt.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
