<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-15 01:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Officer claims he thought Diallo wore bulletproof vest  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - Inside Amadou Diallo's vestibule, there was a din
"like cannon shots." There were flashes. And wood splintering. Chaos.
<P>
	   The description by one of the four officers accused of murdering Diallo with
a barrage of 41 bullets also includes a scary sight: Diallo standing up to the
gunfire and holding a black object that appeared to be a gun.
</P>
<P>
	   Defendant Sean Carroll testified at the officers' trial Monday that he was
sure the West African immigrant was "wearing a bulletproof vest and the only way
to take him out was to shoot at his legs."
</P>
<P>
	   But when Diallo fell, Carroll said, he was shocked to look down and discover
the black object "was just a wallet. ... I said, 'Where's the (expletive) gun?"'
</P>
<P>
	   Carroll, 36 - at times sobbing - and Officer Edward McMellon, 27 - in
monotone - became the first of the four defendants to give public accounts of
how they shot Diallo while patrolling his block at 12:40 a.m. on Feb. 4, 1999.
Officers Kenneth Boss, 28, and Richard Murphy, 27, are expected to take the
stand.
</P>
<P>
	   The defendants have pleaded innocent to second-degree murder. If convicted,
they face a maximum sentence of 25 years to life in prison.
</P>
<P>
	   On Monday, Carroll and McMellon both told jurors they had experience
identifying dangerous street criminals and were trained to quickly move in - or
"close the gap" - to disarm them. Both testified they had been involved in
non-fatal shootings that were deemed justified.
</P>
<P>
	   On the morning Diallo died, the four plainclothes officers were cruising in
an unmarked car. Carroll said he became suspicious as they drove past Diallo's
apartment building and saw him on the front doorsteps "looking up and down the
block, peeking his head out ... like he didn't want to be seen."
</P>
<P>
	   Carroll claimed Diallo, 22, a street vendor, fit the description of a wanted
rapist. He also said he suspected that Diallo might be committing a robbery.
</P>
<P>
	   As the officers got out of the car, McMellon testified, he held out his
badge and said, "Police department. ... Can we have a word with you?" Instead of
stopping, Diallo retreated to the rear of a vestibule and started digging in his
right pocket, both officers testified.
</P>
<P>
	   The defendants described rushing Diallo, ordering him to "Stop!" and "Show
your hands!"
</P>
<P>
	   "We said it clear," Carroll said. "He just didn't want to listen."
</P>
<P>
	   The officers said Diallo turned toward them and began pulling out a square
black object that looked like the top of a semi-automatic pistol.
</P>
<P>
	   "My prior arrests dictated to me that this person was pulling a gun,"
Carroll said. "I just said, 'Gun. He's got a gun."'
</P>
<P>
	   Said McMellon: "I screamed 'What are you doing?' (at Diallo) ... I didn't
want to die."
</P>
<P>
	   Both officers said they had one foot in the 5-foot-by-7-foot vestibule when
they fired the first shots. As they retreated, McMellon fell down a stoop and
unto his back but kept firing.
</P>
<P>
	   Carroll and McMellon repeated defense claims that they fired all 16 shots
from their rapid-fire pistols because Diallo did not immediately go down.
Carroll denied he shot Diallo while he was flat on his back, despite evidence
that one of his bullets tunneled up the victim's leg.
</P>
<P>
	   On cross-examination, both officers said they didn't know which one of them
fired the first shot. Prosecutor Donald Levin demanded Carroll explain what was
so suspicious about a man standing on his front stoop.
</P>
<P>
	   "Looking up and down the block is not a crime, is it officer?" Levin asked.
</P>
<P>
	   "No, it is not," Carroll responded.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-02-15-00 0116 </TRAILER>
