<DOCNO> APW20000215.0048 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-15 01:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Defense asks judge to bar government witnesses  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   NEW YORK (AP) - Defense lawyers in the second Abner Louima trial asked a
judge to bar testimony that Justin Volpe promised a lawyer he would keep silent
about another police officer's role in the bathroom attack.
<P>
	   Calling the proposed testimony "hearsay within hearsay," attorney Stuart
London said Monday it would subject his client, Officer Thomas Bruder, to
"unfair prejudice" by linking him to a crime in which he had no role.
</P>
<P>
	   Bruder, 34, fellow Officer Thomas Wiese, 37, and ex-cop Charles Schwarz, 34,
are on trial for conspiring to conceal Schwarz's role in the Aug. 9, 1997,
assault on Louima in a police station lavatory.
</P>
<P>
	   The illness of a juror Monday forced a one-day recess in the trial, now in
its second week. U.S. District Judge Eugene Nickerson said the female juror
reported an upset stomach.
</P>
<P>
	   Volpe pleaded guilty last May 25 to sodomizing Louima with a broom handle at
Brooklyn's 70th Precinct. The jury in that trial subsequently convicted Schwarz
as an accomplice who held the victim down.
</P>
<P>
	   At sentencing, where he drew 30 years, Volpe said the jury had erred in
convicting Schwarz. He said only Wiese had entered the bathroom during the
attack.
</P>
<P>
	   Just days before his guilty plea, Volpe pledged his silence to Stephen Worth
- then Schwarz's lawyer - in a courthouse hallway, prosecutors told the judge in
a letter last week.
</P>
<P>
	   "In response to Worth's apparent inquiry, Volpe responded in substance:
'Don't worry, man. I'm not going to say nothin'.' Worth thanked Volpe. Volpe and
Worth then parted," the letter said.
</P>
<P>
	   In the letter, Assistant U.S. Attorney Alan Vinegrad did not name the
witnesses but said, "Volpe would have had no reason to indicate to Schwarz's
attorney his intent to 'say nothing' if Schwarz had not participated in the
sexual assault of Mr. Louima."
</P>
<P>
	   London said the government's claim was "nothing more than speculation and
wishful thinking" because it did not include the question that prompted Volpe's
vow to "say nothin"' or precisely what he meant.
</P>
<P>
	   Schwarz's current attorney, Ronald Fischetti, did not comment. He has said
he will subpoena Volpe from prison to testify.
</P>
<P>
	   Worth, a law partner of London, is defending another officer in the Amadou
Diallo murder trial in Albany. He said he would testify if subpoenaed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-02-15-00 0128 </TRAILER>
