<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-15 01:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Farm Raises Yaks, Camels for Wool  </HEADLINE>
    By TRUDY TYNAN Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   HAWLEY, Mass. (AP) -- For fancy yarns, it takes some fancy animals. That's
why passersby in these parts see a trio of shaggy, two-humped camels stepping
nonchalantly around a snow-covered New England hillside.
</P>
<P>
	   The Tregellys Fiber Farm in the Berkshire Hills of Massachusetts is raising
Bactrian camels and yaks, as well as more common critters such as llamas,
Icelandic sheep and Angora goats, for their wool.
</P>
<P>
	   "There's a real market niche for our products," said Jody Cothey, who owns
the farm with her husband, Ed. "It provides us with a way to reclaim this old
farm."
</P>
<P>
	   The Cotheys' place on Hawk Mountain is an eye-catching evolution in a state
where colonial woolen mills launched the nation's textile industry.
</P>
<P>
	   Most of the yarns spun from the exotic wools are colored with organic dyes
in the basement of the farmhouse by their business partner. They then go to the
fashion designer market or folks handy enough to knit their own versions of a
designer sweater.
</P>
<P>
	   Jody Cothey says she envisioned a place in the country with room for their
dogs and cats when they first bought the overgrown former potato farm. The
farm's name is Cornish for "Hidden Homestead."
</P>
<P>
	   Her husband added to their assortment of animals when he traded a wood
chipper for two milk goats. Then he came home from a local fair with some Angora
goats and discovered he had a knack for weaving wool as well as fishing nets.
</P>
<P>
	   And then they expanded from llamas to alpacas, yaks and camels.
</P>
<P>
	   "We were middle-agers basically starting over with a new life," she said.
</P>
<P>
	   Native to the frigid Mongolian desert and equipped with a fuzzy undercoat of
insulating wool, the Bactrian camels aren't at all bothered by the cold, said
Ed, who was a commercial fisherman. It is the soft undercoat, shed during warmer
weather, that is spun into yarn, he said.
</P>
<P>
	   "It's like furry Jell-O," his wife said, reaching up to pat a hump as the
camels -- Bob, Billy and Belinda -- pressed close to the fence.
</P>
<P>
	   The Cotheys' nine Royal Pinto yaks -- bred from Himalayan stock for the
prized white wool in their mixed brown and white coats -- seemed more at home
munching hay against a backdrop of hills rolling north into Vermont.
</P>
<P>
	   As with the camels, it is the fine undercoat shed in spring that is spun
into wool. Unspun wool is used for high-end clown wigs.
</P>
<P>
	   Their herd also includes tiny brown and white polka-dotted Jacob's sheep;
Icelandic sheep, which look like barrels of fuzz topped by quotation mark horns;
yellow-eyed, four-horned Navaho-Churro sheep; alpacas and llamas in every hue,
and White Galloway cattle, raised for their meat.
</P>
<P>
	   Most of the 1,000 pounds of wool the Cotheys' animals produce annually comes
from their 110 curly-haired Angora goats, whose fleece is spun into mohair and
mohair blends.
</P>
<P>
	   Still, the 130-acre farm, which they eventually hope to open to the public,
hasn't been cheap to establish. And after seven years, they have yet to recoup
their $1.5 million investment in barns, corrals and animals. Yaks sell for
$5,000 and up, Ed Cothey said, while camels cost about $12,000.
</P>
<P>
	   "For my whole life I've been financially secure," said Jody. "But, I've
always felt a responsibility to give something back. Reclaiming this old farm
provides me with that opportunity."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-15-00 0129 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
