<DOCNO> APW20000215.0051 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-15 01:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Virginia family sues Beth Israel for relative's autopsy, pauper's  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   NEW YORK (AP) - When someone from Beth Israel Hospital called a Virginia
man and asked him to rate the facility's care of his dead son, there was one
major problem.
<P>
	   The hospital had failed to tell the father that his son was hospitalized,
let alone dead, according to documents filed last week in Manhattan State
Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
	   "This was obviously an extremely shocking and horrible way for the family to
discover that their close relative had died," the Bowman family said in the
paperwork.
</P>
<P>
	   The Bowmans have filed a $13 million lawsuit charging that Beth Israel
conducted an unauthorized autopsy on Lewis Bowman Jr., buried him in a pauper's
grave and failed to tell them he was dead even though he had identified his
father as his next of kin.
</P>
<P>
	   Bowman, who was a 47-year-old brick layer, died in the hospital of pulmonary
embolism, a blood clot in a lung, on Aug. 14, 1998. But his father didn't
receive the call until Feb. 9, 1999, court papers say.
</P>
<P>
	   Will Shewmake, the family's lawyer in Richmond, Va., said Beth Israel failed
to contact the family even though Bowman had given his father's name as the
relative to be notified in case of an emergency.
</P>
<P>
	   When the family received Bowman's body, it had been mutilated in an autopsy,
to which the family objects on religious grounds, and had decomposed so badly
that the family could not have an open-casket funeral.
</P>
<P>
	   Beth Israel spokesman Jim Mandler issued a statement:
</P>
<P>
	   "The medical center is deeply sorry that the family members in Virginia were
not notified of the death of our patient Lewis Bowman Jr. Our sympathy is
extended to the Bowman family for their loss."
</P>
<P>
	   The statement added: "Upon learning of this situation, we worked with the
family to make appropriate reburial arrangements, for which the medical center
assumed full financial responsibility."
</P>
<P>
	   Shewmake said Bowman had come to New York City to look for work. His family
last heard from him when he told them he was staying with a friend, Shewmake
said.
</P>
<P>
	   Bowman's father, Lewis Bowman Sr., who had cancer, died July 31, 1999,
before the family got his son's body back for burial in the family plot near
Richmond, Shewmake said.
</P>
<P>
	   The family's court papers accuse Beth Israel of violating the law by
performing an autopsy on Lewis Bowman Jr.'s body without notifying the next of
kin.
</P>
<P>
	   The lawsuit, which names seven family members as plaintiffs, asks $3 million
in compensatory damages and $10 million in punitive damages for negligence and
for the unauthorized performance of an autopsy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-02-15-00 0142 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000215.0053 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-15 01:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mummy portraits at once Greek, Roman and Egyptian at New York's  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   NEW YORK (AP) - In an ancient and most cosmopolitan world, Egyptian,
Roman and Greek mingled in a rich cultural and artistic tapestry long overlooked
by Western scholars.
<P>
	   But this is changing with the opening today of "Ancient Faces: Mummy
Portraits of Roman Egypt," the first major U.S. exhibit devoted to the mummy art
of Roman Egypt, at the Metropolitan Museum of Art.
</P>
<P>
	   "What we want to show you is something perhaps a bit unusual. We show you
the meeting of two cultures: Greek culture, which then goes into the Roman, and
the ancient Egyptian culture," said Dorothea Arnold, co-curator of the show,
which covers the first through the third centuries A.D.
</P>
<P>
	   The mix produces faces that look almost modern European, but they were
painted to decorate caskets for mummies. In some cases, the figures wear Roman
dress but are set among ancient Egyptian gods.
</P>
<P>
	   "These paintings, which belong in this amazing time when the cultures blend,
have for a long time not really been recognized as the important art they are,"
Arnold said. "It was difficult to understand and people didn't put together the
different sides of this mixed multicultural society."
</P>
<P>
	   A single empire stretched from Aswan, Egypt, in the south, as far north as
Britain, and from Morocco east to Syria and the easternmost shores of the Black
Sea. In Egypt, it was a prosperous time when people of Greek origin adopted
Egyptian traditions, and many Egyptians adopted Greek and Roman ways.
</P>
<P>
	   "The Greek influence was really gaining ground ... especially artistically,
but the Pharaonic culture was there, and this was still Egypt," Arnold, the
museum's curator of Egyptian Art, said. "The ideas of the afterlife really
continued inside the new style, taken over from the Greek and Roman."
</P>
<P>
	   The unique art form of mummy portraiture flourished in Roman Egypt.
Stylistically related to Greco-Roman painting, it was created for a typically
Egyptian purpose: Inclusion in the funerary trappings of mummies.
</P>
<P>
	   The paintings, many on limewood or on linen shrouds, use both Egyptian and
Greco-Roman techniques - and often a combination of the two. And the strongly
naturalistic images show complexions ranging from dark with African features to
the palest of white, reflecting the melting pot that was the Egypt of that
period.
</P>
<P>
	   While the clothing, hair and jewelry imitate the fashions of imperial Rome,
the mummification and accompanying views of the afterlife are Egyptian - and
there are repeated references to Egyptian gods.
</P>
<P>
	   A sculpture of the falcon-headed god Horus, featuring an Egyptian-looking
face with a beak and Egyptian eyes, is dressed in Roman garb. Realistic
feathered-looking armor melds gently into the feathers of a surrealistic bird
head.
</P>
<P>
	   "At work people would speak in Greek, they would use Egyptian at home with
their families and if there was some sort of political event, the language would
be Latin," said Susan Walker, of the British Museum's Department of Greek and
Roman Antiquities, who edited the show's catalog.
</P>
<P>
	   The naturalism of the faces, in which personalities come through clearly,
combines eerily with the exhibit's daily household items - a toy horse, dice,
bright green-blue vases, simple wood furniture and paintings from homes, one
even in its original frame - to bring the period to life.
</P>
<P>
	   The show's works, which include 70 of the finest mummy portraits from
European and North American collections, will be on view through May 7. Because
many of the panels are so delicate, the show will not travel beyond New York.
</P>
<P>
	   But luckily for museum visitors, the exhibit is a taste of things to come.
It is the first step toward the opening in two years of a large new gallery at
the museum devoted exclusively to Roman Egypt.
</P>
<P>
	   "I hope we will be able to show the paintings as you see them now," Arnold
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-02-15-00 0147 </TRAILER>
