<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-15 02:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> High Stakes for McCain, Bush  </HEADLINE>
   By GLEN JOHNSON Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   COLUMBIA, S.C. (AP) -- The first face-to-face meeting since the New
Hampshire primary is also the last before South Carolina votes, and John McCain
and George W. Bush have different challenges in their debate tonight.
</P>
<P>
	   For McCain, it's to regain the high ground as a reformer after being pounded
on his record by Bush and running a negative ad against him.
</P>
<P>
	   For Bush, it's to maintain the pressure on McCain without appearing too
negative himself and alienating groups such as women and independents in
Saturday's vote.
</P>
<P>
	   Aides to the Texas governor said he planned to dig into McCain's record on
Social Security.
</P>
<P>
	   A new Los Angeles Times poll found the race between the two Republican
presidential contenders to be a statistical dead heat among likely voters. Bush
leads McCain by more than 2-to-1 among conservative Republicans, while McCain
leads Bush by the same margin among moderate independents and Democrats.
</P>
<P>
	   The 90-minute debate, sponsored by the South Carolina Business and Industry
Political Education Committee, also includes the third candidate left in the
race, radio talk show host Alan Keyes. It is being broadcast live on CNN with
Larry King as moderator.
</P>
<P>
	   South Carolina Attorney General Charlie Condon, a Bush backer, said despite
the stakes, he didn't expect the debate to change many minds -- unless one of
the candidates makes a major gaffe.
</P>
<P>
	   ``There was a lot of McCain mania after New Hampshire,'' Condon said.
``What's happened since then is people have done something I knew they would do:
They are looking at the people and the issues from what some call a Republican
point of view but what I call a conservative base.''
</P>
<P>
	   The Bush and McCain campaigns tried to strengthen weak spots Monday.
</P>
<P>
	   --Bush focused on education as an issue that could appeal to moderates,
particularly women. Advisers were fretting over internal polling indicating that
Bush's sharp attacks on McCain may be hurting him with women voters.
</P>
<P>
	   --McCain began rebroadcasting two TV commercials that tout his conservative
credentials, including one that notes his anti-abortion voting record and
efforts to take pornography off the Internet.
</P>
<P>
	   Last week he stopped showing an ad that challenged Bush's truthfulness after
it was panned by several top Republicans. The senator also said he would not use
negative ads for the rest of the primary battle.
</P>
<P>
	   Bush has criticized McCain for inconsistency on public financing of
congressional campaigns, which McCain says he opposes but has voted for as part
of reform packages.
</P>
<P>
	   McCain, who has been trying to brand Bush as a negative campaigner, said of
his opponent's criticism: ``This kind of savagery is not necessary in an
American political campaign.''
</P>
<P>
	   Asked about McCain's complaint during a news conference in Saluda, Bush
said: ``How can you call it savagery if the man made five votes, legitimate
votes on the floor of the Senate? It's not savagery; it's what we call full
exposure, full disclosure.''
</P>
<P>
	   Bush had his own complaints about McCain's campaigning, especially his
appeals to independents and even Democrats to vote in the open primary.
</P>
<P>
	   ``People are welcome to come into the party, that's fine with me,'' Bush
said. ``I just don't want Democrats coming in to vote against me because they
think my opponent will be easier to beat in November. We're trying to get rid of
the Clinton era, not reinforce it.''
</P>
<P>
	   McCain hopes a win Saturday will boost him into the Feb. 22 Arizona and
Michigan primaries, and then into the March 7 ``Super Tuesday'' contests.
</P>
<P>
	   On that day, voting in heavily populated states like California and New York
will award almost 60 percent of the total needed for the GOP nomination.
</P>
<P>
	   ``No matter what happens we're both going on to Michigan, Arizona and March
7,'' McCain said.
</P>
<P>
	   For Bush, South Carolina represents his line of defense, his ``firewall,''
to stop McCain's march. The governor has already won the Iowa caucuses and
Delaware primary; McCain routed him in New Hampshire.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-15-00 0205 </TRAILER>
