<HEADLINE> Anderson Files Lawsuit Against Iran  </HEADLINE>
   By TOM RAUM Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A federal judge is gathering evidence in a $100 million
lawsuit filed by former hostage Terry Anderson against the Iranian government.
Anderson's case is being heard as an effort builds in Congress to make it easier
for victims of state-sponsored terrorism to collect such judgments.
</P>
<P>
	   Anderson, former chief Middle East correspondent for The Associated Press
and the longest-held American hostage in Lebanon, accuses Iran of financing and
directing the Beirut terrorists who kept him shackled and blindfolded for nearly
seven years.
</P>
<P>
	   He will testify at a two-day hearing before U.S. District Judge Thomas
Penfield Jackson that begins today.
</P>
<P>
	   His captors were members of Hezbollah, or Party of God, ``a
politico-paramilitary terrorist organization operating in Lebanon'' sponsored
and directed by Iran, Anderson's lawsuit asserts.
</P>
<P>
	   It was filed last March under a 1996 law that allows claims by American
citizens and their families against assets of foreign countries that sponsor
terrorism -- if the actions resulted in personal injury or death.
</P>
<P>
	   So far, no money has been collected under that act. That's because the
Clinton administration, while initially supporting the law, has declined to help
successful U.S. plaintiffs collect.
</P>
<P>
	   Anderson hopes that may soon change.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The Clinton administration is supposed to assist in finding Iranian
assets,'' he said. ``In general, they've said they're willing to do this. But
there's still a ways to go.''
</P>
<P>
	   Anderson's case follows an August 1998 federal court order for Iran to pay
$65 million in damages to fellow American hostages David Jacobsen, Joseph
Cicippio and Frank Reed, and the wives of Cicippio and Reed.
</P>
<P>
	   So far, they have not collected a cent.
</P>
<P>
	   Others have also been frustrated under the 1996 law, including:
</P>
<P>
	   --The families of four men who were killed in 1996 when Cuban military jets
shot down two unarmed civilian planes.
</P>
<P>
	   --The family of Alisa Flatow, 20, of West Orange, N.J., a student at a
seminary in Jerusalem killed April 9, 1995 in an attack on a bus in the Gaza
Strip. Seven Israeli soldiers also died in the attack for which Islamic Jihad
claimed responsibility.
</P>
<P>
	   Two senators are pushing bipartisan legislation that would establish a
better mechanism for tapping into frozen assets to help satisfy such claims
while still seeking to meet the administration's principal objection: that
diplomatic properties -- such as former embassies -- not be among the assets
tapped.
</P>
<P>
	   The senators, Democrat Frank Lautenberg of New Jersey, and Republican Connie
Mack of Florida, also sponsored similar legislation last year but it was
withdrawn in last-minute budget pressures.
</P>
<P>
	   Now, sponsors say they are better organized and getting an earlier start.
``We have strong bipartisan support. We think we can move it,'' said Mack's
spokeswoman Nancy Segerdehal.
</P>
<P>
	   Anderson has been lending his support to the effort on behalf of the Beirut
hostages.
</P>
<P>
	   At the same time, Anderson has met Deputy Treasury Secretary Stuart
Eizenstat, who oversees compensation programs, in search of common ground.
</P>
<P>
	   Though the administration previously opposed the Lautenberg-Mack
legislation, Eizenstat seemed receptive to finding ``alternate ways'' to help
terrorism victims and their families, said Anderson's lawyer, Karen Hastie
Williams.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We're trying to see if there are frozen commercial assets that Iran has
that could be tapped for compensation,'' Williams said. Eizenstat declined
comment.
</P>
<P>
	   Anderson, his wife Madeleine Bassil, and their daughter Sulome Anderson were
to testify on how the hostage ordeal affected their lives.
</P>
<P>
	   To testify Wednesday on the role of overseas journalists are CBS Evening
News anchor Dan Rather and Gene Roberts, former managing editor of The New York
Times and chairman of the Committee to Protect Journalists.
</P>
<P>
	   Also, former diplomat Robert B. Oakley was to testify about the Iranian
government's support of Hezbollah and its role in the hostage crisis.
</P>
<P>
	   The United States froze Iranian assets valued at $12 billion in 1979. Most
of the funds, however, are controlled by the Iran-United States Claims Tribunal
in The Hague, Netherlands, which decides claims against both Iran and the United
States. The United States itself has jurisdiction over only a small fraction of
the assets, mostly real estate.
</P>
<P>
	   Anderson, now 52 and teaching journalism at Ohio University, was taken
captive in Beirut on March 16, 1985. Held longer than any other American in
Lebanon, he was freed 2,454 days later, on Dec. 4, 1991.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
