<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-15 02:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ABA OKs Political Contribution Rule  </HEADLINE>
   By RICHARD CARELLI Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   DALLAS (AP) -- The American Bar Association, spurred by a federal regulator,
has adopted an ethics rule forbidding lawyers from making political
contributions as a way to get government work.
</P>
<P>
	   Opponents said the new rule, targeting a practice known as ``pay to play,''
will chill free-speech rights and prove unenforceable. But Arthur Levitt,
chairman of the Securities and Exchange Commission, contended that investor
confidence was at stake.
</P>
<P>
	   ``By voting to end pay to play, America' lawyers today demonstrated bold and
inspired leadership on a pressing ethical issue,'' Levitt said Monday after the
ABA's policy-making House of Delegates voted 266-157 to adopt the model rule.
</P>
<P>
	   ``This vote reaffirms the belief that competence, not connections, should be
the rule when awarding government contracts,'' Levitt added, calling on state
bar associations to also approve the provision.
</P>
<P>
	   In the past, Levitt has warned against letting money managers make campaign
donations to state and local officials who oversee public employee pension funds
that hold more than $2 trillion in assets nationwide. Such funds should be
managed by those most qualified, and not those with the strongest political
ties, he has said.
</P>
<P>
	   The new ABA rule, which state regulators will be asked to adopt, does not
prohibit all political contributions by lawyers. It states: ``A lawyer or law
firm shall not accept a government legal engagement or an appointment by a judge
if the lawyer or law firm makes a political contribution or solicits political
contributions for the purpose of obtaining or being considered for that type of
legal engagement or appointment.''
</P>
<P>
	   Nashville lawyer Barbara Mayden, a prime supporter of the rule, said
government officials, including elected judges, have imposed ``a black eye on
the profession'' by requiring lawyers to make contributions ``just to get in the
ballgame'' and have a chance of securing government business.
</P>
<P>
	   It is short of bribery, she said, but unseemly nonetheless.
</P>
<P>
	   But Philadelphia lawyer Lawrence Fox called the rule ``bad public policy,''
and noted the ABA already had condemned pay to play.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The world will know that lawyers looked at this rule and saw it was deeply
flawed,'' he said. ``The chilling effect of this rule on lawyers will be
profound ... every time one considers making a political contribution.''
</P>
<P>
	   Buffalo, N.Y., lawyer Sharon Gerstman, another opponent, called the rule
``overbroad,'' and said it would call legitimate contributions into question.
</P>
<P>
	   The ABA's 530-member House of Delegates had rejected the same rule last
August, by a 164-146 vote.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-15-00 0242 </TRAILER>
