<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dr. Sam Sheppard's Trial Resumes  </HEADLINE>
   By JOHN AFFLECK Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   CLEVELAND (AP) -- The guilt or innocence of Dr. Sam Sheppard is once again
the subject of a courtroom drama.
</P>
<P>
	   But this time, Sheppard, whose case was the inspiration for television
series and movie ``The Fugitive,'' is not on trial.
</P>
<P>
	   Instead, his son, Sam Reese Sheppard, has sued the state of Ohio, alleging
his late father unjustly spent 10 years in prison before his conviction for the
beating death of his pregnant wife was overturned.
</P>
<P>
	   Opening statements and testimony began on Monday. The first witness was
famed defense attorney F. Lee Bailey, who recounted his efforts to clear the
doctor's name in the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
	   Marilyn Sheppard was killed on July 4, 1954, at the family home on Lake
Erie.
</P>
<P>
	   The doctor initially was convicted of murder. But the U.S. Supreme Court,
after hearing arguments from Bailey, overturned the verdict because of the
affects of pretrial publicity on jurors and witnesses.
</P>
<P>
	   Sheppard was acquitted at a retrial in 1966 and died four years later.
</P>
<P>
	   When he took Sheppard's case in 1961, Bailey said, he was angry about the
injustices done to the doctor and wanted to ``take a chip out of the seal of the
great state of Ohio.''
</P>
<P>
	   But Bailey, under cross-examination that is expected to continue today, also
said he disagrees with Sheppard's son about who the real killer is.
</P>
<P>
	   Sheppard attorney Terry Gilbert said in opening statements that recent DNA
will show that someone other than the Sheppards bled in the bedroom where she
was killed.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We are here to prove once and for all that Dr. Sheppard was innocent of
the murder of his wife,'' Gilbert said.
</P>
<P>
	   Gilbert also said he will try to show that Richard Eberling, a former window
washer for the Sheppards, is the most likely suspect. Eberling died in 1998
while serving a life sentence for another murder.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Sometimes things go very, very wrong and lives are ruined. When the state
makes a mistake it should be held accountable,'' Gilbert said.
</P>
<P>
	   County prosecutors, who are representing the state, said the Sheppards'
marriage was strained badly by the doctor's repeated and widely known
extramarital affairs. The weekend of her murder, Mrs. Sheppard was angry with
her husband because a house guest had been speaking openly about one of the
doctor's lovers, they said.
</P>
<P>
	   The prosecutors argued that the nature of Mrs. Sheppard's death -- she was
hit 27 times on the head and face with a blunt object -- indicate the actions of
someone in a rage, not a sexual assailant or a burglar.
</P>
<P>
	   Prosecutor William Mason made his point by pounding some rolled-up paper
into his hand and counting the blows up to 27.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We don't know what lit the match, but something caused the powder keg of
marital conflict to blow early on the morning of July 4,'' Mason said.
</P>
<P>
	   Gilbert said the Sheppards' marriage was basically happy and said the couple
was ``ecstatic'' over the Mrs. Sheppard's second pregnancy.
</P>
<P>
	   Bailey, the Sheppard team's opening witness, recounted how he took over the
doctor's case in 1961 and was able to establish that Sheppard's chances for a
fair trial were destroyed in 1954 by newspaper articles and broadcast reports
demanding his arrest and conviction.
</P>
<P>
	   Cross-examination from Assistant County Prosecutor Steve Dever focused on
Bailey's theory that the Sheppards' neighbors, Spencer and Esther Houk, were
responsible for Mrs. Sheppard's death.
</P>
<P>
	   Bailey suggested in 1966 that Mrs. Houk might have delivered the fatal blows
to Mrs. Sheppard after catching Houk having sex with her. Bailey said he knew of
Eberling but did not consider him a likely suspect.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I did not then, or at any time since, form a belief that Richard Eberling
killed Marilyn Sheppard,'' Bailey said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-15-00 0242 </TRAILER>
