<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sweeney Defends Gore Endorsement  </HEADLINE>
   By ALICE ANN LOVE Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW ORLEANS (AP) -- Brushing aside indications that Republican John McCain
has some backing within labor's rank-and-file, AFL-CIO President John Sweeney
has reasserted staunch support for Al Gore's Democratic presidential bid.
</P>
<P>
	   Speaking to reporters at the opening of this week's meeting of the AFL-CIO's
governing body, Sweeney said, ``We're confident that the endorsement was the way
that a significant majority of our members wanted to go.''
</P>
<P>
	   Not long before Sweeney's remarks, the head of the Service Employees
International Union had said enough of his union's members have been interested
in McCain that the union considered officially recommending him as an
alternative to the vice president for its Republican and independent members.
</P>
<P>
	   Andrew Stern, president of the SEIU, noted that the union ultimately did not
take that step and that it has endorsed only Gore. McCain did however, meet with
the union's members in New Hampshire, where he won the Republican presidential
primary last month.
</P>
<P>
	   ``And we'll still do that'' in other states, said Stern. ``Our members
aren't monolithic. They vote on both sides.''
</P>
<P>
	   Sweeney still hasn't brought two key affiliates into line behind the labor
federation's endorsement of Gore. The International Brotherhood of Teamsters and
the United Auto Workers have so far remained neutral.
</P>
<P>
	   They are expected to get on board eventually. But in the meantime, some of
their members have campaigned for Gore's challenger for the Democratic
nomination, former Sen. Bill Bradley of New Jersey, in the nation's earliest
primaries.
</P>
<P>
	   Sweeney disputed the existence of any significant labor movement support for
McCain -- something that McCain's Republican rival, Texas Gov. George W. Bush,
has alleged in recent days.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I think John McCain has been anti-worker, anti-working families' agenda,
throughout his whole career in the United States Senate,'' Sweeney said. As an
example, Sweeney said McCain has opposed increases in the minimum wage.
</P>
<P>
	   ``On the Democratic side, we have two good people. We think Al Gore is the
better of the two,'' said the AFL-CIO president. ``We believe that we're going
to be able to mobilize rank-and-file workers and activists across the country to
be engaged in their communities and their workplaces around the election of Al
Gore.''
</P>
<P>
	   The AFL-CIO council has scheduled a closed-door meeting with Gore on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
	   In addition to politics, the labor leaders who sit on the executive council
are devoting much of this week's discussions to organizing priorities for the
new year. This includes a campaign to unionize hospitality workers here, where
hotel profits swell around this time each year as Mardi Gras nears.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Hotel workers in New Orleans ... are at the heart of challenges facing
unions. While New Orleans hotels are among the most profitable in America, the
city's hospitality workers are among the worst paid in the nation,'' Sweeney
said.
</P>
<P>
	   AFL-CIO organizing director Kirk Adams said unions are trying to top last
year's net gain of 265,000 cardholders -- 600,000 total new members minus union
jobs lost and retirements.
</P>
<P>
	   That was a 20-year record, but Adams said it's not good enough if labor
wants to improve the proportion of union to nonunion workers. About 13.9 percent
of workers are unionized.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We need to do about a million a year to gain,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
	   In New Orleans, just one of the city's many hotels bustling with carnival
gawkers is unionized -- the Fairmont, where AFL-CIO leaders are meeting.
</P>
<P>
	   Tracy Lawson, earning $5.95 an hour as a room service waitress at the posh
Windsor Court a few blocks away, said of hotel visitors: ``They don't know
what's going on inside the building, how we are being mistreated.''
</P>
<P>
	   Elsewhere, ongoing union organizing battles include flight attendants at
Delta Air Lines, health care workers at Catholic hospitals in California and New
York, and construction workers who are more often working for temporary agencies
without benefits because of the recent building boom.
</P>
<P>
	   AFL-CIO treasurer Richard Trumka said the federation is also considering
ways of using the clout of union pension funds as major corporate stockholders
to influence contract talks and organizing drives at companies including Boeing,
Sprint and General Electric.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
