<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kurdish Rebel Leader Wages Struggle  </HEADLINE>
   By SELCAN HACAOGLU Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   ANKARA, Turkey (AP) -- During his first year in prison, Abdullah Ocalan
shaved his bushy Stalin-style mustache, lost nearly 40 pounds and worked to
reshape his guerrilla movement into a political force.
</P>
<P>
	   Ocalan, who was captured by Turkish commandos a year ago today, has changed
from the leader of a guerrilla movement that was facing defeat on the
battlefield into a significant political figure. Some say the rebel leader is
stronger in prison than he was as a free man.
</P>
<P>
	   From his prison cell on death row on Imrali Island, Ocalan sends messages to
his guerrillas through his lawyers, who also feed the rebel leader's statements
to the Turkish and international media. That spotlight is largely new for
Ocalan, who lived in obscurity in Syria before he was captured in Kenya.
</P>
<P>
	   Ocalan's fate -- he was sentenced to death for treason in June -- has become
a key issue in Turkey's relations with the European Union. The EU has demanded
that Turkey not hang Ocalan.
</P>
<P>
	   On the dusty streets of southeastern Turkey, Kurds who never agreed with
Ocalan's violent tactics now say they will never forgive Turkey if the rebel is
executed.
</P>
<P>
	   ``One year ago, he came as a murderer from Kenya,'' the Turkish magazine
Cuma said in the headline to a cover story. ``Now he is a'' political leader.
</P>
<P>
	   Turkey has said that it will never negotiate with Ocalan's Kurdistan Workers
Party, or PKK, dismissing the group as terrorists.
</P>
<P>
	   But Turkey does permit Ocalan's lawyers to release his statements, leading
many to speculate that Turkey is encouraging or at least not objecting to the
guerrilla leader's new conciliatory path.
</P>
<P>
	   Ocalan's transformation, they say, benefits Turkey.
</P>
<P>
	   Since arriving in prison, Ocalan shaved the bushy mustache that he and many
Turkish leftists wore as a badge of their identity. He shed 37 pounds and now
has the same menu as the elite commandos who guard him.
</P>
<P>
	   A month after shaving, a move that some say symbolized his changes, Ocalan
ordered his fighters to declare a unilateral cease-fire and retreat to bases in
Iraq and Iran. He also instructed a handful of rebels to surrender to Turkey, a
move he said demonstrated his sincerity toward peace.
</P>
<P>
	   Since those orders, the number of clashes between militants and rebels have
fallen to a trickle. In August, for example, rebel attacks were down 86 percent
from the same time a year earlier, the Turkish military said.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Ocalan has considerably increased his powers within the group despite
being in prison,'' said Nihat Ali Ozcan, an analyst with Ankara's Eurasia
Strategic Research Center. ``The PKK would not find its'' political path easily
without Ocalan.
</P>
<P>
	   The PKK re-elected Ocalan as its leader in its January meeting in the
mountains of Iran.
</P>
<P>
	   ``A life without our leader is not worth living,'' the group said in a
statement released to coincide with the anniversary of Ocalan's capture.
</P>
<P>
	   But there is dissent within the organization, and some Kurds in the
overwhelmingly Kurdish southeast consider Ocalan a traitor for retreating from
his demands for autonomy and insisting only on cultural rights.
</P>
<P>
	   Kurds are not recognized as a minority in Turkey, and it is illegal to
broadcast or teach in Kurdish. Ocalan's rebels have battled Turkish soldiers for
the past 15 years, a fight that has killed 37,000 people -- mostly Kurds.
</P>
<P>
	   There have been reports that some senior commanders have left the
organization, objecting to Ocalan's calls to lay down arms.
</P>
<P>
	   ``There is growing division and confusion within the group,'' said Michael
Radu of the Foreign Policy Research Institute in Philadelphia. ``There is still
a struggle for succession, and the number of defections are likely to
increase.''
</P>
<P>
	   Some say Ocalan is only making concessions to avoid the gallows.
</P>
<P>
	   ``They are concessions inextricably linked with'' his imprisonment, said
Philip Robins, a lecturer at Oxford University.
</P>
<P>
	   Ocalan's lawyers have appealed his sentence to the European Court of Human
Rights, a process that could take up to two years.
</P>
<P>
	   And Turkey has started talking tough, recently warning journalists that they
could face heavy fines or even prison sentences if they continue printing the
rebel leader's statements.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Ocalan's noose is in our hands,'' said Deputy Prime Minister Devlet
Bahceli, leader of the far-right Nationalist Movement Party.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-15-00 0245 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000215.0073 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-15 02:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Libertarian Seeks Presidency Again  </HEADLINE>
   By DOUGLAS KIKER Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Harry Browne is no fan of government. In fact, it would
be fair to say he even hates it. So what is an anti-government Libertarian to
do?
</P>
<P>
	   On Monday, Browne announced his second long-shot bid for the White House.
</P>
<P>
	   The 66-year-old former investment adviser from Franklin, Tenn., thinks
government has failed. He has proposed a 12-step program that would eliminate
income taxes, Social Security, the war on drugs, federal welfare and a lot of
other things Washington does.
</P>
<P>
	   Browne received less than 1 percent of the vote in the 1996 election, but
contends the climate is ripe for his message of a drastically scaled-back
government.
</P>
<P>
	   His transition from investment adviser to presidential candidate was an odd
one. Not only was he not politically active or connected -- he had not voted
since the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
	   But in 1992, watching Democrat Al Gore on TV, Browne found himself yelling
at the tube and his wife suggested he might make a good president. The idea
excited him, and two years later he sought the Libertarian Party's presidential
nomination.
</P>
<P>
	   ``When I dropped out (of politics) in the 1960s, you were hard-pressed to
ever find anybody who didn't think government could do anything it set out to
do,'' Browne said in an interview. ``If they said we are going to provide health
care for the elderly, then most people said, 'Well, we're going to have health
care for the elderly.'''
</P>
<P>
	   Today a candidate who doesn't talk about reforming Social Security and other
social programs is ``doomed,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
	   Browne finished fifth in 1996, behind Reform Party candidate Ross Perot and
the Green Party's Ralph Nader. This time, his campaign has about $1 million and
he won't take the federal matching funds for which he now qualifies.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I don't believe in government welfare for individuals, and I certainly
don't believe in it for politicians,'' said Browne.
</P>
<P>
	   He sees the Reform Party's infighting as a boost for Libertarians. The
Libertarian Party, he said, at least has a set of core principles all members
believe in.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The Reform Party is just an organization with a vague principle, a vague
objective, and the result is that it lends itself to anyone who can get hold of
the microphone,'' Browne said, referring to last weekend's contentious Reform
meeting and its leadership battle.
</P>
<P>
	   Libertarians meet in Anaheim, Calif., in early July to nominate their
candidate.
</P>
<P>
	   Browne is confident he will be able to rally the party, which includes about
30,000 dues-paying members. He has produced a 30-minute television show about
his candidacy to debut on a small national cable network, but is not unrealistic
about his prospects in November.
</P>
<P>
	   His goal is to win 5 percent of the vote.
</P>
<P>
	   ``It would lay the groundwork for somebody to run for president in 2004, and
maybe win the presidency,'' Browne said. ``And it would certainly lay the
groundwork to elect some Libertarian candidates to Congress in 2002.''
</P>
<P>
	   ------
</P>
<P>
	   EDITOR'S NOTE: Associated Press Writer Katherine Pfleger contributed to this
report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
