<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-15 02:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> McCain a 'Conservative Reformer'  </HEADLINE>
   By LAURA MECKLER Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Con-ser-va-tive (n): resistant to change.
</P>
<P>
	   Re-form (v): to make better by removing faults and defects.
</P>
<P>
	   The words convey very different concepts in the dictionary, but an ad now
airing by Republican presidential candidate John McCain pushes them together
twice in the space of 30 seconds.
</P>
<P>
	   The ad begins: ``John's McCain's agenda is a South Carolina agenda:
conservative reform for America.'' Near the end it concludes: ``Like Ronald
Reagan, John McCain is a conservative reformer.''
</P>
<P>
	   There's nothing particularly conservative about the reforms McCain is
pushing. But the idea is to take two popular concepts and put them together --
to straddle what can be opposing forces. It's a glance to the conservative, then
a wave to the reform.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The tension between conservative and reform is very real,'' said Wayne
Fields, who studies political rhetoric at Washington University in St. Louis.
``Just as the tension between conservative and compassion is real.''
</P>
<P>
	   He's referring, of course, to GOP presidential front-runner Gov. George W.
Bush, who bills himself a ``compassionate conservative,'' telegraphing concern
for the poor and downtrodden while holding onto the conservative mantle. No
matter that in Reagan's heyday, conservative meant undoing the liberal reforms
intended to help the same poor and the downtrodden.
</P>
<P>
	   Now, for good measure, Bush has added ``reformer with results'' to his
sloganeering.
</P>
<P>
	   But how does one proclaim himself both conservative and reformer, all in one
breath?
</P>
<P>
	   Today's use of ``conservative'' is more likely to invoke notions of family
values than anything else, Fields said. The idea is to return to a time before
the wrong sort of change came along.
</P>
<P>
	   ``A conservative doesn't have to leave everything the same,'' said Henry
Graff of Columbia University. ``To save the system you reform it.''
</P>
<P>
	   That's what Reagan -- the ultimate modern conservative -- did. More than
anything, Fields said, he undid the Great Society doings of Lyndon B. Johnson
and his like-minded successors. ``Reagan was trying to undo a liberal
revolution.''
</P>
<P>
	   As for the McCain campaign, spokesman Howard Opinsky says it makes perfect
sense.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I think that South Carolinians and most Americans want a conservative
governing philosophy, coupled with an active reform agenda, that will move us
toward our conservative philosophy,'' he said. ``It may not be in the dictionary
... but that's what John McCain wants.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-15-00 0252 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000215.0078 </DOCNO>
