<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dollar Higher, Tokyo Stocks Lower  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    TOKYO (AP) -- The U.S. dollar was higher against the yen Tuesday afternoon
on purchases by Japanese banks and U.S. funds. The Tokyo stock market's main
index closed lower.
</P>
<P>
	   The dollar bought 108.72 yen at 3 p.m. (0600 GMT), up 0.40 yen from late
Monday in Tokyo but slightly lower than its late New York level of 108.83 yen
overnight.
</P>
<P>
	   The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average lost 188.63 points, or 0.96
percent, to finish the day at 19,367.83. On Monday, the average closed down
153.56 points, or 0.78 percent.
</P>
<P>
	   In currency dealings, the dollar retained most of its strength against the
yen as Japanese bank dealers and some U.S. funds covered their short, or
oversold positions.
</P>
<P>
	   In other currencies, the euro was traded at 106.64 yen, down from 107.04 yen
late Monday in Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
	   On the stock market, share prices fell as companies sold cross-shares, or
shares they hold in other companies to cement business relations.
</P>
<P>
	   Prices had started higher on buying of high technology issues in line with
gains in their U.S. counterparts in New York overnight.
</P>
<P>
	   On Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial average rose 94.63 points, or 0.9
percent, to close at 10,519.84 on Monday.
</P>
<P>
	   In Tokyo, bank stocks were among the biggest losers following media reports
that the Tokyo Metropolitan government would go ahead with a controversial tax
on major Tokyo-based banks.
</P>
<P>
	   The 5-year plan, proposed by Tokyo Gov. Shintaro Ishihara, calls for a 3
percent tax imposed on the gross operating profits of banks with deposits and
equivalent funds of 5 trillion yen (dlrs 47.17 billion) or more, starting in
April.
</P>
<P>
	   Ishihara, who wants to improve Tokyo's revenue shortfall, was to present a
bill to parties in the city assembly Wednesday, with approval expected by late
March, the national Asahi newspaper reported.
</P>
<P>
	   The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the first
section fell 27.27 points, or 1.59 percent, to 1,690.14. The TOPIX closed down
12.06 points, or 0.70 percent, the day before.
</P>
<P>
	   An estimated 815.47 million shares changed hands on the First Section of the
Tokyo Stock Exchange, up from 778.75 million shares on Monday.
</P>
<P>
	   Decliners overwhelmed advancers 923 to 315, while 118 issues closed
unchanged.
</P>
<P>
	   The yield on the benchmark 10-year Japanese government bond fell to 1.8000
percent from Monday's finish of 1.8300 percent. Its price rose 0.25 point to
99.14
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
