<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-15 03:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> State's tourism dollars up 50 percent in 1999  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) - Tourists poured a record $100 million into
Connecticut attractions and related businesses in 1999, an increase of 46
percent from the year before, a new study shows.
<P>
	   The state tourism office of the Department of Economic and Community
Development attributes the increase to a 7-year marketing campaign aimed at
greater metropolitan New York.
</P>
<P>
	   Tourists spent $66 million in Connecticut in 1998.
</P>
<P>
	   The new study showed that travelers to Connecticut last year spent $136
apiece on lodging, up 24 percent over 1998. They also shelled out $136 in
restaurants, an increase of 6.5 percent. And they spent about $142 on shopping
trips around the state, almost 50 percent more than in 1998.
</P>
<P>
	   The number of people who called the state tourism office's information
number, 1-800-CT-BOUND, rose 24 percent to 286,471.
</P>
<P>
	   Of the people that called, almost 58 percent visited the state - a rate that
matched a record set in 1998.
</P>
<P>
	   The study was conducted through a telephone poll of 700 people from metro
New York who had called the state tourism office.
</P>
<P>
	   In 1993, the state tourism office launched an intensive marketing campaign
aimed at greater metro New York that includes TV spots, newspaper inserts and
magazine ads. Of a $5 million annual budget, the office spends a little over $2
million on ads.
</P>
<P>
	   Mystic continues to be the number one destination for travelers from New
York. Ninety percent of New York travelers were repeat visitors.
</P>
<P>
	   The study showed that visitors were pleased with their Connecticut
vacations. Some 88 percent of travelers to the state said they plan to come back
within the next two years.
</P>
<P>
	   The study also showed that more than half, or some 58 percent, of all
visitors are couples, while a third said they come with children.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
