<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Car Booster Seats Urged for Kids  </HEADLINE>
   By CATHERINE STRONG Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The government is launching a campaign to encourage the
use of booster seats for youngsters who have outgrown child safety seats but
aren't big enough to rely solely on adult restraints.
</P>
<P>
	   Kids can't fit safely into adult belts when they weigh 40 to 80 pounds and
are about 4 to 8 years old, officials say. But less than 5 percent of those
children use booster seats, according to an ongoing study of more than 20,000
children by the University of Pennsylvania, Children's Hospital of Philadelphia
and State Farm Insurance.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Booster seats, properly used, can help prevent injury to older children by
making adult-sized seat belts fit effectively,'' Transportation Secretary Rodney
Slater said in announcing a campaign that includes distribution of 50,000
brochures and $7.5 million in grant money to states to promote child passenger
safety.
</P>
<P>
	   Studies show about 70 percent of children 3 and younger are properly
restrained but that number drops to as low as 20 percent for children 4 to 9,
the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration said.
</P>
<P>
	   Booster seats allow children who have outgrown child seats to properly
position lap belts around their hips and shoulder belts across their chests.
</P>
<P>
	   Without the seats, the shoulder belts can tangle around a child's neck and
the lap portion of the belt rides up over the abdomen. That lap belt position
places children at risk of liver, spleen, intestinal and spinal cord injuries
during a crash.
</P>
<P>
	   In 1998, 495 children 5 to 9 were killed and 86,000 were injured in crashes.
</P>
<P>
	   Meanwhile, Ford Motor Co. announced Monday it would provide free dealer
installation of tether strap anchors in all its vehicles from 1989 through 2000
models. The strap, already required in Canada, more securely fastens the top of
child seats to give children better protection from forward head movement in
crashes.
</P>
<P>
	   The federal government is requiring top tether anchors in all vehicles
beginning with the 2001 model year. The strap usually is connected to the back
of a vehicle's package shelf.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-15-00 0305 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000215.0084 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-15 03:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> SBC Application Denial Sought  </HEADLINE>
   By KALPANA SRINIVASAN Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A bid by SBC Communications to provide long-distance
service to its local customers is facing a stumbling block.
</P>
<P>
	   On Monday, the Justice Department recommended that the Federal
Communications Commission reject SBC's application to get into the long-distance
business in Texas.
</P>
<P>
	   The regional Bell company failed to show it was providing equal access to
competing companies seeking to lease its local phone lines, the department said.
</P>
<P>
	   A 1996 law mandated that before a Bell company can offer long-distance
within its service area, it first must show in detail that it has opened its
local monopoly to give rivals a chance to compete. Bell Atlantic convinced
regulators it had done so in New York, and in December it became the first Bell
company to offer long distance service to its local customers.
</P>
<P>
	   San Antonio-based SBC filed an application with the FCC in January arguing
that its Texas market also is fully open to competition.
</P>
<P>
	   But Justice Department officials said the company had not demonstrated it
was giving the required access to competitors seeking to lease lines so they
could offer high-speed Internet and phone services.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Nondiscriminatory access is required for us to find that the market is
open to competition,'' said Joel Klein, in charge of the department's antitrust
division.
</P>
<P>
	   Although the FCC has the final say, it must give substantial weight to the
assessment provided by the Justice Department.
</P>
<P>
	   The FCC previously turned down requests by SBC to provide long-distance
service in Oklahoma and by Ameritech Corp., now owned by SBC, to provide
long-distance service in Michigan.
</P>
<P>
	   The Justice Department's new evaluation comes despite a glowing endorsement
from the Public Utility Commission in Texas, which lent its unanimous support to
the application late last month. The FCC must take that evaluation by state
regulators into account as well before issuing its final decision no later than
the second week of April.
</P>
<P>
	   SBC said Monday it was confident the FCC would eventually approve the
application. The company has already created a separate subsidiary to handle its
high-speed Internet service, ensuring nondiscriminatory access for rivals, SBC
said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
	   The Justice Department also cited a precedent established when Bell
Atlantic's New York long-distance application was approved. The department said
SBC's performance in providing rivals with pieces of its network was below the
level the FCC described as ``minimally acceptable'' when it gave Bell Atlantic
the go-ahead.
</P>
<P>
	   SBC responded that its performance for moving local customers to competitors
without an interruption of phone service meets or exceeds the standards set by
Bell Atlantic when it received FCC approval.
</P>
<P>
	   Bell Atlantic did not receive a full-force endorsement from the Justice
Department, either, but ultimately the FCC gave it approval in late December to
offer long-distance in New York.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-15-00 0305 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000215.0086 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-15 06:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Officer claims he thought Diallo wore bulletproof vest  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - Inside Amadou Diallo's vestibule, there was a din
"like cannon shots." There were flashes. And wood splintering. Chaos.
<P>
	   The description by one of the four officers accused of murdering Diallo with
a barrage of 41 bullets also includes a scary sight: Diallo standing up to the
gunfire and holding a black object that appeared to be a gun.
</P>
<P>
	   Defendant Sean Carroll testified at the officers' trial Monday that he was
sure the West African immigrant was "wearing a bulletproof vest and the only way
to take him out was to shoot at his legs."
</P>
<P>
	   But when Diallo fell, Carroll said, he was shocked to look down and discover
the black object "was just a wallet. ... I said, 'Where's the (expletive) gun?"'
</P>
<P>
	   Carroll, 36 - at times sobbing - and Officer Edward McMellon, 27 - in
monotone - became the first of the four defendants to give public accounts of
how they shot Diallo while patrolling his block at 12:40 a.m. on Feb. 4, 1999.
Officers Kenneth Boss, 28, and Richard Murphy, 27, were expected to take the
stand as early as today.
</P>
<P>
	   "Don't die! Don't die!" Carroll said he yelled as Diallo lay bleeding in the
vestibule. "Keep breathing!"
</P>
<P>
	   The defendants have pleaded innocent to second-degree murder. If convicted,
they face a maximum sentence of 25 years to life in prison.
</P>
<P>
	   On Monday, Carroll and McMellon both told jurors they had experience
identifying dangerous street criminals and were trained to quickly move in - or
"close the gap" - to disarm them. Both testified they had been involved in
non-fatal shootings that were deemed justified.
</P>
<P>
	   On the morning Diallo died, the four plainclothes officers were cruising in
an unmarked car. Carroll said he became suspicious as they drove past Diallo's
apartment building and saw him on the front doorsteps "looking up and down the
block, peeking his head out ... like he didn't want to be seen."
</P>
<P>
	   Carroll claimed Diallo, 22, a street vendor, fit the description of a wanted
rapist. He also said he suspected that Diallo might be committing a robbery.
</P>
<P>
	   As the officers got out of the car, McMellon testified, he held out his
badge and said, "Police department. ... Can we have a word with you?" Instead of
stopping, Diallo retreated to the rear of a vestibule and started digging in his
right pocket, both officers testified.
</P>
<P>
	   The defendants described rushing Diallo, ordering him to "Stop!" and "Show
your hands!"
</P>
<P>
	   "We said it clear," Carroll said. "He just didn't want to listen."
</P>
<P>
	   The officers said Diallo turned toward them and began pulling out a square
black object that looked like the top of a semi-automatic pistol.
</P>
<P>
	   "My prior arrests dictated to me that this person was pulling a gun,"
Carroll said. "I just said, 'Gun. He's got a gun."'
</P>
<P>
	   Said McMellon: "I screamed 'What are you doing?' (at Diallo) ... I didn't
want to die."
</P>
<P>
	   Both officers said they had one foot in the 5-foot-by-7-foot vestibule when
they fired the first shots. As they retreated, McMellon fell down a stoop and
unto his back but kept firing.
</P>
<P>
	   Carroll and McMellon repeated defense claims that they fired all 16 shots
from their rapid-fire pistols because Diallo did not immediately go down.
Carroll denied he shot Diallo while he was flat on his back, despite evidence
that one of his bullets tunneled up the victim's leg.
</P>
<P>
	   On cross-examination, both officers said they didn't know which one of them
fired the first shot. Prosecutor Donald Levin demanded Carroll explain what was
so suspicious about a man standing on his front stoop.
</P>
<P>
	   "Looking up and down the block is not a crime, is it officer?" Levin asked.
</P>
<P>
	   "No, it is not," Carroll responded.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-02-15-00 0648 </TRAILER>
