<DOCNO> APW20000215.0091 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-15 09:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Backs Social Security Bill  </HEADLINE>
   By ANNE GEARAN Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton shifted course on Social Security
reform, promising to sign a separate Republican bill to do away with an earnings
limit affecting hundreds of thousands of older Americans.
</P>
<P>
	   ``It's the right thing to do,'' Clinton said Monday. ``Let's just do it.''
</P>
<P>
	   Clinton's support gives powerful momentum to an election-year drive to
eliminate the earnings penalty, which takes $1 in Social Security benefits from
Americans 65 through 69 for every $3 they earn over a prescribed limit,
currently $17,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
	   House Republicans already were introducing a repeal bill and promised to put
it on a fast track for a vote, likely in March.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I'm thrilled by this. I hope this is just the beginning of a signal from
them that they're willing to work on this whole Social Security area,'' Clinton
said during an interview with CNN.com.
</P>
<P>
	   More than 10,000 people took part in the 25-minute online ``chat'' with
Clinton, said CNN spokesman Paul Schur. He said one of them slipped past CNN's
filtering system and wrote -- under Clinton's name -- that he would like to see
more pornography on the Internet. Schur said he did not know how the impostor
eluded the filter but that the computer system was not hacked.
</P>
<P>
	   The president has advocated eliminating the earnings limit before, but only
as part of a comprehensive plan dealing with the threat of Social Security
insolvency as the baby boom generation retires.
</P>
<P>
	   Removing the Social Security earnings limit is an issue dear to the hearts
of older Americans, an important voting bloc for Democrats and Republicans in
their struggle for control of the White House and Congress.
</P>
<P>
	   More than 800,000 seniors lose part or all of their benefits because of the
earnings limit, according to Social Security Administration estimates. The
earnings ceiling will increase to $30,000 by 2002 under current law.
</P>
<P>
	   Repealing the earnings test would cost roughly $22.7 billion over 10 years,
according to GOP estimates.
</P>
<P>
	   On other subjects, Clinton said:
</P>
<P>
	   --He thinks ``the United States can do business'' with acting Russian
President Vladimir Putin.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We don't agree with him on everything, but what I have seen of him so far
indicates to me that he's capable of being a very strong and effective and
straightforward leader,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
	   --The United States has to strike ``a delicate balance'' in dealing with
Austria, voicing disapproval of Joerg Haider's far-right Freedom Party without
doing ``anything that builds his support even further.''
</P>
<P>
	   ``But I think it ought to be clear to every Austrian citizen that we in the
United States do not approve of his political program or his excessive
rhetoric,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
	   --He is optimistic about reviving peace talks in the Middle East. He
acknowledged, however, that ``we're in a little tough patch right now'' with a
freeze in talks between Israel and Syria, a missed deadline for an
Israeli-Palestinian peace framework and fresh violence in Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We're down to the hard decisions,'' the president said. He added: ``We're
so close on the substance that I am optimistic.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-15-00 0951 </TRAILER>
