<HEADLINE> Dow Up 34.83; Nasdaq Down 47.75  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks were narrowly mixed at the start of trading today as
technology shares slumped and investors found little reason to explore other
sectors of the market.
</P>
<P>
	   In the first hour of trading on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial
average was up 34.83 at 10,554.67.
</P>
<P>
	   Broader stock indicators were lower. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was
down 4.28 at 1,385.66, and the Nasdaq composite index was down 47.75 at
4,370.80.
</P>
<P>
	   The Dow's gains came largely from Exxon Mobil, which rose 3 to 79 7/16 as
the price of crude oil rose in London trading. Crude prices topped $30 a barrel
Monday for the first time since the eve of the Persian Gulf War in Jan. 1991.
</P>
<P>
	   Texaco rose 1 5/16 to 50 3/16 on the New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
	   While rising prices are good for the companies that produce and explore for
oil, they can contribute to inflation. That possibility helped keep investors
out of the broader market today.
</P>
<P>
	   Investors are worried that the Federal Reserve will continue raising
interest rates this year as it works to keep inflation from accelerating. The
Fed has raised rates four times since last June, and has seen little sign that
the economy's growth has slowed.
</P>
<P>
	   Because higher interest rates can cut into corporate profits, investors have
been favoring stocks of companies whose profits are growing rapidly -- namely,
technology stocks. But some of those favorites were lower today as investors
sold shares to lock in profits.
</P>
<P>
	   Intel fell 1 to 108 7/8, and Cisco Systems fell 2 5/8 to 127 7/8.
</P>
<P>
	   Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a slim margin on the New York
Stock Exchange, where volume came to 135.15 million shares, ahead of Monday's
early pace.
</P>
<P>
	   The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies fell 1.98 to 537.96.
</P>
<P>
	   Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average fell 1.0 percent. In afternoon
trading, Germany's DAX index was down 0.4 percent, Britain's FT-SE 100 was up
0.2 percent, and France's CAC-40 was down 1.4 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
