<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-15 10:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Third officer testifies at Diallo trial  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - A third police officer charged in the Diallo
shooting testified today he was certain his partner had been shot when he got
out of his unmarked patrol car.
<P>
	   "Ed was shot. That's all I could see," testified Officer Kenneth Boss as he
recounted seeing Officer Ed McMellon on the ground outside the building where
they encountered Amadou Diallo.
</P>
<P>
	   Boss said he saw Diallo in the rear of the vestibule. "I see a gun and I
say, 'My God, I'm gonna die,"' Boss recalled. "I fired my weapon."
</P>
<P>
	   The object Diallo was holding - which the officers believed was a gun -
turned out to be a wallet.
</P>
<P>
	   When the gunfire ended, Boss ran over to McMellon. "I grabbed him and I
started feeling his chest going, 'Where are you hit, where are you hit?' ... He
said, 'I'm not hit."' McMellon was lying on his back after falling down the
stoop.
</P>
<P>
	   Boss, 28, then went into the vestibule and saw Diallo lying there. "Where
there should have been a gun, there was a wallet," he said.
</P>
<P>
	   Boss then went back to the car and called for an ambulance and police
supervisor.
</P>
<P>
	   Asked how he felt as he made the call, he said: "I was distraught."
</P>
<P>
	   Prosecutor Donald Levin asked Boss whether he had considered the possibility
that the West African immigrant didn't speak English or was emotionally
disturbed or even frightened of the plainsclothes officers.
</P>
<P>
	   "At the time what went through my mind was that we had a fleeing suspect,"
Boss responded. "It didn't occur to me if he spoke English or not, or whether he
was running because he was trying to get away from police or whether he was
afraid of the police."
</P>
<P>
	   Boss' unemotional testimony was similar to that given Monday by Officer Sean
Carroll, who was the first of the four cops to testify at their trial. Carroll
told jurors that he was certain Diallo was "wearing a bulletproof vest and the
only way to take him out was to shoot at his legs."
</P>
<P>
	   But when Diallo fell, Carroll said, he was shocked to look down and discover
the black object "was just a wallet. ... I said, 'Where's the (expletive) gun?"'
</P>
<P>
	   Carroll, 36 - at times sobbing - and Officer Edward McMellon, 27 - in
monotone - became the first of the four defendants to give public accounts of
how they shot Diallo while patrolling his block at 12:40 a.m. on Feb. 4, 1999.
Officer Richard Murphy, 27, also was expected to testify at the trial.
</P>
<P>
	   "Don't die! Don't die!" Carroll said he yelled as Diallo lay bleeding in the
vestibule. "Keep breathing!"
</P>
<P>
	   The defendants have pleaded innocent to second-degree murder. If convicted,
they face a maximum sentence of 25 years to life in prison.
</P>
<P>
	   On Monday, Carroll and McMellon both told jurors they had experience
identifying dangerous street criminals and were trained to quickly move in - or
"close the gap" - to disarm them. Both testified they had been involved in
non-fatal shootings that were deemed justified.
</P>
<P>
	   On the morning Diallo died, the four plainclothes officers were cruising in
an unmarked car. Carroll said he became suspicious as they drove past Diallo's
apartment building and saw him on the front doorsteps "looking up and down the
block, peeking his head out ... like he didn't want to be seen."
</P>
<P>
	   Carroll claimed Diallo, 22, a street vendor, fit the general description of
a wanted rapist. He also said he suspected that Diallo might be committing a
robbery.
</P>
<P>
	   As the officers got out of the car, McMellon testified, he held out his
badge and said, "Police department. ... Can we have a word with you?" Instead of
stopping, Diallo retreated to the rear of a vestibule and started digging in his
right pocket, both officers testified.
</P>
<P>
	   The defendants described rushing Diallo, ordering him to "Stop!" and "Show
your hands!"
</P>
<P>
	   "We said it clear," Carroll said. "He just didn't want to listen."
</P>
<P>
	   The officers said Diallo turned toward them and began pulling out a square
black object that looked like the top of a semi-automatic pistol.
</P>
<P>
	   "My prior arrests dictated to me that this person was pulling a gun,"
Carroll said. "I just said, 'Gun. He's got a gun."'
</P>
<P>
	   Said McMellon: "I screamed (at Diallo) 'What are you doing?' ... I didn't
want to die."
</P>
<P>
	   Both officers said they had one foot in the 5-foot-by-7-foot vestibule when
they fired the first shots. As they retreated, McMellon fell down the stoop and
onto his back but kept firing.
</P>
<P>
	   Carroll and McMellon repeated defense claims that they fired all 16 shots
from their rapid-fire pistols because Diallo did not immediately go down.
Carroll denied he shot Diallo while he was flat on his back, despite evidence
that one of his bullets tunneled up the victim's leg.
</P>
<P>
	   On cross-examination, both officers said they didn't know which one of them
fired the first shot. Prosecutor Donald Levin demanded Carroll explain what was
so suspicious about a man standing on his front stoop.
</P>
<P>
	   "Looking up and down the block is not a crime, is it officer?" Levin asked.
</P>
<P>
	   "No, it is not," Carroll responded.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
