<HEADLINE> Study: China Deal Can Boost Exports  </HEADLINE>
   By MARTIN CRUTSINGER AP Economics Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The November trade agreement the Clinton administration
reached with China appears to have achieved America's major negotiating
objectives and should offer significant opportunities for U.S. farmers and
manufacturers, a congressional study said today.
</P>
<P>
	   The nonpartisan Congressional Research Service said ``most of the
commitments China reportedly made in April 1999 appear to have been included in
the November 1999 agreement.'' U.S. negotiators won significant additional trade
concessions in such areas as banking, securities, films and music, the study
said.
</P>
<P>
	   ``If and when fully implemented, China's WTO (World Trade Organization)
commitments could result in substantial new opportunities for U.S. exports to
and investment in China,'' the CRS study concluded.
</P>
<P>
	   It did not put a specific figure on the gains but cited a forecast made by
Agriculture Secretary Dan Glickman that U.S. farm exports could be increased by
$2 billion annually once the Chinese start removing barriers cited in the
agreement.
</P>
<P>
	   U.S. agriculture exports to China totaled $1 billion last year, making China
the eighth-largest market for American farm products. Farm groups are expected
to be one of the major groups working to win passage of legislation that would
give China permanent normal trading status with the United States.
</P>
<P>
	   Republican leaders released the new study as they sought to rally support
for the China legislation. Congress must eliminate the annual review of China's
trading status before U.S. exporters get the benefits of reduced trade barriers
that China has agreed to make in order to gain membership in the WTO.
</P>
<P>
	   ``This study is further proof that continued trade with China will help
farmers and workers here at home through more jobs and better-paying jobs,''
Rep. Bill Archer, R-Texas, chairman of the House Ways and Means Committee, said
in a statement.
</P>
<P>
	   ``American farmers and workers have so much to gain from normal trade with
China,'' said Rep. Phil Crane, R-Ill. ``Admitting China to the international
trading community will force them to play by the rules of free and fair trade.''
</P>
<P>
	   U.S. Trade Representative Charlene Barshefsky finally reached agreement on a
market-opening trade package with China last November after President Clinton
rejected similar offers made by Chinese Premier Zhu Rongji during his visit to
the United States in April.
</P>
<P>
	   The Clinton administration has tapped Commerce Secretary William Daley to
head up its lobbying efforts on the China issue but administration officials
conceded they have a tough fight, given that organized labor and many Democrats
in the House are opposed.
</P>
<P>
	   The White House is pushing for a vote on the measure before midsummer in
order to keep the debate from spilling over into the fall congressional
elections.
</P>
<P>
	   Those opposed ending the annual review of China's trading status argue that
it will give the United States less leverage to win improvements in China's
performance on human rights and other nontrade issues.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-15-00 1241 </TRAILER>
