<HEADLINE> Big Movers in the Stock Market  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks that are moving substantially or trading heavily
today on the New York Stock Exchange and Nasdaq Stock Market.
</P>
<P>
	   Paine Webber raised its rating on the stock, saying that recent rumors about
Warren Buffett's health were false and that growth prospects remain strong. On
Monday, Berkshire revealed holdings in Citigroup, Liz Claiborne and Dun &AMP;
Bradstreet.
</P>
<P>
	   Lehman Brothers raised its rating on the stock to "buy" from "neutral,"
saying the share price should hit 65 within 12 months. Texaco also benefited
from the rise in crude oil prices, which are now above $30 a barrel for the
first time since Jan. 1991.
</P>
<P>
	   The company said it expects a decline in earnings for the first half of
2000, with a "significant" decline in the first quarter. West cited weakness in
its contract services segment, which has been under review.
</P>
<P>
	   Goldman Sachs raised its rating on the stock to "trading buy" from "market
outperform." On Monday, the company, a provider of health care services, posted
fourth quarter operating profits of $1.20 per share, 7 cents above views.
</P>
<P>
	   Shares rose on the expectation that Intel will continue using Rambus
technology in manufacturing high-speed computer chips. A year ago, Intel was
forced to delay release of a chipset using Rambus' memory technology because it
discovered glitches in the product.
</P>
<P>
	   The company entered into a two-year alliance with America Online Inc.'s
European unit. The agreement makes EBookers, a European travel Web site, a
"primary and preferred" partner on AOL and CompuServe Web sites.
</P>
<P>
	   The company said it expects earnings to slip in its current fourth quarter,
which ends March 31. Digitial Video cited higher expenditures on staff for its
growing China operations and seasonal factors.
</P>
<P>
	   J.P. Morgan initiated coverage of the stock with a "buy" rating. The company
develops testing, management and development software.
</P>
