<HEADLINE> States' Health Care Varies Widely  </HEADLINE>
   By KAREN GULLO Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Access to health insurance, Medicaid payments and health
care costs vary widely from state to state, says a new report that suggests
where people live might affect their longevity, especially for low-income
Americans.
</P>
<P>
	   Poor people in Arizona, Texas and New Mexico are more likely to lack health
insurance than low-income people in Connecticut and Wisconsin, according to a
state-by-state analysis by AARP, the nation's largest organization of older
adults.
</P>
<P>
	   One-quarter of Arizona residents didn't see a doctor because of costs,
compared to just 6 percent of people in Wisconsin who didn't go to the doctor
for the same reason, said the AARP report, released today.
</P>
<P>
	   Health coverage costs vary widely. Workers in Florida fork out over $2,000
for family health coverage, while employees in Michigan pay just $757.
</P>
<P>
	   Even in Medicaid, a nationwide health program for low-income Americans,
coverage and payments vary widely state by state. In the District of Columbia,
61 percent of people at or below the poverty level are on Medicaid and recieve
an average of $7,548. Medicaid reaches only 29 percent of poor people in South
Dakota, where payments average $3,737, the report showed.
</P>
<P>
	   While many factors affect health care, including economic conditions, the
scope of health plan benefits and income levels, AARP officials said that the
report highlights the fact that people in some states, especially those with low
incomes, face more obstacles to health care than people in other states.
</P>
<P>
	   ``There's a lot of cause for concern in the data that we present,'' said
John Rother, AARP director of legislation and public policy. ``Where you live
might affect how many years you have left.''
</P>
<P>
	   The group used recent data from federal, state and private sources to come
up with 95 key health indicators for states. Other findings included:
</P>
<P>
	   --Mississippi had the highest heart disease rate, with 188 deaths per 1,000
people, and Minnesota had the lowest, with 93 deaths per 1,000.
</P>
<P>
	   --Washington, D.C., had the highest cancer rate, with 155.8 deaths per 1,000
people, and Utah had the lowest, with 84.9 cancer deaths per 1,000.
</P>
<P>
	   --Alaska had the highest nursing home costs, with a median cost per day of
$212.94. Oklahoma ranked among the lowest in nursing home costs, with a median
daily rate of $47.58.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
