<BODY>
<HEADLINE> House Votes To Honor NYC Cardinal  </HEADLINE>
   By SHANNON McCAFFREY Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The House voted today to award an ailing Cardinal John
O'Connor the Congressional Gold Medal, the body's highest civilian honor.
</P>
<P>
	   O'Connor, the longtime spiritual leader of New York City's 2.3 million Roman
Catholics, recently turned 80 and had surgery last fall to remove a brain tumor.
He is expected to retire as soon as Pope John Paul II appoints a replacement.
</P>
<P>
	   The House voted 413-1 to give the award to O'Connor. Rep. Ron Paul, R-Texas,
was the lone opponent. The Senate is expected to approve the honor next month.
</P>
<P>
	   Before today's vote, lawmakers extolled O'Connor's work on behalf of the
needy, children, AIDS victims and others. They also spoke of his leadership in
establishing diplomatic ties between the Vatican and Israel.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Cardinal O'Connor has spent a lifetime using one simple tool -- love. Love
for his country, his church and his fellow human beings,'' said Rep. Vito
Fossella, R-N.Y., who first nominated O'Connor for the medal.
</P>
<P>
	   O'Connor, the oldest active U.S. bishop in the United States, is a close
ally of the pope. The cardinal has drawn criticism over the years for denouncing
homosexuality, premarital sex and birth control.
</P>
<P>
	   O'Connor served in the Navy for 27 years and saw combat in Korea. He was a
career military chaplain before being named bishop in Scranton, Pa. He has led
the Archdiocese of New York since 1984.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
