<HEADLINE> Spotlight on Fertility Fraud Trial  </HEADLINE>
    By LARRY NEUMEISTER Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) -- Infertile couples and doctors across the country are
closely watching the federal trial of a Park Avenue specialist accused of
tricking insurance companies into paying for fertility treatments most are loath
to cover.
</P>
<P>
	   Some experts say that what Dr. Neils Lauersen is accused of doing is a
common, unspoken practice among many doctors. What makes the case extraordinary
is that Lauersen has been charged by prosecutors with fraud.
</P>
<P>
	   Lauersen, 63, is accused of getting insurers to pay millions of dollars in
coverage for hundreds of patients over the past decade.
</P>
<P>
	   According to prosecutors, he helped couples get pregnant by providing
fertility treatments not covered by insurance. Then, he allegedly submitted
bills for various covered treatments.
</P>
<P>
	   "This sort of thing is unfortunately very widespread," said Michael Diegel,
spokesman for the Coalition Against Insurance Fraud in Washington.
</P>
<P>
	   He said Lauersen's trial should be a warning to all doctors tempted to bend
the rules.
</P>
<P>
	   Lauersen could get up to 10 years in prison on the most serious of the
charges.
</P>
<P>
	   Diegel's coalition -- made up of consumers, government agencies, public
interest groups and insurers -- estimated that health insurance fraud cost
insurers $53.9 billion in 1997. Much of that cost, he said, must be passed onto
the consumer as higher rates.
</P>
<P>
	   "One trial like this is helpful, but it's a long hard slog to convince
people to change their attitudes," Diegel said. "As many as 40 percent of the
people in this country think insurance fraud is OK."
</P>
<P>
	   Lauersen's lawyer, Theodore D. Wells, has said that his client did nothing
wrong and that the doctor merely billed insurers for treating the underlying
problems that cause infertility rather than for the infertility treatments
themselves.
</P>
<P>
	   Some of Lauersen's patients have been holding a vigil at the doctor's trial
and have said he was unfairly targeted, in part because he speaks out against
insurance companies that deny infertility coverage. Many of his patients
consider him a hero for making it possible for them to conceive.
</P>
<P>
	   Paulina Vizgan, 32, of Brooklyn, sitting in the courtroom Monday, said she
named one of her quadruplet boys Neils in honor of the doctor. "He is not a
criminal," Vizgan said. Infertility is "a major disability that impairs people's
lives."
</P>
<P>
	   Jennifer Cardillo, 28, of West Hampstead, said it is "not fair that they
cover Viagra and stuff for men and not this, which is for life." She said
Lauersen was "very caring, loving, dedicated and he makes every patient his
life."
</P>
<P>
	   Diegel estimated that half of all U.S. doctors are willing to bend the rules
to get insurers to pay for patient treatments. But doctors groups disagreed that
abuse is widespread.
</P>
<P>
	   "Our members follow the law," said Debra Crawford, spokeswoman for the
American Society for Reproductive Medicine. But she added that society members
would be pleased if more insurers covered infertility treatments, which often
run into the thousands of dollars.
</P>
<P>
	   "We've seen insurance companies getting a little greedier as time goes on
and covering less and less," Crawford said.
</P>
<P>
	   A single attempt to produce a child through in vitro fertilization or other
methods that rely on the processing of sperm and eggs in the laboratory can cost
as much as $7,500.
</P>
<P>
	   About 46,000 doctors nationwide provide infertility treatment to about 6.1
million couples, but insurance companies have been reluctant to cover
infertility.
</P>
<P>
	   Dennis Jay, executive director of the Coalition Against Insurance Fraud,
said insurance companies are an easy target because they now wield so much more
power than they did in the days when doctors "had it their own way, like an
American Express card, an unlimited amount they could charge."
</P>
<P>
	   "Most of them did not abuse that, but a large enough number did and that
burned a lot of insurance companies," he said. "Now the pendulum has swung back
the other way."
</P>
<P>
	   Linda Lyons, 38, another of Lauersen's patients, had bitter words for the
managed care system: "They're giving insurance companies more and more power as
to whether we live and die or whether we have children."
</P>
<P>
	   Three states -- Arkansas, Hawaii and Maryland -- require insurance companies
to cover, with some limits, in-vitro fertilization, in which sperm and eggs are
processed in a laboratory and inserted in a woman.
</P>
<P>
	   California, Connecticut and Texas require insurance companies to offer
coverage for infertility diagnosis and treatment.
</P>
<P>
	   Seven others -- Illinois, Massachusetts, Montana, New York, Ohio, Rhode
Island and West Virginia -- require some type of infertility coverage, though in
New York it is limited to the "diagnosis and treatment of correctable medical
conditions."
</P>
<P>
	   That often means the treatment of physical problems causing infertility,
such as fibroids, scarring, tubal damage from infection and ovulatory problems.
It does not mean, say, implantation of an embryo.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
