<DOCNO> APW20000215.0124 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-15 14:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nasdaq Down 92.06; Dow Up 99.28  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    NEW YORK (AP) -- Stock market measures diverged today, with technology
stocks falling sharply as investors collected profits from a recent run to
record levels. A rally in oil stocks and some bargain-hunting helped lift the
Dow Jones industrials, however.
</P>
<P>
	   In afternoon trading on Wall Street, the Nasdaq composite index was down
92.06 at 4,326.49, while the Dow Jones industrial average was up 99.28 at
10,619.12.
</P>
<P>
	   The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was down 3.26 at 1,386.68.
</P>
<P>
	   Technology stocks fell in the latest show of nervousness from investors who
are worried that the Federal Reserve will continue raising interest rates this
year as it works to keep inflation from accelerating. The Fed has raised rates
four times since last June, and has seen little sign that the economy's growth
has slowed.
</P>
<P>
	   Because higher interest rates can cut into corporate profits, investors have
been favoring stocks of companies whose profits are growing rapidly -- namely,
technology stocks. But some of those favorites were lower today as investors
sold shares to lock in profits.
</P>
<P>
	   Intel fell 3 5/8 to 106 1/4, and Cisco Systems fell 4 23/64 to 126 9/64.
</P>
<P>
	   "Markets are currently going through a period of trial, where upward
pressure on rates continue to take their toll on most financial instruments,"
said A.C. Moore, chief investment strategist for Dunvegan Associates in Santa
Barbara, Calif.
</P>
<P>
	   For a second session, the Dow held up better than the technology-dominated
Nasdaq. Consumer products company 3M rose 5 11/16 to 88 9/16, leading the index.
</P>
<P>
	   Also, Exxon Mobil rose 2 13/16 to 79 1/4 as crude oil futures remained above
$30 a barrel. Crude prices topped $30 a barrel Monday for the first time since
the eve of the Persian Gulf War in January 1991.
</P>
<P>
	   Texaco rose 1 1/16 to 49 15/16 on the New York Stock Exchange. A Lehman
Brothers analyst raised his rating on Texaco stock today, estimating that shares
will reach 65 within the next 12 months.
</P>
<P>
	   While rising prices are good for the companies that produce and explore for
oil, they can contribute to inflation. That possibility helped keep investors
out of the broader market today.
</P>
<P>
	   Later this week, the government will release data on producer prices and
consumer prices. Both reports are considered important gauges of inflation
pressures lurking in the economy.
</P>
<P>
	   Also, Fed chairman Alan Greenspan will testify before the House Banking
Committee on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
	   Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 5-to-4 margin on the New York
Stock Exchange, where volume came to 710.42 million shares at midafternoon,
compared with 615.45 million at the same time Monday.
</P>
<P>
	   The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies fell 4.48 to 535.46.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
