<HEADLINE> Albright To Visit Croatia, Albania  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Secretary of State Madeleine Albright will visit Croatia
on Friday to attend the inauguration of President-elect Stipe Mesic, and then
will travel to Albania for talks with top officials.
</P>
<P>
	   Albright visited Zagreb on Feb. 2 to endorse the democratic trends in the
country. U.S. officials believe the results of the national elections in Croatia
in January put the country much closer to the European mainstream.
</P>
<P>
	   They also believe the election could serve as a model for opposition groups
in Yugoslavia seeking to dislodge President Slobodan Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
	   The trip to Albania on Saturday will be Albright's first since the end of
the air war over Yugoslavia in June. She had been prevented from going to Tirana
before now because of security concerns.
</P>
<P>
	   State Department spokesman James P. Rubin said Albright will recognize the
role played by the people of Albania during the Kosovo crisis, particularly in
dealing with the hordes Kosovo Albanian refugees who fled to Albania at the
time.
</P>
</TEXT>
