<HEADLINE> AP Financial News at 3:10 p.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tuesday, Feb. 15, 2000
</P>
<P>
	   Industrial Production Soars in January
</P>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Industrial production at the nation's
factories, utilities and mines surged in January to its highest
level since August 1998. The Federal Reserve reported today that
production rose by 1 percent last month, twice the 0.5 percent gain
many analysts expected. The gain covered just about all sectors.
Plants were operating at about 81.6 percent of capacity.
</P>
<P>
	   Dow Up 138.06; Nasdaq Down 51.32
</P>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stock market measures diverged today, with
technology stocks falling as investors collected profits from a
recent run to record levels. A rally in oil stocks and some
bargain-hunting helped lift the Dow Jones industrials, however.
Just before 3 p.m. EST, the Dow Jones industrial average was up
138.06 at 10,657.90 while the Nasdaq composite index was down 51.20
at 4,367.35. Technology stocks fell in the latest show of
nervousness from investors who are worried that the Federal Reserve
will continue raising interest rates this year as it works to keep
inflation under control. Intel fell 3 5/8 to 106 1/4, and Cisco Systems
fell 4 23/64 to 126 9/64. Meanwhile, Exxon Mobil rose 2 13/16 to
79 1/4 as crude oil futures remained above $30 a barrel. Texaco rose 1
1/16 to 49 15/16.
</P>
<P>
	   Financial Figures
</P>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) -- Financial figures just before 3 p.m. EST:
