</P>
<P>
	   Clinton Concerned at Oil Prices
</P>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton said today the rising cost
of home heating oil was ``deeply troubling'' for low-income
families and that the federal government may release more money to
help them warm their homes. ``I have not closed off any options,''
the president said. ``I'm monitoring this on a daily basis.'' He
spoke briefly with reporters in the Cabinet Room after crude oil
prices climbed above $30 for the first time since the eve of the
Persian Gulf War nine years ago. Clinton said there would be some
important meetings among oil-producing countries within the next
few days, and price trends may be more apparent after that.
</P>
<P>
	   Chevron To Pay $9M Tax Settlement
</P>
<P>
	   NEW ORLEANS (AP) -- Chevron has agreed to pay Louisiana $9.6
million in a settlement the state hopes will serve as a model for
its other lawsuits involving alleged severance tax underpayments.
Oil companies must pay a state tax on all oil produced, or severed,
within Louisiana. Under the settlement, Chevron will pay Louisiana
$8.7 million to resolve the claims, plus $865,000 to cover
attorneys' fees for the case. Chevron did not acknowledge violating
any laws.
</P>
<P>
	   Cos. Urged on Global Leadership
</P>
<P>
	   BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) -- Multinational corporations were urged
at a U.N. trade conference today to fill a power vacuum left by
governments struggling to catch up in the globalizing world. The
increasing power of giant corporations in many countries means
people will turn to them -- rather than to their governments -- for
solutions to problems, said Juan Somavia, director-general of the
International Labor Organization. Somavia, of Chile, was the
featured official today at the weeklong U.N. Conference on Trade
and Development, bringing together some 190 countries to attempt to
define the world economy in the new millennium.
</P>
<P>
	   Clinton Taking Up Web Security
</P>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Following last week's attacks on Internet web
sites by hackers, President Clinton today began exploring ways to
tighten security on the World Wide Web. But he also said the
attacks were not a major disaster like the Japanese attack on Pearl
Harbor in World War II. He pictured hacking as part of the price
people have to pay for the success of the Internet.
</P>
<P>
	   Deadline Looms for Examiner Sale
</P>
<P>
	   SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- This the last day to bid to buy the San
Francisco Examiner, the Hearst Corp.'s 112-year-old flagship
newspaper. It has been has been up for sale since August without
finding any apparent powers. Now, Hearst says if none materialize
today, it plans to close the paper and merge its staff and
resources into the morning San Francisco Chronicle, which Hearst is
buying. Critics say such a setup would leave the Chronicle with a
monopoly as the city's only general interest daily newspaper.
</P>
<P>
	   Reuters Reporters Withhold Bylines
</P>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) -- U.S.-based reporters at Reuters have begun a
12-day byline strike to protest the company's stance on
negotiations for a contract to replace one that expired in February
1998. Some photographers also will withhold credits until Feb. 25,
according to their union, the Newspaper Guild of New York. ``This
gets us no closer to an agreement,'' said Bob Crooke, Reuters vice
president for media relations. ``The idea of having a byline on a
story for a major media corporation, one would have thought was a
privilege.''
</P>
<P>
	   Thomson Newspapers Put Up for Sale
</P>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) -- The Thomson Corp. plans to sell all its daily
and weekly newspapers except for its flagship, The Globe and Mail
in Toronto, in order to concentrate on its information services
business, the company announced today. The newspapers being sold
include 49 daily U.S. papers, most of which have circulations of
under 50,000, five dailies in Canada and more than 75 nondaily
newspapers. Thomson, which is based in Toronto, expects the sale to
close during the second half of the year. Thomson has been
increasing its focus on information services over the past several
years. Its legal and regulatory operations are a leading provider
of data and software to lawyers, accountants and other
professionals.
</P>
<P>
	   French Workweek Law Revision Sought
</P>
<P>
	   PARIS (AP) -- A group of French business leaders is asking
lawmakers to revise a controversial new law that shortens the
workweek to 35 hours. Ernest-Antoine Seilliere, leader of the MEDEF
organization of business leaders, said Tuesday the law needed
reworking so businesses ``can exist in acceptable conditions.'' The
law cuts working hours from 39 to 35 hours a week in a bid to
create jobs. Selliere told a news conference that the law is
``completely unsuited'' to the climate of growth that has recently
boosted the French economy after years of stagnation.
</P>
<P>
	   Japan Says Economy Improves
</P>
<P>
	   TOKYO (AP) -- Japan's economy has improved modestly for the last
five months but recession-weary consumers remain hesitant to spend,
the government said today. The assessment came in a monthly report
by the Economic Planning Agency. Its pronouncements are closely
watched by businesses and analysts as key indicators of the
government's thinking on the state of the world's second-largest
economy. The cautiously optimistic verdict delivered in the
February report was identical to the agency's four previous monthly
assessments.
</P>
<P>
	   Russia Denies Vodka Price Increase
</P>
<P>
	   MOSCOW (AP) -- Even though the minimum price for vodka is about
to go up because of a tax increase, acting President Vladimir Putin
denied Tuesday that the government had decided to raise the price.
The government sets a minimum price for vodka and determines excise
taxes. The price increase that is to take effect Feb. 25 results
from a 40 percent rise in excise taxes on alcoholic beverages.
</P>
<P>
	   Economic Reports
</P>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Economic reports:
</P>
<P>
	   Industrial production: up 1.0 percent
</P>
<P>
	   Tomorrow: Housing starts
</P>
<P>
	   Thursday: Jobless claims
</P>
<P>
	   Thursday: Producer price index
</P>
<P>
	   Friday: Consumer price index
</P>
<P>
	   Friday: International trade
</P>
