<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-15 15:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Up 190.49; Nasdaq Down 20.16  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    NEW YORK (AP) -- Stock market measures diverged today, with a rally in oil
stocks and some bargain-hunting buoying the Dow Jones industrials. In a major
turnaround from recent weeks, the strength in blue-chips helped pull technology
stocks out of a slump.
</P>
<P>
	   With an hour remaining in Wall Street's regular session, the Dow Jones
industrial average was up 190.49 at 10,710.33 while the Nasdaq composite index
was down 20.16 at 4,398.39. In earlier trading, the Nasdaq had been down as much
as 127 points.
</P>
<P>
	   The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was up 10.15 at 1,400.09.
</P>
<P>
	   For a second session, the Dow held up better than the technology-dominated
Nasdaq. Consumer products company 3M rose 5 11/16 to 88 9/16, leading the index.
</P>
<P>
	   Also, Exxon Mobil rose 3 9/16 to 80 as crude oil futures remained above $30
a barrel. Crude prices topped $30 a barrel Monday for the first time since the
eve of the Persian Gulf War in January 1991.
</P>
<P>
	   Texaco rose 1 1/4 to 50 1/8 on the New York Stock Exchange. A Lehman
Brothers analyst raised his rating on Texaco stock today, estimating that shares
will reach 65 within the next 12 months.
</P>
<P>
	   While rising prices are good for the companies that produce and explore for
oil, they can contribute to inflation. That possibility helped keep investors
out on edge today.
</P>
<P>
	   Technology stocks fell in the latest show of nervousness from investors who
are worried that the Federal Reserve will continue raising interest rates this
year as it works to keep inflation from accelerating. The Fed has raised rates
four times since June, and has seen little sign that the economy's growth has
slowed.
</P>
<P>
	   Because higher interest rates can cut into corporate profits, investors have
been favoring stocks of companies whose profits are growing rapidly -- namely,
technology stocks. But some of those favorites were lower today as investors
sold shares to lock in profits.
</P>
<P>
	   Cisco Systems fell 2 7/16 to 128 1/16, and MCI WorldCom fell 1 25/32 to 48
9/32.
</P>
<P>
	   "Markets are currently going through a period of trial, where upward
pressure on rates continue to take their toll on most financial instruments,"
said A.C. Moore, chief investment strategist for Dunvegan Associates in Santa
Barbara, Calif.
</P>
<P>
	   By late afternoon, however, some massive gains from a handful of technology
stocks were powering the index higher. Rambus rose 52 9/16 to 164 on the
expectation that Intel will use its technology to manufacture high-speed
computer chips.
</P>
<P>
	   Later this week, the government will release data on producer prices and
consumer prices. Both reports are considered important gauges of inflation
pressures lurking in the economy.
</P>
<P>
	   Also, Fed chairman Alan Greenspan will testify before the House Banking
Committee on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
	   Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 10-to-9 margin on the New York
Stock Exchange, where volume came to 849.54 million shares at late afternoon,
compared with 734.72 million at the same time Monday.
</P>
<P>
	   The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies fell 1.68 to 538.26.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
