<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-15 15:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Trade Tops GOP Trade Agenda  </HEADLINE>
   By JIM ABRAMS Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Cementing trade relations with China, opening markets to
Africa and the Caribbean and confirming America's leadership role in world
organizations are the main trade objectives of Congress this year, House
Republican leaders said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
	   In outlining their agenda, Republicans also released a congressional study
finding that the November trade agreement the Clinton administration reached
with China offers real opportunities for U.S. farmers and manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
	   That agreement, committing China to major market-opening measures, sets the
stage for China's accession to the World Trade Organization and requires
Congress to end the annual review of China's trade status and put trade
relations with China on a permanent basis.
</P>
<P>
	   The China vote expected this summer, said Rep. David Dreier, R-Calif., may
be the most important Congress casts this year to maintain the nation's economic
prosperity and leadership in the world.
</P>
<P>
	   House Majority Leader Dick Armey, R-Texas., described the GOP's three goals
as the ``trade expansion Contract with America.''
</P>
<P>
	   Before April, he said, Congress will try to complete legislation to promote
freer trade with sub-Saharan Africa and the Caribbean. The House last year
passed a bill that would allow most products from sub-Saharan Africa to enter
the country with no quotas or duties. The Senate passed a more limited Africa
trade bill and tacked on another measure to promote trade with the Caribbean.
The two chambers have yet to reach a compromise bill.
</P>
<P>
	   Second, he said, the House will work to ``soundly defeat'' expected
legislation that would withdraw U.S. support from the WTO. ``The WTO is not the
villain the Seattle radicals and their Washington allies would have us
believe,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
	   Finally is the vote on permanent trade status for China, which supporters
say will turn China into a more free and open society and be a significant
benefit to American exporters and investors. Opponents argue it would reward a
despotic, hostile country and take away an important tool to influence China's
human rights and weapons proliferation policies.
</P>
<P>
	   The nonpartisan Congressional Research Service report issued by the
Republicans cited a forecast by Agriculture Secretary Dan Glickman that U.S.
farm exports could increase by $2 billion annually once the Chinese start
removing barriers cited in the November agreement.
</P>
<P>
	   The Agriculture Department repeated on Tuesday that sales of farm products
to China could triple to $3 billion annually and tariffs on beef alone could
drop from 45 percent to 12 percent if China enters the WTO. Glickman told farm
lobbyists they have to be ``intent and focused'' on the matter and urged them to
organize pressure from farmers and other constituents on members of Congress.
</P>
<P>
	   House Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., said open trade with China is crucial
in his home state where corn prices are at their lowest in recent history and
Caterpillar tractors are not selling because of the lack of foreign markets.
</P>
<P>
	   Hastert said he planned to work with President Clinton on the trade agenda
and several Republicans praised the president for his commitment to winning
Democratic support. Dreier said he and other Republicans met Clinton Tuesday
night and ``I believe he is going to do everything he can'' to win the China
vote.
</P>
<P>
	   The administration has assigned Commerce Secretary William Daley to lead its
lobbying efforts on the China issue. Permanent trade status is opposed by labor,
human rights and environmental groups, among the Democrats' most important
constituents.
</P>
<P>
	   ``This is going to be the toughest fight we face this year on Capitol
Hill,'' White House chief of staff John Podesta told farm groups last week.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-15-00 1534 </TRAILER>
