<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-15 15:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New York state's highest court hears commuter tax case  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - New York City lawyers will argue Tuesday before the
state's highest court that legislators, preoccupied with winning a special
election in the state Senate, improperly rescinded a lucrative local tax on
commuters.
<P>
	   The only way the state Legislature and Gov. George Pataki could legally have
eliminated the city's tax was if the New York City Council had first passed a
"home rule" message requesting that it do so, the city's lawyers will contend.
No such home rule message was ever passed.
</P>
<P>
	   Also before the Court of Appeals Tuesday will be lawyers for Pennsylvania
and Connecticut. They will argue that if the elimination of the commuter tax is
upheld for New York state residents who work in the city but live outside the
five boroughs, then it is unconstitutional for the city to continue taxing
commuters living in their states.
</P>
<P>
	   The seven-member Court of Appeals is expected to hear more than an hour of
arguments in the case and to hand down a written ruling within six weeks. The
judges have promised to handle the case - various earlier legal actions against
the commuter tax were consolidated into one case for reasons of the appeal - in
an expedited fashion.
</P>
<P>
	   Both friends and foes of rescinding the commuter tax agree that its demise
was precipitated by local politics.
</P>
<P>
	   As part of a tough special election race to fill a vacant state Senate seat
in New York City's northern suburbs, the Democratic candidate stated that if
elected, he would not vote to extend the commuter tax. Republican candidate
Thomas Morahan - the eventual winner - said he would go one better and work to
repeal the tax altogether.
</P>
<P>
	   To the dismay of New York City Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, the Legislature and
Pataki quickly did away with the tax, even before the special election was held.
</P>
<P>
	   Pataki said he and the Legislature did the right thing and it's time to move
on.
</P>
<P>
	   "I think the commuter tax is gone," Pataki said Tuesday at an appearance at
a high-tech research center in Albany. "I think it's a good thing that will help
the state's economy and certainly help the city's economy. People will no longer
have a reason to avoid working or having their office located in New York City."
</P>
<P>
	   The case puts Giuliani, who is expected to run for Senate against Hillary
Rodham Clinton this November, in the somewhat uncomfortable position of pursuing
a court case to make hundreds of thousands of commuters - and potential voters -
pay a tax to the city.
</P>
<P>
	   "I have the advantage and disadvantage of holding a public office that is
one of the most difficult in the country," he said Monday when asked about the
case. "The things that I did as mayor of New York City to protect the people of
New York City I would equally as strongly and equally as well do to protect the
people of the state of New York."
</P>
<P>
	   Some 300,000 commuters from surrounding states work in New York City daily.
About 500,000 others come in from New York counties outside the five boroughs.
The city's 0.45 percent income tax totals $450 on an income of $100,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
	   A complete repeal could cost the city as much as $360 million a year;
repealing the tax only for New York residents would cost $210 million a year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-02-15-00 1535 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000215.0148 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-15 15:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Settlement means tobacco deal money can begin flowing into New  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   MORRISTOWN, N.J. (AP) - New Jersey will soon see the first installment
of its multibillion-dollar share of the national tobacco settlement after a
legal settlement reached Tuesday removed the last roadblock to disbursing the
money.
<P>
	   The first installment of over $180 million had been delayed for about two
months because two lawyers representing 12 smokers objected to the state's
settlement with big tobacco, saying more antismoking measures should have been
implemented.
</P>
<P>
	   The money, currently being held in an interest-bearing escrow account, could
be available in several weeks, said Michael A. Ferrara Jr., a lawyer on the
six-firm group hired by New Jersey to pursue the state case against cigarette
makers, which focused on reimbursement for Medicaid expenses.
</P>
<P>
	   Only a handful of states have not yet begun receiving tobacco money.
</P>
<P>
	   Tuesday's deal, reached after late-night talks, was concluded in the morning
outside a courtroom where an appellate panel was about to hear arguments on
efforts by the smokers' lawyers to intervene in the state settlement. The state
opposed that effort.
</P>
<P>
	   The deal requires Gov. Christie Whitman to recommend in her remaining
budgets that $30 million from the tobacco settlement go toward stop-smoking
programs each year.
</P>
<P>
	   She has already made that suggestion in the first of those budgets,
proposing that $8.7 million of the $30 million be spent on programs for addicted
adults and youth; $7 million for community tobacco control programs; $6.3
million for a youth anti-smoking awareness media campaign; $5 million for youth
antismoking programs, and $3 million for administration.
</P>
<P>
	   "Through our efforts, the people of the state of New Jersey will have the
benefit of smoking cessation programs that they might not otherwise have had,"
said Terry Paul Bottinelli, one of the lawyers for the 12 smokers.
</P>
<P>
	   He said he hoped that such programs would ultimately garner $750 million
from the state's $7.6 billion share of the national tobacco settlement, which is
to be received over 25 years. The state stood to lose all the money if the
intervention case had not concluded by Dec. 31, 2001.
</P>
<P>
	   Of the state's $300 million tobacco money infusion in the next fiscal year,
Whitman proposed spending one-third to provide health insurance for low- and
middle-income workers and one-third on new school construction, part of a $10
billion building program.
</P>
<P>
	   As a result of the deal, programs that had been suspended can now resume,
the governor said Tuesday, noting that antismoking billboards that came down
will be replaced.
</P>
<P>
	   One of Bottinelli's clients, Bruce S. Shortino of Clifton, works as a
security guard in the Morris County Courthouse where the appellate hearing was
scheduled.
</P>
<P>
	   Shortino, 53, a smoker for 35 years, said he has been unable to quit "cold
turkey." Since the private agency he works for provides no benefits, and he
cannot afford treatment, Shortino said he was happy that money may be available
to help smokers stop.
</P>
<P>
	   "If funds are put aside, I'll be the first one in line. I desperately want
to quit smoking," Shortino said.
</P>
<P>
	   Although Bottinelli and his co-counsel, Marc C. Saperstein, did not get any
fees as part of Tuesday's deal, they still hope to get compensation from an
alliance of 60 law firms that represents individuals who have sued the tobacco
industry.
</P>
<P>
	   They negotiated a mention in the state attorney general's news release that
announced the settlement and will present that to the alliance, of which they
are a part, Bottinelli said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-02-15-00 1537 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000215.0149 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-15 15:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feds probe $200,000 missing church grant  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   NEW HAVEN, Conn. (AP) - Federal prosecutors are investigating the
handling of a $200,000 grant given to a Bridgeport church to help homeless
veterans.
<P>
	   The findings of the U.S. attorney's investigation will be presented to a
grand jury, according to Kerri Childress, a spokeswoman for the U.S. Department
of Veterans Affairs. Childress said it would be up to the grand jury to decide
whether an indictment should be issued.
</P>
<P>
	   The VA gave the $200,000 to the Shiloh Baptist Church in Bridgeport in
January 1997, as the first part of a $500,000 award, Childress said. The money
is unaccounted for, she said.
</P>
<P>
	   The money was to be used to develop the Bridgeport Living Skills Center - a
live-in facility for homeless veterans to be built at the former Park City
Hospital administration building.
</P>
<P>
	   "The VA carefully monitors grant money. It is disbursed incrementally to
ensure work is being done, and the VA receives verification on an ongoing
basis," Childress said.
</P>
<P>
	   "We're concerned whenever money isn't used for its intended purpose," she
said. "Results of the investigation are pending."
</P>
<P>
	   The Rev. Carl McCluster, pastor of Shiloh Baptist, would not discuss the
matter and referred questions to his two lawyers.
</P>
<P>
	   One of his attorneys, Hugh F. Keefe, said it is too early to discuss the
case.
</P>
<P>
	   "No one has indicated to me that he has been charged, or will be charged,
with any crime," Keefe said.
</P>
<P>
	   McCluster's other attorney, William J. Egan, did not return telephone calls
seeking comment.
</P>
<P>
	   Assistant U.S. Attorney Calvin Kurimai, whose office Childress said is
handling the investigation, would not comment.
</P>
<P>
	   The Living Skills Center was to house homeless veterans while they learned
to manage money, become substance-free and search for long-term housing.
</P>
<P>
	   A new, nonprofit organization plans to apply for a grant to open a new
facility to serve homeless veterans in Bridgeport. Applied Behavioral
Rehabilitation Institute, a group based in New Haven, expects to apply for a new
VA grant next month, said John Wygmans, the institute's president.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-02-15-00 1544 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000215.0150 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-15 15:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wal-Mart's 4Q Profits Up 23 Percent  </HEADLINE>
    By RACHEL BECK AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) -- Wal-Mart Stores Inc.'s fourth-quarter profits rose 23
percent from a year ago, fueled by strong sales growth at its U.S. superstores
and operations abroad.
</P>
<P>
	   While the results reported Thursday by the world's largest retailer were
slightly above expectations, its stock fell nearly 3 percent on concerns that
its growth may slow in the coming year.
</P>
<P>
	   Wal-Mart earned $1.92 billion, or 43 cents a share, for the quarter ended
Jan. 31, compared with $1.56 billion, up from 35 cents a share a year ago.
That's above the 42 cents a share that analysts' had forecast.
</P>
<P>
	   Quarterly sales totaled $51.39 billion, an increase of 26 percent over the
$40.79 billion in the same period a year ago. Sales at stores open at least a
year, an industry gauge of performance, rose 6.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
	   Sales at its Wal-Mart stores rose 12.6 percent in the quarter, boosted by
gains at its SuperCenters, which combine discount and grocery stores. Sales at
its Sam's Club warehouse stores increased 7.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
	   International sales gained about 164 percent, fueled by strength in its
Mexican, Canadian, British and Puerto Rican division.
</P>
<P>
	   During the quarter, Wal-Mart named Lee Scott as president and chief
executive officer, replacing David Glass who will remain at the company for a
year as chairman of the executive committee of the board of directors.
</P>
<P>
	   Scott, who was Wal-Mart's chief operating officer and vice chairman, had
been tapped about a year ago to succeed Glass.
</P>
<P>
	   The company also took some significant steps during the quarter to beef up
its Internet operations.
</P>
<P>
	   In December, Wal-Mart teamed up with America Online Inc. to develop an
Internet service provider and offer discounted Web access to people who
currently may not have an affordable phone hookup in towns near its 2,500
stores. The name and price of the ISP have not yet been released.
</P>
<P>
	   In January, the company relaunched www.Walmart.com, which now stocks more
than 600,000 items and offers a wide array of services, such as travel
reservations. It also formed a new Internet company with venture-capital firm
Accel Partners, which will work to enhance the giant retailer's Web site.
</P>
<P>
	   While Wal-Mart continues to outpace most of its rivals with its sharp
growth, there were fears that its pace may slow in the coming year.
</P>
<P>
	   The Federal Reserve boosted interest rates four times in the last year to
fend off inflationary pressure -- and may raise rates further. That has raised
concerns that consumer spending may slow in the coming months.
</P>
<P>
	   "That's the real issue affecting all retailers right now," said Jeffrey
Feiner, a retail analyst at Lehman Brothers Inc.
</P>
<P>
	   Wal-Mart also said that it will continue aggressively cutting prices, which
the company calls "rollbacks." But such promotions will be more difficult in the
coming year because of high raw material prices, increased labor costs and
strengthening of Asian currencies.
</P>
<P>
	   The "rollbacks" have been one of Wal-Mart's key marketing strategies to woo
shoppers into its stores.
</P>
<P>
	   Wal-Mart's shares were down $1.68 3/4 at $57.18 3/4 in afternoon trading on
the New York Stock Exchange. The Bentonville, Ark.-based retailer's stock was
down as low as $55 in early trading.
</P>
<P>
	   For the year, Wal-Mart earned $5.58 billion, or $1.25 a share, compared with
$4.43 billion, or 99 cents a share, in 1998. Sales for the year were $165
billion, an increase of 20 percent over the previous year.
</P>
<P>
	   Its annual results do not include a 4-cent reduction due to a change in
rules by the Securities and Exchange Commission in how Wal-Mart accounts for
membership revenues at its Sam's Club.
</P>
<P>
	   As of Jan. 31, Wal-Mart operated 1,801 Wal-Mart stores, 721 Supercenters,
and 463 Sam's Clubs in the United States. Internationally, the company operated
13 units in Argentina, 14 in Brazil, 166 in Canada, six in China, 95 in Germany,
five in Korea, 462 in Mexico, 15 in Puerto Rico and 232 in the United Kingdom.
</P>
<P>
	   Wal-Mart employs more than 885,000 people in the United States and 255,000
internationally.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-15-00 1545 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000215.0151 </DOCNO>
