<HEADLINE> Clinton Worried on Heating Oil Costs  </HEADLINE>
   By TERENCE HUNT AP White House Correspondent
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton said Tuesday the federal government is
willing to give more help to families ``that are really getting hurt'' by the
soaring cost of home heating oil in New England and the Middle Atlantic states.
</P>
<P>
	   So far, the government has released $200 million from the Low Income Home
Energy Assistance Program. ``We can release more,'' the president said.
</P>
<P>
	   Energy Secretary Bill Richardson will travel to Boston on Wednesday to meet
with leaders of industry and consumer groups about fuel costs.
</P>
<P>
	   The rising cost of heating oil has become an issue in the Senate race
between the president's wife, Hillary Rodham Clinton, and her likely Republican
rival, New York Mayor Rudolph Giuliani. The mayor has urged the president to
release oil from the country's strategic petroleum reserve to offset oil price
increases that have put the price above $30 for the first time since the eve of
the Persian Gulf War nine years ago.
</P>
<P>
	   That war marked the only time the reserve was tapped since its establishment
a quarter-century ago.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I have not closed off any options,'' the president said, talking with
reporters in the Cabinet Room during a meeting with high technology officials.
``I'm monitoring this on a daily basis.''
</P>
<P>
	   The administration has refused to dip into the petroleum reserve, created to
deal with national emergencies. White House press secretary Joe Lockhart said
Clinton ``does not believe it's appropriate to draw down'' the reserve now.
</P>
<P>
	   However, Lockhart said, ``This situation is one that involves watching
further, and that context may change.''
</P>
<P>
	   Clinton said important meetings are scheduled among oil-producing countries
within the next few days. ``We will know more about this in a week or 10 days,
about what the trends are going to be,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
	   ``But the American people are handling the price increase pretty well in
terms of every aspect of our lives because of increased energy efficiency,
except for home heating oil,'' he said. He said many people in New England and
Middle Atlantic states ``are still dependent upon a source of heating which the
rest of the country left long ago.''
</P>
<P>
	   ``And they are unbelievably burdened by this,'' the president said.
</P>
<P>
	   Clinton said the government's heating oil assistance eases the burden of the
poorest families, ``but there are a lot of working people on modest incomes that
are just getting killed by this, because of their reliance on home heating
oil.''
</P>
<P>
	   He said middle- and lower-income Americans ``have no option to heat their
home but home heating oil. They're the people that are really getting hurt.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
