<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000215.0159 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-15 16:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Paris Launches Graffiti Offensive  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS (AP) -- The mayor of Paris on Tuesday announced an ambitious program to
wipe out the graffiti now staining the City of Light, offering free cleaning for
all buildings.
</P>
<P>
	   Mayor Jean Tiberi said cleaners will work throughout Paris to eliminate
graffiti -- usually consisting of squiggly black spray paint. The city estimates
that graffiti covers 2.7 million square feet and is found on about 40 percent of
the city's 90,000 buildings.
</P>
<P>
	   The six-year program will cost $72 million, the mayor said.
</P>
<P>
	   Until now, building owners had to foot the bill to remove graffiti. Now the
city will cover the cost, even on privately-owned apartment buildings, the mayor
said.
</P>
<P>
	   Building owners who reject the free service will have to pay to keep their
properties clean.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We think we will correct the problem for 90 percent of the situations
within a year,'' Tiberi told reporters, explaining that a five-year maintenance
program would follow.
</P>
<P>
	   The cost of the cleanup is small compared to the benefits, Tiberi said. He
said that clean walls would help curb ``feelings of insecurity.''
</P>
<P>
	   The city will start cleaning all buildings this April. After the initial
cleaning, building owners will have 12 days to contact the city to get any new
graffiti wiped away.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-15-00 1618 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000215.0160 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-15 16:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> TV, Radio Ads Drive Gains at CBS  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    NEW YORK (AP) -- CBS Corp. narrowly beat analysts' expectations for
fourth-quarter earnings Tuesday as advertising gains in its television and radio
operations surged ahead.
</P>
<P>
	   CBS reported net income of $251 million, or 34 cents per share, for the
three months ended Dec. 31 compared to a net loss of $1 million in the same
period a year ago.
</P>
<P>
	   The reported figures included a one-time gain of $232 million related to the
sale of the company's former industrial businesses. Without the gain, CBS earned
$19 million, or 3 cents per share, edging the 2 cents per share estimated by
analysts surveyed by First Call /Thomson Financial.
</P>
<P>
	   Revenues jumped 24 percent to $2.22 billion from $1.79 billion in the
year-ago period.
</P>
<P>
	   A robust environment for advertising spending lifted results across CBS'
business segments, which include the TV network, 16 TV stations, cable and a
majority stake in Infinity Broadcasting, a major radio broadcaster and outdoor
advertising company.
</P>
<P>
	   CBS' newly formed Internet subsidiary lost $30 million, mainly as a result
of its investment in iWon.com, a new portal site which launched a major ad
campaign during the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
	   Not counting the Internet loss, depreciation or amortization costs, the
company's after-tax cash flow rose 81 percent to $279 million from $154 million
in the same period a year ago.
</P>
<P>
	   During the fourth quarter CBS also completed its acquisition of King World,
a major syndicator of TV programs such as "Wheel of Fortune." Its Infinity
subsidiary also closed its deal to acquire Outdoor Systems, a major billboard
and out-of-home advertising company.
</P>
<P>
	   CBS was reporting in what may be its last quarter as a stand-alone company
before its merger with MTV owner Viacom Inc., which was recently approved by the
shareholders of both companies.
</P>
<P>
	   For the full year, CBS reported net income of $780 million, or $1.08 per
share, compared to a loss of $21 million or 3 cents per share in 1998. Revenues
rose 8 percent to $7.37 billion from $6.81 billion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
