<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AP Reviews Renee Fleming Concert  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    AN AP ENTERTAINMENT REVIEW
</P>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) -- Renee Fleming, the reigning soprano of the Metropolitan
Opera, spent her 41st birthday producing some of the most beautiful singing to
be heard currently, in the role of Lucrezia Borgia in a concert version at
Carnegie Hall.
</P>
<P>
	   Donizetti's opera, in which Lucrezia Borgia poisons six people in the last
scene, was Monday's Valentine's Day gift from the Opera Orchestra of New York,
conducted by Eve Queler. The hall was long sold out.
</P>
<P>
	   Fleming, a lyric soprano, alternated between a wild, rip-roaring,
passionate, Maria Callas-style interpretation and the more delicately spun lines
she generally chose. The words and music could be interpreted either way.
</P>
<P>
	   At the opera's end, for instance, when she realizes her son is among the
young noblemen she has poisoned, Fleming had a vocal outburst -- then sang like
she was dreaming, soft and lovely. She tore briefly into dramatic coloratura,
then returned to the contemplative singing of a breaking heart.
</P>
<P>
	   In the prologue, in which Lucrezia first encounters her grown son from a
previous marriage, Fleming's voice was ravishingly beautiful throughout. In Act
1, Lucrezia becomes angry when her family crest is defaced and her singing was
more fiery. The contrast was good and probably helpful for surviving a long role
with voice intact.
</P>
<P>
	   "Lucrezia Borgia" is the opera in which Fleming was booed at La Scala in
1998. In rehearsal there, she had disagreed with conductor Gianluigi Gelmetti
about her ornamentation of the vocal line. At the first performance, on July 6,
she was booed from the first note she sang by some people, believed to be an
anti-American group. Gelmetti fainted in the pit, which interrupted the
performance.
</P>
<P>
	   Fleming shared the stage Monday with another exceptional singer, Stephanie
Blythe, a dramatic mezzo-soprano who sang Orsini, one of the young noblemen who
have had relatives killed by Lucrezia. Blythe's voice, clear and shining on top,
gutsy on the low notes, contained excitement in every note.
</P>
<P>
	   Blythe, who won the 1999 Richard Tucker Award, made her Metropolitan Opera
debut in 1995. She was making her debut with the Opera Orchestra of New York.
Fleming was singing with the organization for the seventh time.
</P>
<P>
	   Marcello Giordani from Sicily sang Gennaro, Lucrezia's son, as he had at La
Scala in 1998. He was making his debut with the Opera Orchestra and at Carnegie
Hall. His is a good, solid Italian tenor. Bass-baritone Dean Peterson was
notable as Lucrezia's husband, Duke Alfonso. He made his Met Opera debut this
season. Ars Musica Chorale was the chorus; they and the orchestra were
excellent.
</P>
<P>
	   This is the 29th season of the Opera Orchestra of New York, which
specializes in one-night performances of seldom-heard operas in concert version.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-15-00 1624 </TRAILER>
