<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Starts Member Talks With Six  </HEADLINE>
   By CONSTANT BRAND Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) -- The 15-nation European Union took another step
towards expanding Tuesday, opening membership talks with six more candidate
nations.
</P>
<P>
	   Romania, Bulgaria, Slovakia, Latvia, Lithuania and Malta constitute the
second wave of mostly eastern European nations to start negotiations with the EU
on future membership.
</P>
<P>
	   They join Poland, Hungary, Slovenia, the Czech Republic, Cyprus and Estonia,
which started talks two years ago and hope to be allowed into the union within
the next two or three years.
</P>
<P>
	   ``After being for almost half a century on the bad side of history ... this
historic moment means Romania is now on the right side,'' Romanian Foreign
Minister Petre Roman said.
</P>
<P>
	   Many of the six new candidate countries are ambitiously aiming to enter the
EU around 2004, when they hope they will meet difficult economic and political
criteria, including the acceptance of free market policies and adherence to
democratic principles.
</P>
<P>
	   Negotiations also must tackle a vast range of complex technical issues,
including agricultural and industrial subsidies, environmental standards and
antitrust law.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The process that lies ahead of us will be very difficult,'' EU Enlargement
Commissioner Gunter Verheugen said.
</P>
<P>
	   The widening of enlargement talks comes at an awkward time for the EU, which
is struggling with an internal crisis sparked by the entry of Austria's
far-right Freedom Party into that country's coalition government.
</P>
<P>
	   The Freedom Party has expressed opposition to the EU expansion, fearing an
influx of immigrants from Austria's poorer eastern neighbors and a loss of jobs
as investors move to low-wage former Eastern bloc nations. Concern over Austria
has put it at odds with the union's other members.
</P>
<P>
	   Austria's new foreign minister, Benita Ferrero-Waldner, insisted her
government was committed to the EU's shift eastward. She is a member of the
mainstream People's Party, the Freedom Party's coalition partner.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Austria is in favor of the enlargement ... all the other comments who say
we are opposed are wrong,'' she said. But she added that Austria had special
concerns over the expansion since it is the EU country with the longest frontier
with the eastern candidate nations.
</P>
<P>
	   The 12 nations now in talks with the EU are not the end of the expansion
list. Turkey has also been recognized as a candidate, while Croatia, Macedonia,
Albania and Bosnia have expressed long-term hopes of joining.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Joining the European Union is a very important guarantor of independence
and prosperity,'' said Portuguese Foreign Minister Jaime Gama, who chaired
Tuesday's meeting.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-15-00 1625 </TRAILER>
