<HEADLINE> EU Lifts Ex-French Premier Immunity  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) -- The European Union's executive body on Tuesday
lifted the immunity of former French Premier Edith Cresson, clearing the way for
Belgian authorities to question her about a scandal that brought down the
previous EU executive team.
</P>
<P>
	   Officials want to question Cresson about her hiring of a dentist friend,
Rene Berthelot, to work at the EU's headquarters when she was the EU's research
commissioner.
</P>
<P>
	   Revelations that Berthelot received $135,000 for scientific consultancy work
for which he was subsequently judged unqualified were a major factor in forcing
the resignation of Cresson and the whole EU Commission in March 1999.
</P>
<P>
	   The investigation, which began a year ago, centers around allegations of
fraud, forgery and abuse of trust, judicial officials said. It was too early to
say if Cresson would be charged with any offense.
</P>
<P>
	   The Belgian public prosecutors office said eight people, including Cresson
and Berthelot, were included in the investigation, with others likely to follow.
</P>
<P>
	   Cresson was an EU commissioner from 1995 to 1999 and French prime minister
for 10 months ending in 1992. She has denied allegations Berthelot was given a
fictitious job and said that although not a scientific expert, he had sound
managerial experience.
</P>
<P>
	   Cresson also has been accused of mismanaging programs she was responsible
for overseeing.
</P>
<P>
	   EU commissioners and former commissioners have diplomatic immunity for
events that occurred while they were working for the union. But the 20-member EU
Commission can suspend the immunity.
</P>
<P>
	   The new EU Commission, which took office in September under Romano Prodi,
has pledged to root out corruption and nepotism in the EU civil service.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
