<HEADLINE> Moscow Welcomes Clinton Remarks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW (AP) -- The Russian Foreign Ministry said Tuesday it welcomed
President Clinton's remarks in an interview on U.S.-Russian relations, which
have been in a period of tension, the news agency Interfax reported.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The Russian leadership shares the desire expressed by the U.S. president
to intensify the bilateral dialogue, primarily in the spheres of security and
disarmament, and to overcome the trend there for a dangerous impasse,'' the
ministry said, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
	   Clinton, in an interview with CNN that was broadcast on the Internet, said
good things about acting President Vladimir Putin.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Based on what I have seen so far, I think that the United States can do
business with this man. I think he's obviously highly intelligent; he's highly
motivated; he has strong views,'' Clinton said in response to a question sent in
from a viewer using e-mail.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We don't agree with him on everything, but what I have seen of him so far
indicates to me that he's capable of being a very strong and effective and
straightforward leader.''
</P>
<P>
	   Relations between Washington and Moscow have been troubled in the past year
over the NATO bombing of Yugoslavia, U.S. criticism of the war in Chechnya and
Russia's concerns about the eastward expansion of NATO, among other issues.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
