<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-15 16:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NATO Said 'Marking Time' in Kosovo  </HEADLINE>
   By ROBERT BURNS AP Military Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Eight months after NATO forced the Serb army's withdrawal
from Kosovo, the top U.S. military officer said Tuesday that international
peacekeepers are ``marking time'' while waiting for U.N. and other civilian
authorities to assume police and civil reconstruction duties.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We're hurting. We need more police'' to fill the law-enforcement vacuum
that U.S. and other peacekeepers are forced to deal with in Kosovo, said Army
Gen. Henry Shelton, chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff.
</P>
<P>
	   While noting that much of Kosovo has been stabilized, Shelton said the
eruption of ethnic violence last weekend in Mitrovica, in a section of northern
Kosovo controlled mainly by French peacekeepers, showed that tensions remain
high and illegal arms are readily available to both Serbs and ethnic Albanians.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I am concerned that the violence was so great'' during the Serbs' forced
expulsion of hundreds of thousands of Albanians last year, ``and the animosity
and the desire for retribution is so great that it will take a long time for
that to ever go away,'' Shelton said in an interview with defense reporters.
</P>
<P>
	   Shelton sounded pessimistic about the prospect of achieving the United
Nations' stated goal of rebuilding a multiethnic Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I would have to stop short of saying whether or not I think we can get
there,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
	   The main problem, Shelton said, is that the United Nations, the Organization
for Security and Cooperation in Europe, the European Union and other
international civilian organizations have not lived up to their commitments to
provide tools needed to rebuild Kosovo's political, judicial and economic
systems.
</P>
<P>
	   ``All those (groups) have got to come to bear on this problem (and) get it
moving at a faster pace than it is going now,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
	   In the meantime, the peacekeepers are being asked to do things, such as law
enforcement work, that civilians should be doing, he said.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We're kind of marking time, waiting for them to do that,'' he said.
``Ultimately you've got to have a government put back in, you've got to have
police and rule of law -- those things that our soldiers, our KFOR troops, do
not do.'' KFOR is the Kosovo Force of international peacekeepers.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The long-term solution is not to keep KFOR there forever.''
</P>
<P>
	   Shelton said it was not clear what triggered the burst of ethnic violence in
Mitrovica in recent days. He declined to fault the French peacekeepers in that
area for failing to stop the flow of illegal arms.
</P>
<P>
	   ``As you know, this is somewhat analogous to the Old West in terms of where
the bows and arrows might be or where the weapons are being kept,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
	   The Pentagon, meanwhile, said that 20 to 25 American soldiers moved Tuesday
from the U.S.-controlled southeastern sector of Kosovo to the French-controlled
area where snipers on Sunday wounded two French peacekeepers.
</P>
<P>
	   The Americans -- mainly communications and language specialists -- are
supporting a group of about 100 Greek infantry soldiers who will help patrol the
Mitrovica area for the next few days, Pentagon spokesman Rear Adm. Craig Quigley
said. The Greeks also moved from the U.S.-controlled sector.
</P>
<P>
	   ``These forces are very visible when they move into various sectors, by
design, to show NATO's presence, to show solidarity and the cross-national
solidarity of the NATO alliance as well,'' Quigley said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-15-00 1656 </TRAILER>
