<HEADLINE> Mexico University Building Occupied  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY (AP) -- Supporters of the 9 1/2-month strike at Latin America's
largest university continued to occupy the campus science building Tuesday, one
day after classes resumed in most of the university.
</P>
<P>
	   Students at the science school of the National Autonomous University voted
Monday to block the return of classes there. About 300 people occupied the
building Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
	   Strikers had occupied the entire campus until Feb. 6, when unarmed police
entered the main campus and arrested hundreds of students, including strike
leaders.
</P>
<P>
	   Though the university administration retook control of the whole campus in
the days after the raid, the council that led the occupation insists that the
strike isn't over. The council is pressing its demands for changes in university
policies and administration. It is also calling for the release of the
approximately 250 strikers still in jail.
</P>
<P>
	   The strike began as a protest to university plans to raise tuition, which
had been a few cents, to the equivalent of $140. It continued even after the
administration backed down on the tuition increase.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
