<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-15 17:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Two more officers claim Diallo threat  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - Toeing the defense line, two more officers on trial
for killing Amadou Diallo with a barrage of 41 bullets testified Tuesday he
appeared to draw a gun and take a "combat stance" as shots flew.
<P>
	   Both Kenneth Boss and Richard Murphy also described a futile search inside
the vestibule of Diallo's Bronx apartment building for a gun he never had. Boss
told jurors at the murder trial he was "destroyed" to learn the black object
found in the West African immigrant's right hand was a wallet.
</P>
<P>
	   "I kept praying the weapon would be in there, that it was somewhere," said
Boss, who fired five of the shots.
</P>
<P>
	   Amid the gunfire, Diallo stood at the rear of the 5-by-7-foot vestibule with
his right arm extended, Boss said. The victim, he added, "was crouched like in a
combat stance. ... The same one I was taught in the police academy."
</P>
<P>
	   Boss also testified that he saw Officer Edward McMellon "fly off" of
Diallo's doorstep. When the gunfire ended, he grabbed McMellon and "started
feeling his chest, going 'Where are you hit, where are you hit?' ... He said,
'I'm not hit."' McMellon actually had fallen while retreating.
</P>
<P>
	   Said Murphy: "There was not a doubt in my mind that (Diallo) had a gun. I
had a sick feeling in my stomach that I was going to be hit at any second.
That's why I fired." He shot four times.
</P>
<P>
	   The jury heard a recording of a radio call in which a frantic-sounding Boss
says, "I need a bus forthwith, and a boss" - police parlance for an ambulance
and a supervisor. He said he had to find a street sign before giving the
dispatcher a location because "I didn't know what street I was on."
</P>
<P>
	   Attorneys never questioned Boss about shooting and killing a man armed with
a shotgun in Brooklyn in October 1997. A grand jury found no wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
	   In the courtroom were several of the officers' family members and supporters
wearing "Free the Bronx 4" buttons. Diallo's Guinean parents, dressed in
colorful robes, sat across the aisle; scores of their supporters rallied
outside.
</P>
<P>
	   The testimony of Boss, 28, and Murphy, 27, echoed that of codefendants Sean
Carroll, 37, and McMellon, 27, who took the stand Monday to explain why they
each fired 16 shots. Diallo was hit 19 times.
</P>
<P>
	   At the time of the shooting - at 12:40 a.m. on Feb. 4, 1999 - the
plainclothes officers wore blue jeans and sneakers and bulletproof vests under
sweatshirts.
</P>
<P>
	   The defendants were patrolling Diallo's neighborhood in an unmarked car in
search of armed criminals. Only Carroll had more than one year of experience in
the roving Street Crime Unit.
</P>
<P>
	   The officers' testimony emphasized similar points: that it was dark; that
Diallo ignored orders to halt for questioning; that the gunfire lasted only a
few seconds and was continuous; and that the victim remained on his feet
throughout. Each officer denied ever shooting him after he was already down.
</P>
<P>
	   The prosecution contends the officers never yelled any warnings before
trapping the unarmed victim in the vestibule with a "wall of lead." Backed by
autopsy findings, prosecutors also say most of the bullets hit Diallo while he
was going down or flat on his back.
</P>
<P>
	   The shooting of an unarmed black man by four white officers resulted in
enough pretrial publicity and protests alleging widespread police abuse of
minorities that an appeals decided to move the case to Albany. Testimony was
expected to continue through the end of this week, with summations early next
week.
</P>
<P>
	   Supreme Court Justice Joseph Teresi and attorneys were to meet Tuesday to
discuss how the jury will be instructed before deliberating.
</P>
<P>
	   The officers have pleaded innocent to charges of intentional murder,
depraved indifference and reckless endangerment. If convicted, they face a
maximum sentence of 25 years to life.
</P>
<P>
	   Attorney say the jury probably will be allowed to consider lesser charges
against the officers - like manslaughter or criminally negligent homicide -
which carry lighter penalties.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-02-15-00 1712 </TRAILER>
