<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-15 17:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thruway Authority will reconsider toll hike  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - Its toll increase plan encountering strong
opposition from Gov. George Pataki, the state Legislature and business groups,
the state Thruway Authority said Tuesday it is reconsidering the proposal.
<P>
	   Pataki said leaders at the authority "are going to take another look" at
whether the Thruway can fund $1 billion in improvements to transportation
facilities over the next five years in some other way than a toll increase.
</P>
<P>
	   The Thruway's board, with all three members selected by Pataki, approved a
previously unannounced plan on Jan. 27 to let tolls increase by up to 3 percent
each year. The increases would be tied to a 20-city building expense standard
called the Construction Cost Index and the Thruway's first toll increase would
be 1.8 percent starting June 1.
</P>
<P>
	   But Senate Majority Leader Joseph Bruno and Assembly Speaker Sheldon Silver
threatened to block the toll increase legislatively if the Thruway Authority
didn't withdraw the proposal.
</P>
<P>
	   Pataki's statements Tuesday, made after an appearance at the State
University of New York at Albany, were his strongest and most negative to date
on the toll hike.
</P>
<P>
	   "I'm opposed to any toll increases," Pataki said. "We've had five years and
two months without any toll increases since I've been governor, and I hope they
can avoid this one as well."
</P>
<P>
	   Pataki in 1996 made the Thruway Authority back down from a planned toll
increase.
</P>
<P>
	   Pataki's hand-picked chairman on the Thruway Board, Lou Tomson, issued a
statement later Tuesday acknowledging that the board was actively searching for
alternatives to a toll hike.
</P>
<P>
	   "We look forward to working with the governor and the Legislature on ideas
that will allow us to make the important investments necessary to keep the
Thruway safe and efficient without the need for a toll increase," Tomson, once a
top figure in Pataki's executive chamber, said.
</P>
<P>
	   On Tuesday morning, state Assembly Republicans said the Thruway toll
increases can be avoided by relieving the Thruway Authority of the
responsibility of running the state barge canal system.
</P>
<P>
	   Handing the canal system to the Office of Parks, Recreation and Historic
Preservation would save the Thruway Authority $55 million a year, Assembly
Minority Leader John Faso said. If that happens, the authority would be left
with enough money at current toll levels to operate the superhighway and to make
what Thruway officials say are crucial improvements to the system.
</P>
<P>
	   Thruway tolls have been propping up operations of the state canal system
since its transfer from the state Department of Transportation to the Thruway
Authority in 1992, amid a deep state financial trough.
</P>
<P>
	   Faso said that including the canal as a responsibility of the Thruway
Authority was a fiscal "contrivance" and a "gimmick" by former Gov. Mario Cuomo
who wanted to fund the historic system with the reliable revenue of Thruway
tolls. The authority was also able to borrow money for canal improvements.
</P>
<P>
	   "It's up to the Legislature to remedy the Cuomo-era mistake that was made,"
Faso said. "It's not up to the Thruway Authority to do that."
</P>
<P>
	   Shifting the canal system to the Parks office would put the onus on state
taxpayers to pay for the canals' maintenance and operations, offset by the
relatively small amount raised on the waterways through fees.
</P>
<P>
	   Tomson on Tuesday called the idea of shifting oversight for the canal system
to a different agency "one potential alternative that merits serious
consideration."
</P>
<P>
	   The previously unannounced plan to hike tolls angered Democratic and
Republican legislators, who said a toll increase would harm upstate, where the
economy remains sluggish compared to the rest of the state and nation.
</P>
<P>
	   Pataki said even he did not know the toll hike plan was going to be voted
on.
</P>
<P>
	   "You'd be amazed about what I read in the newspapers," Pataki said. "I did
not know they were going to be passing this resolution."
</P>
<P>
	   Assembly Republicans said they were not advocating that the Thruway
Authority divest itself of maintenance responsibilities for Interstate 287 and
Interstate 84 north of New York City. Both of those have connections to the
Thruway and are also highway systems, Faso said.
</P>
<P>
	   On Wednesday, two Democratic committees will continue hearings in Albany on
the proposed Thruway toll increase.
</P>
<P>
	   ----
</P>
<P>
	   EDITOR'S NOTE: AP Writer Marc Humbert contributed to this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-02-15-00 1724 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
