<DOCNO> APW20000215.0185 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-15 17:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Police union delegate denies cops met to coordinate their stories  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   NEW YORK (AP) - A police union official admitted Tuesday he told cops at
Brooklyn's 70th Precinct to keep silent about the bathroom assault on Abner
Louima, but denied that four officers agreed in a secret meeting to coordinate
their versions of the brutal incident.
<P>
	   Called as a reluctant government witness, Michael Immitt, a trustee of the
Patrolmen's Benevolent Association, seethed with palpable anger as he testified
about his involvement with three officers now on trial for conspiring to
obstruct justice.
</P>
<P>
	   Several times, Assistant U.S. Attorney Alan Vinegrad pounced on answers that
evaded or contradicted what Immitt had said previously about the meeting and the
PBA's role in trying to keep the racially charged affair under control.
</P>
<P>
	   At one point, Immitt claimed that at the time of the closed-door
stationhouse meeting on Aug. 13, 1997 - four days after the attack - he didn't
know the Louima sexual assault story was already on newsstands under the banner
headline, "Tortured By Cops."
</P>
<P>
	   "This meeting did not occur until after the story was on the front page of
the Daily News?" Vinegrad asked.
</P>
<P>
	   "That's not true," Immitt snapped.
</P>
<P>
	   Vinegrad then showed him the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
	   "That's what it says. That's the case," the witness conceded. "If I met with
them that afternoon, then the story was already out."
</P>
<P>
	   Officer Justin Volpe pleaded guilty last May and is serving 30 years for
sodomizing Louima, a Haitian immigrant, with a broom handle. Officer Charles
Schwarz was convicted of holding the victim down and faces a possible life
sentence.
</P>
<P>
	   In the current trial, Schwarz, 34, Thomas Bruder, 34 and Thomas Wiese, 37,
are accused of conspiring to conceal Schwarz's role by claiming Schwarz was
never in the bathroom when Louima was sodomized.
</P>
<P>
	   At sentencing, Volpe said Wiese was the only other cop in the room during
the incident, and did not take part. Volpe is expected to testify for the
defense.
</P>
<P>
	   All four were present at the meeting with Immitt and a PBA lawyer four days
later.
</P>
<P>
	   Under Vinegrad's hostile questioning, Immitt denied coaching the four
officers on what to tell investigators from the police Internal Affairs Bureau,
or that he urged other cops at the beleaguered Brooklyn stationhouse to shut up
about the Louima affair.
</P>
<P>
	   He insisted he went to the meeting not knowing what to expect and learned
little about the case from the discussion itself.
</P>
<P>
	   "Isn't it a fact that the meeting's purpose was to figure out ... a way that
the IAB investigation would not succeed?" Vinegrad asked.
</P>
<P>
	   "No," said Immitt. "I had no idea what was going on. ... I walked out
knowing only that Abner Louima had been assaulted in some fashion."
</P>
<P>
	   "But you didn't know that Abner Louima had an object shoved up his rectum?"
Vinegrad asked. "No, I did not," snarled Immitt.
</P>
<P>
	   After Vinegrad reminded him of previous testimony to a federal grand jury,
Immitt admitted that he had visited 70th Precinct roll calls on each of the
three daily shifts to urge officers not to discuss the case - but not for
purposes of interfering with investigators.
</P>
<P>
	   "I didn't want anyone else involved who wasn't involved," he said.
</P>
<P>
	   U.S. District Judge Eugene Nickerson indicated he would rule Wednesday on
whether prosecutors may call unnamed witnesses who allegedly overheard Volpe say
he would "say nothin"' to implicate Schwarz.
</P>
<P>
	   Depending on the ruling, the government could wrap up its case by the
weekend.
</P>
<P>
	   Prosecutors say Volpe made the remark to Stephen Worth - then Schwarz's
lawyer - in a courthouse hallway last May 20, just days before his guilty plea.
</P>
<P>
	   "In response to Worth's apparent inquiry, Volpe responded in substance:
'Don't worry, man. I'm not going to say nothin'." Worth thanked Volpe. Volpe and
Worth then parted," Vinegrad said in a letter to Nickerson.
</P>
<P>
	   The letter did not name the witnesses but said, "Volpe would have had no
reason to indicate to Schwarz's attorney his intent to say nothing if Schwarz
had not participated in the sexual assault of Mr. Louima."
</P>
<P>
	   Bruder attorney Stuart London argued that the report was only "speculation
and wishful thinking" because it didn't include Worth's question.
</P>
<P>
	   On Tuesday, prosecutors said Worth had asked Volpe, "What are you going to
say? What are you going to do?"
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
