<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-15 17:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lockheed Does Most Defense Business  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    WASHINGTON (AP) -- Lockheed Martin Corp., maker of the F-16 fighter and
other military aircraft and weapons, ranked first in the amount of business
among defense contractors last year with $12.7 billion worth, the Pentagon said
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
	   In second place was Boeing Co., at $10.9 billion. Boeing makes a wide
variety of weapons, including the F-15 fighter. It is collaborating with
Lockheed on the next-generation Air Force fighter, the F-22 Raptor.
</P>
<P>
	   Each of the top six defense contractors in 1999 held the same position the
year before. No. 3 was Raytheon Corp, followed by General Dynamics Corp,
Northrop Grumman Corp. and United Technologies Corp.
</P>
<P>
	   Litton Industries Inc., a maker of Navy warships and provider of advanced
electronic systems to the U.S. military, moved up to No. 7 on the 1999 list with
$2.1 billion in contract awards. In 1998 it was No. 8 with $1.6 billion.
</P>
<P>
	   The eight-largest defense contractor in 1999 was General Electric Co., with
$1.7 billion.
</P>
<P>
	   Tied for 9th were TRW Inc. and Textron Inc., each with $1.4 billion.
</P>
<P>
	   The total value of defense contracts issued by the Pentagon in 1999 was $125
billion, or $6.9 billion more than the year before.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
