<P>
	   Oil Prices Fuel BP Amoco Profits
</P>
<P>
	   LONDON (AP) -- Sharply higher crude oil prices more than offset
pinched margins in the refining industry to help boost BP Amoco
PLC's fourth-quarter operating profit by 145 percent. BP Amoco
announced a quarterly profit for the period ending Dec. 31 of $2.12
billion, excluding one-time charges of $439 million. In the
fourth-quarter a year ago, BP Amoco earned $866 million. The result
was a striking turnaround from a year ago, when the Anglo-American
company's profit plunged due to a 12-year low in oil prices and the
costs of BP's buyout of Chicago-based Amoco Corp. in 1998.
</P>
<P>
	   Clinton Concerned at Heating Oil
</P>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton said today the rising cost
of home heating oil was ``deeply troubling'' for low-income
families and that the federal government may release more money to
help them warm their homes. ``I have not closed off any options,''
the president said. ``I'm monitoring this on a daily basis.'' He
spoke briefly with reporters in the Cabinet Room after crude oil
prices climbed above $30 for the first time since the eve of the
Persian Gulf War nine years ago. Clinton said there would be some
important meetings among oil-producing countries within the next
few days, and price trends may be more apparent after that.
</P>
<P>
	   Chevron To Pay $9M Tax Settlement
</P>
<P>
	   NEW ORLEANS (AP) -- Chevron has agreed to pay Louisiana $9.6
million in a settlement the state hopes will serve as a model for
its other lawsuits involving alleged severance tax underpayments.
Oil companies must pay a state tax on all oil produced, or severed,
within Louisiana. Under the settlement, Chevron will pay Louisiana
$8.7 million to resolve the claims, plus $865,000 to cover
attorneys' fees for the case. Chevron did not acknowledge violating
any laws.
</P>
<P>
	   German Official Poised for IMF Post
</P>
<P>
	   BERLIN (AP) -- European Union finance ministers look set to
propose German Deputy Finance Minister Caio Koch-Weser as the EU's
candidate for head of the International Monetary Fund. He would
succeed France's Michel Camdessus, who retired yesterday after 13
years in the post. Koch-Weser is known as a consensus-builder who
has worked in both developing ocountries and the industrialized
West. A consensus was reached after France, which has had the post
for 30 years and had been the main stumbling block, agreed to
support the German candidate, EU presidency spokesman Manuel
Meneses said.
</P>
<P>
	   Industrial Production Soars in January
</P>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Industrial production at the nation's
factories, utilities and mines surged in January to its highest
level since August 1998. The Federal Reserve reported today that
production rose by 1 percent last month, twice the 0.5 percent gain
many analysts expected. The gain covered just about all sectors.
Plants were operating at about 81.6 percent of capacity.
</P>
<P>
	   Wal-Mart's 4Q Profits Up 23 Percent
</P>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) -- Wal-Mart Stores Inc.'s fourth-quarter profits
rose 23 percent from a year ago, fueled by strong sales growth at
its U.S. superstores and operations abroad. While the results
reported today by the world's largest retailer were slightly above
expectations, its stock fell on concerns that its growth may slow
in the coming year. Wal-Mart earned $1.92 billion, or 43 cents a
share, up from 35 cents a share a year ago. Analysts' had forecast
42 cents. Quarterly sales totaled $51.39 billion, an increase of 26
percent over the $40.79 billion in the same period a year ago.
Despite its earnings showing Wall-Mart's stock was down 1 7/8 at57
today.
</P>
<P>
	   Clinton Taking Up Web Security
</P>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Following last week's attacks on Internet web
sites by hackers, President Clinton today began exploring ways to
tighten security on the World Wide Web. But he also said the
attacks were not a major disaster like the Japanese attack on Pearl
Harbor in World War II. He pictured hacking as part of the price
people have to pay for the success of the Internet. Clinton met
with Web experts at the White House.
</P>
<P>
