<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-15 17:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cities seek consolidation of services for survival  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - Upstate New York's largest cities that helped drive
a young America must be redesigned quickly into a compact model, or else.
<P>
	   The mayors of Buffalo, Syracuse, Rochester and Albany argued that point at
the Capitol Tuesday. They said the cities need $85 million now, but more
importantly require long-term, fundamental changes like sharing the cost of
services with other governments.
</P>
<P>
	   "New York state has got to modernize its ability to provide services," said
Buffalo Mayor Anthony Masiello. If not, "Upstate New York is going to collapse,
I'll tell you right now."
</P>
<P>
	   They said the need is as stark as a tax bill.
</P>
<P>
	   In Rochester, a typical family with a median household income of $23,000 a
year pays about $700 in city taxes. If the state doesn't come across with the
aid and changes pushed by the mayors, that bill would be $1,200, or almost three
weeks full paychecks before taxes, according to figures provided by the city.
</P>
<P>
	   As for business, increasing local tax bills are partly to blame for the loss
of a couple hundred Rochester jobs - 40 percent of the work force - at the
Genesee brewery, city officials said.
</P>
<P>
	   The mayors' pitch for fundamental changes include consolidating services
with counties and other municipalities and reducing the size of city governments
that now operate as entities separate of their counties and the towns they
border. The mayors who serve nearly 800,000 residents told the state Senate
Committee on Cities that the "revolutionary" changes should be intiated and
pressured by the state over two to four years.
</P>
<P>
	   "If we continue to go in the direction we are going we will displace our
troubles," said Albany Mayor Gerald Jennings. He said the rising costs of
services while urban populations and tax bases dwindle is compounding Albany's
deficit of about $9.5 million, where three-quarters of property is tax exempt.
</P>
<P>
	   "I can't cut anymore," said Syracuse Mayor Roy Bernardi. "If we have to cut
it's in police, fire and schools."
</P>
<P>
	   In a time of state government surpluses, windfalls from settlements with
tobacco companies, a new $9 billion Health Care Reform program, and growing
suburbs boasting no town taxes, the four upstate cities face a combined deficit
of more than $73 million.
</P>
<P>
	   "The state has left us scrounging around for crumbs," said Rochester Mayor
William Johnson Jr. "You can't revitalize upstate if you don't revitalize the
cities."
</P>
<P>
	   Tax credits to help businesses locate in upstate cities is part of Gov.
George Pataki's Upstate Economic Agenda. Pataki announced the $700 million
package of tax cuts and incentives aimed at attracting jobs.
</P>
<P>
	   "Private sector employment in upstate New York is at an all-time high and
unemployment remains at or below the national average," Pataki said at a
Binghamton high-tech firm. "But we must do more to ensure every upstate
community shares in our strong economy and our record employment levels."
</P>
<P>
	   The fundamental changes of regionalization pushed by the mayors have been
promoted for years, yet rarely implemented. The benefits, however, would ripple
beyond city lines into the relatively prosperous suburbs, the mayors argued.
</P>
<P>
	   "There's no question, if the cities are strong, the regions will be," said
Marvin LeRoy, a former supervisor of one of those prosperous suburbs, in a
separate interview. "The lion's share of businesses are still in the cities.
</P>
<P>
	   "Our affluence and wealth is from the cities," said LeRoy, a Republican who
stepped down in December after eight years of running the the Saratoga County
town of Clifton Park. The town has 35,000 people, new housing development, new
businesses and no town tax. He served on a state regionalization commission that
"died on the vine" from a lack of action.
</P>
<P>
	   But it's worked in Atlanta, Charlotte, N.C., and other cities, he said.
</P>
<P>
	   In addition to the long-term changes, the mayors called for about $85
million in funding in the state budget now being written. That, they said, would
help offset huge property tax increases that would erode the confidence in
upstate New York businesses seek.
</P>
<P>
	   The mayors also seek:
</P>
<P>
	   -Unfettered and free use of schools after 3 p.m. for civic and recreation
programs in part to deter juvenile crime that peaks from 3:30 p.m. to 7:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
	   -Allowing more city projects to be exempt from paying government-set
"prevailing" wages to contractors.
</P>
<P>
	   -An official role on local school boards from which they could affect labor
negotiations and policy.
</P>
<P>
	   "We need New York state to initiate structural changes," Masiello said.
"We're in the battle for our lives."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
