<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thomson Newspapers Put Up for Sale  </HEADLINE>
    By SETH SUTEL AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) -- The Thomson Corp. is selling its U.S. newspapers business,
comprised mainly of 49 local and regional dailies, in order to concentrate on
the professional information services that make up the vast majority of the
Canadian company's operations.
</P>
<P>
	   Thomson is keeping its flagship newspaper The Globe and Mail. Published out
of Thomson's home base of Toronto, it serves as a major national daily for
Canada, going up against the year-old newspaper launched by Conrad Black, The
National Post.
</P>
<P>
	   It was the latest divestiture for Thomson, following the sale of a British
travel business in 1998 and an oil and gas business in 1989. Thomson has also
sold several of its smaller newspapers over the past few years as part of an
effort to increase the consolidation of papers in regional clusters.
</P>
<P>
	   Investors welcomed the announcement, pushing Thomson's shares up 12.5
percent on the Toronto Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
	   The dailies being sold are small; most have circulations of less than
50,000. Thomson is also putting up for sale five dailies in Canada and more than
75 nondaily newspapers, most of which are based in the United States.
</P>
<P>
	   Altogether the newspapers being sold account for less than 15 percent of the
company's business.
</P>
<P>
	   Dick Harrington, president and CEO of Thomson, said the company reached the
decision to put the papers up for sale after deciding to concentrate on business
and professional information services that could be delivered electronically.
</P>
<P>
	   "After we sold the travel business in 1998, we were really an information
company that had an interest in newspapers," Harrington said in an interview.
"Now we're going after the business-to-business and business professional market
that's global in scope and electronic in nature."
</P>
<P>
	   Thomson's main business is selling specialized legal, professional and
educational materials, about half of which is delivered electronically. It has a
major legal and regulatory research arm, West Group, and a large business
providing scientific and health care research to academics and other
professionals.
</P>
<P>
	   Increasingly, Thomson has focused on products that can be delivered
electronically instead of in print, such as textbooks.
</P>
<P>
	   Thomson also operates a financial information service that includes First
Call, a service widely used by Wall Street analysts to disseminate research
about companies to investors.
</P>
<P>
	   Stuart Garner, president of Thomson Newspapers, said several parties had
already expressed interest on Tuesday after the announcement was made. Lee
Westerfield, a publishing analyst at PaineWebber, said he expected the
newspapers could fetch a price of about 10 times cash flow, which would be more
than $2 billion.
</P>
<P>
	   Garner said the company hoped to complete the sale in as few transactions as
possible, adding that the company was not inclined to break up the geographic
concentrations around which the newspapers had been grouped.
</P>
<P>
	   The U.S. newspapers have been grouped into 21 regional clusters, the largest
being in Ohio, Wisconsin and Indiana. The titles being sold include the
Connecticut Post, The Tribune of Mesa, Arizona and The Post-Crescent, Appleton,
Wisconsin.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
