<HEADLINE> Palladium Soars; Pork Falls  </HEADLINE>
    By MARTHA IRVINE Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   Speculation that China will buy more U.S. soybeans -- perhaps more than
200,000 metric tons -- boosted soybean futures prices on the Chicago Board of
Trade Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
	   On other markets, pork prices continued to fall, while palladium
skyrocketed.
</P>
<P>
	   Earlier in the day, soybean futures had fallen on news that several inches
of rain drenched key growing regions in Brazil on Monday. Traders expected the
rain would boost the supply and drive prices lower once crops are harvested.
</P>
<P>
	   But soybean prices rebounded later in the day on news of a potential deal
with China -- giving a smaller boost to corn futures prices, which also had
fallen earlier in the day.
</P>
<P>
	   China has already bought smaller amounts of U.S. soybeans but has yet to
reveal further import plans.
</P>
<P>
	   "The thought is that China may be interested in buying more," said Don
Roose, president of Iowa-based U.S. Commodities Inc.
</P>
<P>
	   Wheat, however, did not benefit from the rally, with futures finishing the
day mostly lower. Analysts say forecasts for rain in the Plains states played a
role in pressuring prices.
</P>
<P>
	   Wheat for March delivery fell 2 3/4 cents to $2.66 a bushel; March corn
broke even at $2.22 1/4 a bushel; March oats fell  1/2 cent to $1.08 3/4 a
bushel; and March soybeans jumped 3 3/4 cents to $5.08 3/4 a bushel.
</P>
<P>
	   On the Chicago Mercantile Exchange, live hog and pork belly futures
continued to fall Tuesday. Analysts say the downward trend is a sign that
generally healthy futures prices are not in line with consumer demand.
</P>
<P>
	   That's particularly true of pork belly prices, which are high for this time
of year, said Charles Levitt, a livestock analyst for Chicago-based Alaron
Trading Corp.
</P>
<P>
	   "A lot of it has to be wrung out," Levitt said, predicting that the pork
market will continue to be somewhat volatile in the days to come.
</P>
<P>
	   At the end of trading Tuesday, April lean hogs fell 1.38 cents to 56.02
cents a pound; and March pork bellies fell 1.93 cents to 83.32 cents a pound;
April live cattle remained unchanged at 70.62 cents a pound; and March feeder
cattle fell .35 cent to 82.87 cents a pound.
</P>
<P>
	   Continued concern over supplies caused March palladium to jump nearly 9
percent. Russia is the leading producer of the metal used to make catalytic
converters for cars but has been lagging in exports.
</P>
<P>
	   March palladium rose $52.85 to $658.35 an ounce on the New York Mercantile
Exchange -- a third consecutive all-time high.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
