<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-15 18:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Community wants officer tried in court  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) - Citing their own private investigation, leaders
of Hartford's North End community on Tuesday again called for the indictment of
a city police officer in April's fatal shooting of a 14-year-old mugging
suspect.
<P>
	   A special prosecutor's report, and his decision on whether to charge Officer
Robert Allan is expected this week.
</P>
<P>
	   Black community leaders gathered in Mount Olive Church to urge that the
decision be greeted with calm. But they also reaffirmed their strong desire to
see Allan tried in court, be it state or federal.
</P>
<P>
	   "The case should be put before a court and jury and they should be allowed
to decide in accordance with the laws under which we are all governed," said
minister Wadell Muhammad.
</P>
<P>
	   Allan, who is white, has said he thought he heard gunshots and believed the
boy was reaching for a weapon when he shot him in the early morning hours of
April 13 as the teen and others were fleeing police.
</P>
<P>
	   Muhammad said the group's own investigation turned up several witnesses
whose names were forwarded to New London State's Attorney Kevin Kane, the
special prosecutor.
</P>
<P>
	   "We have reason to believe that all of these witnesses in this incident have
not been interviewed by the State's Attorney's Office," said Muhammad.
</P>
<P>
	   One witness saw Aquan had his hands in the air and was not reaching for
anything, Muhammad said.
</P>
<P>
	   The group would not discuss the specifics of their findings. They said they
were waiting to see Kane's report, to compare the two. Calls to Kane's office
were not returned Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
	   "We're not judging anything to date. They may have something we don't have.
We want to have an opportunity to review what they found, evaluate it, discuss
it as a group and community and come up with a decision of what action we need
to take at that point," said Larry Charles, executive director of ONE/CHANE a
neighborhood improvement group.
</P>
<P>
	   He said should Kane fail to indict Allan, the group could bring the case to
federal officials.
</P>
<P>
	   Charles said leaders also want to send a strong message specifically to the
community's youth, that regardless of the outcome of Kane's report, they must
not react with violence.
</P>
<P>
	   "It's not over. There are still options available to us," said Charles.
</P>
<P>
	   Community leaders also strongly criticized the irregular use of a grand jury
system in Connecticut. Most decisions to bring charges rest solely with a
prosecutor.
</P>
<P>
	   "This places an undue burden on a prosecutor because he or she relies on the
testimony of police officers in order to do their job every day," said Muhammad.
</P>
<P>
	   Since 1985, fewer than 10 cases have gone before a grand jury, including the
high-profile Martha Moxley murder case in Greenwich.
</P>
<P>
	   Under state law, prosecutors must file an application with a panel of judges
to request a grand jury and demonstrate that other investigative procedures have
failed. The single-person grand jury used in Connecticut doesn't technically
indict a suspect but can recommend whether there is enough evidence to warrant
an arrest.
</P>
<P>
	   City councilwoman Elizabeth Horton Sheff said regardless of the special
prosecutor's ruling she will urge that Allan be dismissed from the Hartford
police department.
</P>
<P>
	   "He is, not prepared, in my opinion, to serve as a sworn peace officer in
this city," she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-02-15-00 1810 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000215.0205 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-15 18:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> House OKs Computer Research Bill  </HEADLINE>
   By JANELLE CARTER Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The House passed a $6.9 billion measure Tuesday aimed at
expanding the government's role in computer and scientific research and
maintaining the nation's role as a technology leader.
</P>
<P>
	   The bill, which passed by voice vote, would almost double the amount spent
on technology research last year. Over the next five years, it would funnel
millions more into research projects that include ways to speed up the Internet
and how to integrate computing and medical research.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Maintaining the nation's global leadership in information technology is
not a given,'' said Rep. F. James Sensenbrenner Jr., R-Wis., chairman of the
House Science Committee. ``This bipartisan legislation demonstrates a commitment
to upholding our nation's preeminence.''
</P>
<P>
	   Rep. Nick Smith, R-Mich., said past successes are not enough to ``keep pace
and ahead of a world that is dedicated to matching us.''
</P>
<P>
	   ``The current boom in information technology is based on the basic research
carried out more than 15 years ago,'' Smith said. ``There is an urgent need to
replenish the knowledge base.''
</P>
<P>
	   Lawmakers have noted that the Internet was based largely on technology
developed in the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
	   The bill would authorize the money to be spent over the next five years by
several agencies, including the National Science Foundation, NASA and the
Environmental Protection Agency.
</P>
<P>
	   In addition to providing money to increase technology research, the bill
includes $95 million for mathematics and science research internships for
college students.
</P>
<P>
	   The measure now goes to the Senate.
</P>
<P>
	   ``By investing in research and development and these programs today, we are
investing in our future economic potential as a nation,'' said Rep. James Moran,
D-Va.
</P>
<P>
	   The research is designed to supplement advances already being made by the
private sector. The government's initiative would focus on basic fundamental
research, costly projects that may take years of study. Often, private industry
focuses more on short-term developments that can deliver a quick profit.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I think 20 years from now, as historians look back, they will view this as
probably the most single important piece of legislation that the Congress
considers,'' said Sensenbrenner. ``America will have made a commitment to the
information technology research we need to continue ... as number one in this
area.''
</P>
<P>
	   ------
</P>
<P>
	   EDITOR'S NOTE -- The bill is H.R. 2086.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
