<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-15 18:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> School owner emerges as Skakel's biggest defender  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   GREENWICH, Conn. (AP) - Michael Skakel once described the Elan School as
a "concentration camp for kids," a place where he claimed he was beaten and
abused.
<P>
	   But now, more than 20 years after Skakel was treated for alcoholism at Elan,
school cofounder Joseph Ricci has emerged as Skakel's biggest defender and
perhaps his best hope for beating charges he killed Greenwich teen-ager Martha
Moxley in 1975.
</P>
<P>
	   Ricci disputes critical elements of the prosecution's case against Skakel,
the 39-year-old nephew of Robert and Ethel Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
	   Ricci challenges allegations by former Elan students who claim that Skakel -
a student from 1978 to 1980 - confessed to killing Moxley in October 1975, when
they were both 15.
</P>
<P>
	   The killing took place in the exclusive Belle Haven neighborhood of
Greenwich, where Moxley and Skakel were neighbors. Moxley was beaten with a
6-iron that was matched to a set of golf clubs owned by the Skakels.
</P>
<P>
	   Ricci claims that although the Moxley murder was discussed at the school
during Skakel's therapy, no confession was ever made.
</P>
<P>
	   His account finds support among some former Elan students, but conflicts
with what investigators have heard from others.
</P>
<P>
	   One former student recently interviewed by The Hartford Courant said he
never heard that Skakel confessed, either publicly or privately.
</P>
<P>
	   Another student, according to the transcript of a 1996 interview, said he
learned in the early 1990s that Skakel may have confessed privately to his
roommate.
</P>
<P>
	   Still another student, according to investigators, claims to have heard
Skakel privately admit guilt.
</P>
<P>
	   Ricci discounts such incriminating statements, attributing them to the lure
of reward money.
</P>
<P>
	   "I'd like to see Martha Moxley's mother get closure because I have two
children of my own, but this is a big lie," Ricci said.
</P>
<P>
	   Skakel was committed to Elan in 1978 at age 17 by his father, Rushton
Skakel, following a drunken driving incident in New York. He spent two years at
Elan, which was licensed to treat teen-agers with substance abuse and behavioral
problems.
</P>
<P>
	   Ricci said Skakel was confronted by peers and counselors about his suspected
involvement in Moxley's murder, but school officials made Skakel aware that
juvenile laws at the time would have resulted in him being imprisoned only until
the age of 18.
</P>
<P>
	   "It's illogical for him not to have come forward back then," Ricci said.
</P>
<P>
	   Stories that Skakel had publicly confessed to the killing while at Elan were
first alleged by Sutton Associates, an investigative firm hired in 1992 by the
Skakel family.
</P>
<P>
	   Leaked in 1995, the report revealed that the two brothers had changed their
stories regarding their whereabouts on the night Moxley was killed. A former
Elan student and worker, Dan Benison, claimed Skakel had talked about the murder
during a therapy session, Sutton investigators said.
</P>
<P>
	   Separately Tuesday, the Greenwich Time reported that some physical evidence
in the murder investigation may be missing, although it may not figure in the
prosecution of Skakel.
</P>
<P>
	   Citing sources knowledgeable of the investigation, the newspaper said a pair
of red-stained dungarees and sneakers that belonged to Skakel are missing.
</P>
<P>
	   Police records indicate that the red stains on the pants and sneakers were
found to be zinc oxide boat paint.
</P>
<P>
	   Skakel was arrested Jan. 19, more than 24 years after Moxley's killing. His
arraignment is scheduled for March 14.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-02-15-00 1813 </TRAILER>
