<HEADLINE> Bonds Fall in Light Trading  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    NEW YORK (AP) -- Bond prices were mostly lower in light trading Tuesday as
investors cashed in on gains made during the two previous sessions.
</P>
<P>
	   Analysts said investors took some profits but essentially traded cautiously
in advance of Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan's congressional testimony,
scheduled Thursday before the House Banking Committee.
</P>
<P>
	   The price of the 30-year Treasury bond fell 9/32 point, or $2.81 per $1,000
in face value. Its yield, which moves in the opposite direction of price, rose
to 6.24 percent from 6.22 percent late Monday.
</P>
<P>
	   In addition to Greenspan's upcoming testimony, bond traders were also
keeping a cautious eye on surging oil prices, which added to inflation worries.
Crude oil climbed above $30 a barrel on Monday for the first time since the eve
of the Persian Gulf War and remained about $30 on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
	   Prices of short-term Treasury securities were unchanged to down 1/16 point
Tuesday, while intermediate maturities fell  1/8 point or were unchanged,
according to Bridge Telerate.
</P>
<P>
	   In other trading Tuesday, yields on three-month Treasury bills were 5.73
percent, with the discount rising 0.06 percentage point from Monday's auction to
5.57 percent. Six-month yields were 6.00 percent as the discount fell 0.02
percent from the weekly auction to 5.74 percent. One-year yields finished
unchanged at 6.16 percent, with the discount holding at Monday's late rate of
5.81 percent.
</P>
<P>
	   Yields are the interest bonds pay by maturity, while the discount is the
interest at which they are sold.
</P>
<P>
	   The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between banks, rose
to 5.88 percent from 5.81 percent late Monday.
</P>
<P>
	   The Bond Buyer index of municipal bonds rose 1/16 point to 92 5/32. The
yield was unchanged at 6.24 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
