<HEADLINE> Dollar Finishes Mixed  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    NEW YORK (AP) -- The dollar rose against the yen on Tuesday, but fell
against the euro and the British pound.
</P>
<P>
	   In late New York trading, the euro was quoted at 98.12 cents, up from 97.96
cents at the same point on Monday. The dollar, meanwhile, was trading at 109.05
Japanese yen, up from late Monday's quote of 108.83 yen.
</P>
<P>
	   The advance against the yen, came amid worries about the strength of the
Japanese economy. The Japan economy has been recovering of late, but there are
questions related to its sustainability.
</P>
<P>
	   Currency markets have been quiet this week ahead of U.S. Federal Reserve
Board Chairman Alan Greenspan's testimony before Congress scheduled for
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
	   In other trading, the dollar was quoted at 1.6366 Swiss francs, down from
1.6402 on Friday, and 1.4569 Canadian dollars, down from 1.4576. The British
pound rose to $1.5964 compared with late Monday's quote of $1.5878.
</P>
<P>
	   The currencies of the 11 countries participating in the euro are no longer
traded separately and are tied to the euro by a fixed rate.
</P>
<P>
	   Based on Monday's euro rate, the dollar was worth: 1.9931 German marks, down
from 1.9949 late Monday; 6.6846 French francs, down from 6.6907; and 1,973.17
Italian lire, down from 1,974.98.
</P>
</TEXT>
