<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-15 18:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gillette May Sell Stationery Units  </HEADLINE>
    By TOM KIRCHOFER AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   BOSTON (AP) -- Gillette Co. shares gained 4 percent Tuesday after the
company said it may dispose of its struggling stationery products business to
concentrate on its better-performing razors and batteries.
</P>
<P>
	   Although it has well-known brands, the Paper Mate, Parker and Waterman pen
lines have been a drag on Gillette's earnings, with profit from the stationery
business dropping 89 percent in the fourth quarter of last year.
</P>
<P>
	   Analysts said the stationery business just didn't fit well with Gillette's
shaving products and Duracell batteries.
</P>
<P>
	   "It strikes at core competencies. What businesses are you in?" said Ira R.
Weiss, dean of the College of Business Administration at Northeastern
University. "It seems to me that pens are a business to get out of."
</P>
<P>
	   Pens and related products accounted for about 7.5 percent of Gillette's $10
billion in sales last year.
</P>
<P>
	   Gillette got into the business in 1955 when it bought the Paper Mate brand.
Liquid Paper correction fluid was added in 1979, and the company bought the
Waterman pen maker in 1987 and the Parker pen brand in 1993.
</P>
<P>
	   But the sector has stumbled. In addition to the dismal fourth-quarter
profits, quarterly stationery sales fell 17 percent. For all of last year
stationery sales were down 13 percent and profits were off 83 percent from 1998
levels.
</P>
<P>
	   Earlier this week, Gillette confirmed that it has retained Merrill Lynch to
assist in a review of its alternatives for the stationery business. The company
will only say a decision will be made "early this year."
</P>
<P>
	   "We're looking at several options. Divestiture is one of those options,
spinning it off is an option, as is retaining it," said Eric A. Kraus, the
company's spokesman.
</P>
<P>
	   Gillette also makes lines of toiletries, and it owns the Oral-B brand of
dental care products and Duracell batteries. The company makes Braun household
products which have also been faltering of late, and some followers of the
company have suggested that line should be disposed of as well.
</P>
<P>
	   The battery business is currently one of the strongest elements in
Gillette's portfolio, while the personal hygiene products at least have some
marketing and distribution similarities with Gillette's market-dominating razors
and blades.
</P>
<P>
	   But pens -- especially the deluxe Waterman and Parker brands -- have a hard
time fitting in with such a stable of products, said Fredric E. Russell, head of
Fredric E. Russell Investment Management Co., a Tulsa, Okla., money management
firm that has stock in Gillette.
</P>
<P>
	   "When people think of consuming blades, they also think of consuming on the
same shopping trips toothpaste and things like that, but not pens," Russell
said. "These are very good, smart strategic moves to sell off the stationery."
</P>
<P>
	   Russell said it was not clear how much of a premium the stationery business
would fetch.
</P>
<P>
	   "They may not get a fire sale price, but they're not going to get a price
driven by euphoria either," he said. "They're not selling at the peak, but they
are making a good decision."
</P>
<P>
	   Gillette's stock, listed on the New York Stock Exchange, gained $1.50
Tuesday to $38.25 a share as of 4:30 p.m. EST. The stock has fallen sharply from
its March 1999 52-week high of $64.37 1/2, but Weiss thought selling off the
stationery business would put Gillette on the road to reconciliation with Wall
Street.
</P>
<P>
	   "Clearly the stockholders on Wall Street are not looking favorably on them,
although Gillette has been the star for ages for ongoing continued growth,"
Weiss said. "The street is going to look kindly at getting rid of those pens.
You're getting rid of a drag on profits."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
