<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-15 18:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New York state's highest court hears commuter tax case  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - The state Legislature and Gov. George Pataki made a
"sham" of the lawmaking process when they rescinded a lucrative New York City
tax to help candidates in a state Senate election, a lawyer for the city argued
Tuesday.
<P>
	   Elizabeth Freedman, an assistant corporation counsel, told the seven-member
state Court of Appeals that state leaders eliminated the city's "commuter" tax
for "frivolous and truly insignificant reasons."
</P>
<P>
	   The members of the state's highest court would be justified in undoing the
tax rescinder, she argued, because of the political motivation behind passage of
the state law. She also contended that technically, the state did not have the
authority to rescind the tax because it had not been formally asked to do so by
the New York City Counsel in a "home rule" message.
</P>
<P>
	   But Freedman's arguments prompted some sharp questioning from Court of
Appeals judges.
</P>
<P>
	   Judge Howard Levine told her, "You're suggesting that we're going to test
the credibility of the statements by (legislative) sponsors, statements in
debates? We're going to say they're disingenuous?"
</P>
<P>
	   And Judge Joseph Bellacosa said by using such words as "sham" and
"legitimate," Freedman was asking the court to get into "some heady waters"
where the judges were being asked to interpret not only the legality of what
legislators did, but their motivations for doing so, too.
</P>
<P>
	   Also Tuesday, lawyers for New Jersey and Connecticut asked the court to find
it unconstitutional for New York to waive the commuter tax for New York state
residents who live outside the five boroughs, but to charge it to residents of
Connecticut, New Jersey or Pennsylvania who work in New York City.
</P>
<P>
	   "We are dealing with fundamental, profound, significant principles,"
Connecticut Attorney General Richard Blumenthal said. "This is precisely the
kind of levy, indeed, that our constitutional framers sought to prevent.
Disparate treatment. Discriminatory burden. Unfair treatment."
</P>
<P>
	   New Jersey's deputy attorney general, Patrick DeAlmeida, called on the Court
of Appeals to order refunds of the commuter tax to out-of-staters.
</P>
<P>
	   "The state has hundreds of millions of dollars that it's going to keep from
out-of-state residents, interest free," DeAlmeida said. "It has had it for some
time and there is no justification for the state to have an interest-free loan
on the back of out-of-state residents under a clearly unconstitutional statute."
</P>
<P>
	   The Court of Appeals is expected to issue a written ruling within six weeks.
The judges have promised to handle the case - various earlier legal actions
against the commuter tax were consolidated into one case for reasons of the
appeal - in an expedited fashion.
</P>
<P>
	   Both friends and foes of rescinding the commuter tax agree that its demise
was precipitated by local politics.
</P>
<P>
	   As part of a tough special election race to fill a vacant state Senate seat
in New York City's northern suburbs, the Democratic candidate stated that if
elected, he would not vote to extend the commuter tax. Republican candidate
Thomas Morahan - the eventual winner - said he would go one better and work to
repeal the tax altogether.
</P>
<P>
	   To the dismay of New York City Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, the Legislature and
Pataki quickly did away with the tax, even before the special election was held.
</P>
<P>
	   Pataki said he and the Legislature did the right thing and it's time to move
on.
</P>
<P>
	   "I think the commuter tax is gone," Pataki said Tuesday at an appearance at
a high-tech research center in Albany. "I think it's a good thing that will help
the state's economy and certainly help the city's economy. People will no longer
have a reason to avoid working or having their office located in New York City."
</P>
<P>
	   The case puts Giuliani, who is expected to run for Senate against Hillary
Rodham Clinton this November, in the somewhat uncomfortable position of pursuing
a court case to make hundreds of thousands of commuters - and potential voters
in a Senate election - pay a tax to the city.
</P>
<P>
	   "I have the advantage and disadvantage of holding a public office that is
one of the most difficult in the country," he said Monday when asked about the
case. "The things that I did as mayor of New York City to protect the people of
New York City I would equally as strongly and equally as well do to protect the
people of the state of New York."
</P>
<P>
	   Some 300,000 commuters from surrounding states work in New York City daily.
About 500,000 others come in from New York counties outside the five boroughs.
The city's 0.45 percent income tax totals $450 on an income of $100,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
	   A complete repeal could cost the city as much as $360 million a year;
repealing the tax only for New York residents would cost $210 million a year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
