<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-15 18:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Anti-smoking Ads Pulled Over Taste  </HEADLINE>
    By SKIP WOLLENBERG AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) -- The organization created to mount the biggest U.S.
anti-smoking campaign ever has pulled two of its first four edgy commercials
after complaints arose from the world's biggest cigarette maker, a TV network
and some state attorneys general.
</P>
<P>
	   One of the pulled ads showed young people stacking "body bags" on the
sidewalk outside a tobacco company building, while the other showed teens
equipped with a lie detector trying to get into a tobacco company's offices to
quiz sales executives about smoking's addictiveness.
</P>
<P>
	   The building was not specifically identified in either ad but the
commercials were filmed inside and outside the Philip Morris Cos. headquarters
in Manhattan. In addition to complaints from Philip Morris and several state
attorneys general, the CBS television network refused to run the two ads.
</P>
<P>
	   The ads are part of a $1.5 billion anti-smoking campaign being financed with
proceeds from the industry's huge 1998 settlement with the states over claims
for reimbursement for treating sick smokers.
</P>
<P>
	   An organization called the American Legacy Foundation was created to oversee
anti-smoking advertising and educational efforts, and last week it began running
the first commercials in the campaign developed by a team of agencies led by
Arnold Communications of Boston.
</P>
<P>
	   The two remaining ads in the initial series of four parodied soft drink and
sneaker commercials, showing one of three product users being unexpectedly
vaporized. The message: "Only one product actually kills a third of the people
who use it. Tobacco."
</P>
<P>
	   But it was the other two ads that drew fire. The 1,200 "body bags" stuffed
with paper and stacked near the tobacco offices in one ad run on the USA Network
this past weekend was supposed to stand for people who die each day from
tobacco-related illness.
</P>
<P>
	   The teenage interrogators in the "Lie Detector" ad that ran on the cable
network Comedy Central late last week wound up being escorted to the door by a
security guard.
</P>
<P>
	   Cheryl Healton, the president and chief executive of the foundation, said
Tuesday the foundation's board held a teleconference meeting Monday and voted
without objection to take the ads temporarily out of the rotation. She said
efforts would be made to see if the ads could be reworked.
</P>
<P>
	   "It is obvious we pushed a number of buttons and we are going to keep
pushing buttons," Healton said.
</P>
<P>
	   But she said "concerns were raised from a variety of sectors" about the two
ads and addressing the controversy was starting to take too much of her time.
</P>
<P>
	   Philip Morris, the maker of the top-selling brand Marlboro, had said last
week that it was disappointed with the "Lie Detector" commercial and the Web
site created for the anti-smoking campaign and said it was weighing its options.
</P>
<P>
	   It noted that the settlement agreement creating the anti-smoking campaign
specified that the fund wouldn't be used for personal attacks on an individual
or company, and said Tuesday it was pleased the ads had been withdrawn.
</P>
<P>
	   The CBS television network refused to run the "Lie Detector" and "Body Bag"
ads because "we feel they crossed the line," CBS spokesman Dana McLintock said
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
	   The foundation remains in negotiations with CBS and other networks about
taking its other ads, Healton said.
</P>
<P>
	   Attorney General Christine Gregoire of Washington, who led the states in the
1998 negotiations with the tobacco industry and chairs the American Legacy
Foundation, said through a spokesman that several attorneys general she did not
name had also raised objections about the two ads.
</P>
<P>
	   "This is a distraction from the goal: to stop 3,000 kids a day from becoming
addicted to tobacco," she said. "It was not worth being distracted by one or two
ads with others in the arsenal."
</P>
<P>
	   One of the attorneys general who objected to the ads was Michael F. Easley
of North Carolina, who was among the state negotiators during the tobacco talks.
</P>
<P>
	   In a letter distributed last week to the attorneys general who signed the
agreement, Easley said "there is little question that they can be fairly viewed
as personally attacking or vilifying the tobacco companies, something that all
of us who sat around the negotiating table in New York agreed we would not do."
</P>
<P>
	   "All of the states that signed the agreement rightly expect the tobacco
companies to live up to the commitments they made to us. If we hope to have this
agreement honored, we must do likewise," he wrote in the letter obtained by The
Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
	   Philip Morris spokesman Brendan McCormick said the company continues to
consider its options on the Web site, which is at www.thetruth.com.
</P>
<P>
	   Tobacco critic Matthew Myers, head of the Campaign for Tobacco-Free Kids,
said even after the withdrawal of the ads, the Legacy anti-smoking campaign
still "is hard-hitting" and it bears watching whether the foundation will
continue in that direction.
</P>
<P>
	   "Hopefully this is a one-time incident in which the tobacco companies
demonstrate that they haven't really changed by threatening the foundation
whenever it produces hard-hitting ads that put the tobacco industry in a bad
light," he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
