<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-15 18:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ex-Bank of New York Exec Surrenders  </HEADLINE>
    By LARRY NEUMEISTER Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) -- A former Bank of New York executive specially trained in
money laundering detection and her husband surrendered to the FBI Tuesday with
the expectation they would plead guilty to their roles in one of the
largest-ever money-laundering scandals, a source told The Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
	   The former executive, Lucy Edwards, and her husband, Peter Berlin, were
indicted last year. Investigators allege they were involved in illegally moving
as much as $10 billion from Russia through accounts at the Bank of New York, the
nation's 16th largest bank.
</P>
<P>
	   The pair surrendered to authorities shortly after arriving in the United
States from London, said a source familiar with the investigation who would only
speak on condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
	   They were taken into custody in the company of their lawyers, and were
expected in Manhattan federal court Wednesday to plead guilty to charges related
to money laundering, the source said.
</P>
<P>
	   Investigators believe most of the laundered money came from Russian
importers trying to avoid paying taxes, though they are still looking into
whether some of the money came from criminal activity and was transferred
through accounts at the Bank of New York in order to mask its origin.
</P>
<P>
	   Authorities have said that Edwards, as head of the bank's Eastern European
operations in London, had easy access to bank accounts to engage in money
laundering, whereby crime proceeds are moved through a series of bank accounts
until they appear to be legitimate profits from legal businesses.
</P>
<P>
	   Edwards was dismissed from her job Aug. 18 after her name arose as a target
of an investigation that stretched across the globe. She was accused by the bank
of gross misconduct, violation of the bank's internal policies, falsification of
bank records and failure to cooperate with the bank's investigation.
</P>
<P>
	   Her husband was targeted by investigators after it was suspected that the
majority of the billions of dollars at stake were moved through a company he
controlled, Benex Worldwide Ltd., and other accounts in his name.
</P>
<P>
	   Investigators alleged they found nine accounts at the Bank of New York
connected to Benex or Berlin.
</P>
<P>
	   Both Berlin and Edwards, together with their partner Aleskey Volkov, were
charged by U.S. Attorney Mary Jo White in Manhattan with conspiring to operate a
wire-transfer business. Volkov remains a fugitive.
</P>
<P>
	   All three have denied the allegations.
</P>
<P>
	   The charges came in September, just a few months after Edwards made a
presentation on the latest money laundering techniques at a two-day conference
for financial executives in Riga, Latvia. Her speech was entitled "Money
Laundering: Latest Developments and Regulations."
</P>
<P>
	   In their indictment, prosecutors alleged that Edwards and Berlin conspired
from 1996 to last August to illegally transmit funds and receive deposits
without obtaining authorization from any federal or state banking agency.
</P>
<P>
	   If convicted of those charges, Edwards would face a maximum prison term of
five years and a maximum fine of $250,000 or twice the gain or loss resulting
from the crime.
</P>
<P>
	   In addition to the conspiracy charge, Berlin and Volkov face charges of
conducting an illegal money-transferring business and engaging in an illegal
banking operation. If convicted, they could face up to 15 years in prison and a
fine of $175,000 or twice the gain or loss resulting from the crime.
</P>
<P>
	   A message left with the couple's lawyers Tuesday was not immediately
returned.
</P>
<P>
	   Marvin Smilon, a spokesman for the U.S. attorney's office in Manhattan,
declined to comment as did a spokesman for the FBI in New York, which is
conducting the investigation.
</P>
<P>
	   The Bank of New York also declined to comment, though it has acknowledged
previously that it needs to improve its money-handling procedures.
</P>
<P>
	   Last week, the Bank of New York signed an agreement with the Federal Reserve
Bank of New York and the New York State Banking Department pledging to enhance
its customer screening program and report suspicious activities. It also has to
present a plan describing the steps the bank "will continue to take to
strengthen compliance with regard to anti-money laundering procedures and
suspicious activity reporting."
</P>
<P>
	   --------
</P>
<P>
	   Associated Press Writer Pat Milton contributed to this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
