<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Judge approves $8 million settlement for inmates in 1971 Attica  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) - A judge put his stamp of approval Tuesday on an
offer by New York state to pay $8 million to inmates caught up in the 1971
Attica riot, virtually settling a 25-year-old lawsuit over the nation's
deadliest prison uprising.
<P>
	   The proposed settlement "is determined to be fair, reasonable and in the
best interest ... of all parties concerned and is, therefore, preliminarily
approved," U.S. District Judge Michael Telesca said in a 27-page ruling.
</P>
<P>
	   Final approval will be withheld, he said, until claims have been filed by
all surviving inmates who claimed they were tortured, beaten and denied medical
treatment in the aftermath of the revolt and the bloody efforts by authorities
to put it down.
</P>
<P>
	   State police launched an all-out assault on the maximum-security Attica
Correctional Facility near Buffalo on Sept. 13, 1971, the fifth day of the
uprising. More than 2,000 rounds of ammunition were fired over six minutes.
</P>
<P>
	   In all, 32 inmates and 11 correction officers died, most of them killed
during the raid. Hundreds more were wounded.
</P>
<P>
	   In agreeing to settle, the state admitted no wrongdoing and agreed to pay
the inmates' lawyers $4 million in legal fees and costs. The original
class-action lawsuit in 1974 sought $100 million in damages.
</P>
<P>
	   Of the 1,281 inmates who were in prison yard "D" when police stormed the
prison, hundreds have since died and no more than 500 were expected to file
claims. By year's end, the judge will divide up the money between them - most of
them former inmates in their 50s or older.
</P>
<P>
	   A lawyer for the former inmates Ellen Yackman said, "The legal team is
extremely gratified and relieved that the last chapter of this very long and
tedious process of bringing justice to the Attica plaintiffs has now finally
begun."
</P>
<P>
	   With one exception, more than a dozen former inmates spoke in favor of the
deal at a hearing held Monday to give claimants a chance to object to the terms
of the settlement.
</P>
<P>
	   Joseph McKee of Rochester, who testified that he was repeatedly beaten and
had four teeth knocked out, said it was time to "get it over with."
</P>
<P>
	   Attica's lesson could turn out to be that "even though you are in prison, at
least you can be treated like a human being," said one of the revolt's leaders,
Frank Smith, 66.
</P>
<P>
	   Smith, a convicted robber who was freed in 1973, was forced to lie on a
table while officers beat and burned him. He was also ordered to hold a football
under his chin and threatened with death if he allowed it to fall.
</P>
<P>
	   Hours after the prison was recaptured, inmates were forced to run naked
through a gantlet of law enforcement officers who hit them with clubs and
nightsticks.
</P>
<P>
	   In 1997, a federal jury awarded $4 million to Smith and $75,000 to David
Brosig, another inmate who was injured. Telesca was brought into the case in
August when an appeals court reversed those verdicts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
