<HEADLINE> Holbrooke Pushes UN Force in Congo  </HEADLINE>
   By DAVID BRISCOE Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- U.N. Ambassador Richard Holbrooke appealed to Congress on
Tuesday to support a new force of peacekeepers for Congo -- a force that would
not include U.S. troops.
</P>
<P>
	   ``It is imperative that we fulfill our responsibility to help,'' Holbrooke
told a hearing of the House International Relations subcommittee on Africa.
``The time has come for the U.N. to take the next steps for peace in Congo.''
</P>
<P>
	   The United States has proposed an initial force of 5,537. It would include
protective troops for a corps of 500 military observers to monitor a cease-fire
agreement signed last summer between the main groups engaged in the conflict,
which has drawn in several African nations.
</P>
<P>
	   Congress must authorize the money before the United States can vote for the
increased U.N. presence in Central Africa. Holbrooke said he expects a Security
Council vote no earlier than Feb. 23 on a resolution dealing with the crisis.
</P>
<P>
	   That proposed resolution, which would require Congo's warring sides to
ensure the monitors' safety, represents the first major step in the proposed
deployment of a full-fledged peacekeeping force.
</P>
<P>
	   Rwanda and Uganda are supporting rebels who launched an insurrection in
August 1998 to oust President Laurent Kabila, who is backed by Zimbabwe, Namibia
and Angola.
</P>
<P>
	   Holbrooke said the peacekeepers would be allowed to use force to protect
themselves and civilians under immediate threat of violence.
</P>
<P>
	   He said dispatching the force is part of a three-phase U.N. plan to bring
peace to Congo.
</P>
<P>
	   The first phase included just 90 U.N. military liaison officers in Congo and
other capitals involved in the conflict. The extent of the third phase has yet
to be determined.
</P>
<P>
	   ``No U.S. peacekeeping troops would be on the ground as part of this
operation,'' Holbrooke assured the panel.
</P>
<P>
	   He said the United Nations would not taken any enforcement responsibility
and would not forcibly disarm ``nonstate actors'' in the conflict.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The U.S. has an interest in upholding regional stability and in preventing
the resurgence of genocide and mass killing in Central Africa,'' Holbrooke said.
</P>
<P>
	   He said the operation involves risks. But if the conflict is allowed to
fester, Holbrooke said, it will be even more difficult to promote stability in
Angola, Burundi, Rwanda, Uganda and Sudan.
</P>
<P>
	   He said instability in Congo also has drawn in ``rogue states'' such as
Libya, Iran, North Korea, Cuba and Sudan, who he said want to use the region for
weapons sales, terrorist bases and access to uranium and diamonds.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The current conflict is the most violent in Africa, with enormous costs to
U.S. political and economic interests,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
