<HEADLINE> Britain Aviation Deal Sought  </HEADLINE>
   By ClAUDE R. MARX Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Transportation Secretary Rodney E. Slater pledged Tuesday
to continue pushing the British government to allow more flights to Britain by
U.S. carriers but did not endorse retaliatory actions suggested by some
lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
	   House Transportation Committee Chairman Bud Shuster, R-Pa., and the
committee's ranking Democrat, James Oberstar of Minnesota, suggested Slater
consider such steps as withdrawing landing rights for the Concorde and revoking
``slots'' allotted to British carriers at U.S. airports.
</P>
<P>
	   Slater said such steps ``were under consideration'' by the administration
but he gave no indication that any action was imminent.
</P>
<P>
	   Slater told the panel's aviation subcommittee that improving access for U.S.
carriers is a priority, but when asked if he was willing to predict when that
would occur he replied, ``I don't really know.''
</P>
<P>
	   Under the 1977 Bermuda II treaty, U.S. and British carriers each are limited
to 21 daily flights between the countries. Negotiations to expand the treaty
broke down last month.
</P>
<P>
	   USAirways is among the U.S. carriers pushing for expansion of the treaty. It
wants to pick up a Pittsburgh-to-London flight that was discontinued by British
Airways last year because planes were only half-full.
</P>
<P>
	   USAirways Chairman Stephen Wolfe told the subcommittee that the existing
agreement allows the British government and British Airways to ``veto innovative
pricing and, most importantly, to restrict access to London.''
</P>
<P>
	   In written testimony, the British government said it ``habitually honors its
obligations under Bermuda II, and makes concessions beyond it. We are naturally
disappointed when our closest ally does otherwise.''
</P>
<P>
	   It further accused the United States of backing policies that block access
to American markets. One such rule requires government personnel, contractors
and mail to only use American carriers. Britain has no such rule.
</P>
<P>
	   Frederick W. Smith, chairman of FedEx parent FDX Corp., said British and
American negotiators have not paid enough attention to improving the rules for
transporting cargo between the nations.
</P>
<P>
	   He told the panel the failure to reach an agreement ``represents the most
flagrant betrayal of businesses in both the U.S. and UK and the communities they
serve.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
