<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Flake's Support of Gore Attacked  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Rev. Floyd Flake's support of Democratic presidential
front-runner Al Gore is being criticized by a religious watchdog group.
</P>
<P>
	   Americans United for Separation of Church and State has filed a complaint
with the Internal Revenue Service charging Flake, a former Democratic
congressman, with knowingly violating tax laws by backing Gore from the pulpit
of his Queens church on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I don't do endorsements from across the pulpit because I never know who's
out there watching the types of laws that govern separation of church and
state,'' Flake said at his Allen A.M.E. Church. ``But I will say to you this
morning, and you read it well: This should be the next president of the United
States.''
</P>
<P>
	   Gore appeared surprised by the announcement.
</P>
<P>
	   IRS laws prohibit churches and other not-for-profit organizations from
endorsing or opposing candidates for public office.
</P>
<P>
	   Flake called the complaint ``ridiculous.''
</P>
<P>
	   ``I never endorsed Gore. I said I couldn't,'' he said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
	   But Barry Lynn, executive director of the watchdog group, said Flake
``seemed fully aware that his actions were wrong.''
</P>
<P>
	   ``Such a flagrant violation of the law cannot be ignored,'' Lynn said in a
letter Monday to IRS Commissioner Charles Rossotti.
</P>
<P>
	   The IRS did not return a phone call Tuesday seeking comment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
