<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Daimler Employees Sickened by Food  </HEADLINE>
   By JUSTIN HYDE AP Auto Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   DETROIT (AP) -- About 100 employees of Chrysler, Dodge and Jeep auto
dealerships nationwide have reported suffering from food poisoning, possibly
from boxed banquet meals shipped to them by parent company DaimlerChrysler AG.
</P>
<P>
	   DaimlerChrysler has periodically sent out the meals over the past two years
to congratulate dealerships that rated well in sales performance.
</P>
<P>
	   The company stopped all shipments and started contacting dealers after the
first illnesses were reported Thursday, said DaimlerChrysler spokeswoman Kathryn
Blackwell.
</P>
<P>
	   The meals were made only for DaimlerChrysler, said Dan Kurz, spokesman for
HoneyBaked Foods Inc. of Toledo, Ohio. The packages included ham and/or turkey
with side dishes of pasta, cheese, bread and mustard and were packed in ice and
shipped by next-day delivery.
</P>
<P>
	   Blackwell said about 100 employees at about 30 dealerships in 17 states had
reported being sick with a ''24-hour, bad food-type reaction.'' Two people spent
a night in hospitals with the illness, she said.
</P>
<P>
	   She said it was not known what illness the employees had contracted, nor was
it clear what if any food in the package might have been the source.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We're testing all the products,'' Kurz said. ``Obviously, HoneyBaked Foods
is very concerned about the health and safety of our customers.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
