<HEADLINE> Death Row Inmates Prefer Injection  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) -- Not one of Florida's death row inmates has chosen
the electric chair over injection since the state changed its primary method of
execution last month.
</P>
<P>
	   The electric chair, previously the state's sole execution tool, had seen a
decade marked by flames shooting from the apparatus in two executions and blood
flowing from a man's face in a third.
</P>
<P>
	   The Legislature changed the primary method to injection -- saving
electrocution as an option -- after the U.S. Supreme Court agreed to hear a case
challenging its use of the chair. After the state law was changed, the court
backed out of deciding whether the chair was cruel and unusual punishment.
</P>
<P>
	   About two-thirds of the 366 inmates on death row had until Monday to inform
the Florida State Prison warden if they wanted to go to the electric chair
rather than be injected with a fatal combination of drugs.
</P>
<P>
	   None did, said C.J. Drake, a spokesman for the state Department of
Corrections.
</P>
<P>
	   The remaining third still have their first appeal pending before the Florida
Supreme Court. If their sentences are upheld, they will have 30 days to make a
decision.
</P>
<P>
	   Inmates' lawyers have challenged the constitutionality of the law.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
