<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-15 20:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Burlington County school district to ban cell phones in class  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   MEDFORD, N.J. (AP) - Will Lawrence wasn't happy to hear an announcement
in homeroom last week that students could no longer carry cellular phones during
the school day.
<P>
	   Under proposed rule changes in the Lenape Regional High School District,
students would have to leave cell phones in their lockers during classes.
</P>
<P>
	   "It's horrible," said Lawrence, a junior at Lenape High School in Medford.
"If there's an emergency I have to run back to my locker."
</P>
<P>
	   He wants to be able to call his mother and have her come and get him in case
there is another bomb scare in the district, he said Monday.
</P>
<P>
	   Danielle Brining, a special education teacher at Lenape High School, said
after a bomb scare at nearby Shawnee High School last spring, not long after the
school shootings in Littleton, Colo., many students asked their parents for cell
phones. And many got them.
</P>
<P>
	   "Kids felt they had the right to have them," Brining said.
</P>
<P>
	   New Jersey law has prohibited students from carrying beepers onto school
property since the 1980s, when the paging devices were primarily associated with
drug dealers. Exceptions are made for volunteer firefighters and paramedics and
students with certain medical conditions. There is no state regulation for the
use of cell phones in school, leaving each district to create its own policy.
</P>
<P>
	   The Lenape Regional High School District's board of education is expected to
adopt the cell phone ban on Wednesday. The district includes about 6,000
students at Lenape, Shawnee and Cherokee high schools in Burlington County.
</P>
<P>
	   Pat Milich, a spokeswoman for the district, said the board drafted the
policy as a "commonsense approach" to a new technology. It generated no response
from parents, she said.
</P>
<P>
	   Standing in the parking lot of Lenape High School on Monday, students
acknowledged that some use their phones during class.
</P>
<P>
	   "It's mostly the girls," said Ryan Scott, a 17-year-old junior. He keeps his
cell phone in his car. "You don't need a cell phone in school. There are pay
phones."
</P>
<P>
	   Some other New Jersey schools already ban cell phone use during class.
</P>
<P>
	   Several educators said they have not received any complaints from parents -
and few squawks from students - about their bans.
</P>
<P>
	   Christopher Nagy, principal of Allentown High School, said his school
initiated the ban two years ago because students were using them in class.
</P>
<P>
	   "They went off at inappropriate times. They were not part of the educational
environment we were trying to uphold here," Nagy said.
</P>
<P>
	   "Parents understand this is school," said Henry Kiernan, superintendent of
West Morris Regional High School District. "The students must be focused on
their studies, not receiving a phone call during class."
</P>
<P>
	   "It's bad enough when one goes off in a movie theater, said John Kazmark,
principal of Princeton High School. "You can't have that in the classroom."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-02-15-00 2026 </TRAILER>
