<HEADLINE> Cruise Ship Stranded in Caribbean  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI (AP) -- The Carnival Cruise Lines ship Destiny was adrift Tuesday near
the Turks and Caicos Islands because of an electrical problem.
</P>
<P>
	   The Destiny, which was carrying 2,956 passengers on a seven-day eastern
Caribbean cruise, left Miami on Sunday. There were 1,063 crew members on board.
</P>
<P>
	   All shipboard functions were normal and passengers had air conditioning,
running water and working toilets, said Carnival spokesman Andy Newman.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The ship is not in any immediate danger of running aground,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
	   Newman said the ship was on its way to San Juan, Puerto Rico early Tuesday
when one of its two cycloconverters broke down. Cycloconverters transmit
electricity from the ship's diesel engines. As the ship's engineers were trying
to diagnose the problem, the other cycloconverter went down, Newman said.
</P>
<P>
	   More engineers arrived at the ship later Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
	   The ship was about 60 miles east of Grand Turk, Turks and Caicos Islands.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
