<HEADLINE> Nichols Granted Appeal Delay  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER (AP) -- A federal appeals court agreed Tuesday to give more
preparation time to the lawyer handling the appeal for convicted Oklahoma City
bombing conspirator Terry Nichols.
</P>
<P>
	   The 10th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals pushed the due date for Nichols'
opening brief from Feb. 17 to April 3. It is the second delay granted.
</P>
<P>
	   In requesting the delay, attorney Susan L. Foreman said she wanted more time
to review new evidence that forms the basis of the appeal.
</P>
<P>
	   Nichols, 44, is serving a life sentence for his role in the April 1995
Oklahoma City bombing and for the involuntary manslaughter of eight federal
agents who were killed.
</P>
<P>
	   Prosecutors had no objection to Foreman's request, according to the motion.
</P>
<P>
	   Earlier this month, a federal judge turned down a similar request on behalf
of Timothy McVeigh, who was sentenced to die for his role in the bombing.
Prosecutors had opposed that request.
</P>
<P>
	   The bombing of the Oklahoma City federal building killed 168 people and
injured more than 500.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
