<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tipper Gore campaigns for husband in Princeton  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   PRINCETON, N.J. (AP) - One morning at the breakfast table, the Gores
faced a dilemma.
<P>
	   Tipper Gore had a live radio interview later that day, while Al Gore had a
meeting with a foreign head of state. Their son had a school function and wanted
one of his parents there. Tipper told Al she could not cancel her radio
interview, which was about mental illness. So Al Gore rearranged his meeting
with the foreign leader.
</P>
<P>
	   "In this very hectic year of campaigning, my husband was able to make all of
(their son's) football games, said Tipper Gore. "He puts his family first. And
he will continue to put your family first.
</P>
<P>
	   That's the type of tale Tipper Gore wove for women Tuesday, at a fund-raiser
at Jasna Polana, a posh Princeton country club, just a few miles from where Al
Gores primary rival, Bill Bradley, attended college and played basketball for
Princeton University.
</P>
<P>
	   "I wanted them to have a sense of who my husband is as a family man, his
service, his experience, his concerns about education, healthcare and the
environment, she said after the event.
</P>
<P>
	   This is the first time that the vice-presidents wife has campaigned in New
Jersey since Al Gore began his run for president. Her foray into Bradley's home
state influenced at least one voter.
</P>
<P>
	   "Coming here today I had not made up my mind, said Irene Karmazsia, 42, from
Edison. "But, hearing what she had to say, I'm tending to sway toward her
husband. I didn't know his family values.
</P>
<P>
	   Tipper Gore has been campaigning heavily around the country, trying to drum
up support for her husband. On Tuesday, she was far from South Carolina, where
the next presidential primary is scheduled for Saturday.
</P>
<P>
	   That was partly because the New Jersey fund-raiser had been rescheduled from
earlier this month when Tipper Gore was recovering from having a nodule removed
from her thyroid. Doctors were unsure whether the growth was cancerous and so
removed it in late December as a precaution.
</P>
<P>
	   New Jersey's primary is not until June, when many expect the presidential
candidates will already have been chosen.
</P>
<P>
	   The fund-raiser was expected to add more than $55,000 to Gores coffers, said
event organizer Debra Lynch, wife of state Sen. John Lynch, D-Middlesex. The
vice-president has raised close to $900,000 in New Jersey, compared to Bradley's
$2.57 million.
</P>
<P>
	   "I think she sends a clear message that hes on board with we women on
healthcare and that he understands the issues, said Debra Lynch.
</P>
<P>
	   Most of the attendees paid $250 a plate, but about 20 paid $1,000 and were
privy to a brief reception with Tipper Gore after the event.
</P>
<P>
	   Before Gore delivered her 15-minute speech, a lineup of speakers discussed
different issues, including cancer care for women and education for inner city
children.
</P>
<P>
	   "Al has said many times that the very best that we can do for our children
is to give them a healthy start, said Tipper Gore.
</P>
<P>
	   That means access to good healthcare that is "fiscally responsible, and a
good education. Al Gore and Bradley have sparred over their different healthcare
plans, with Gore attacking Bradley's plan as being too expensive.
</P>
<P>
	   Tipper Gore also highlighted her husbands support of abortion rights, noting
that he picked up an endorsement Tuesday from the National Abortion Rights
Action League.
</P>
<P>
	   "This election is going to be very critical in deciding how far were going
to go, she said. "Weve worked hard for the strongest economy ever. But we also
have to continue to unite in spirit and solidify the progress weve made in human
rights and women's rights.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
