<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-15 21:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Doral Cigarettes 'Burn Slower'  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    WINSTON-SALEM, N.C. (AP) -- R.J. Reynolds Tobacco has added more tobacco to
its Doral cigarettes and launched a new advertising slogan in an effort to stop
the slide of the nation's top-selling discount cigarette.
</P>
<P>
	   "Smokers have consistently told us that the primary product-quality issue
among value brands is that they burn too fast and don't last as long as
premium-priced brands," said Doug Shouse, the vice resident for Doral marketing.
</P>
<P>
	   "Packed tighter to burn slower" is Doral's new advertising slogan. RJR said
it will pack all of Doral's 18 styles tighter, but Doral's blend of flue-cured
and burley tobaccos won't change.
</P>
<P>
	   RJR hopes to strengthen its brand as smokers switch to cheaper cigarettes
because premium brands are getting more expensive, said Guy Chance of the
research firm Scott and Stringfellow in Richmond.
</P>
<P>
	   Over the past two years, RJR raised prices 82 cents a pack over the previous
two years to offset costs from the 1997 $206 billion settlement with 46 states,
the company reported.
</P>
<P>
	   "It's a good time for a (Doral ad) campaign to improve market share
considering the tremendous price increase of cigarettes overall," Chance said.
</P>
<P>
	   RJR shipped 26.6 billion Doral cigarettes in 1999, down 13.5 percent from
1998.
</P>
<P>
	   Doral's retail market share slipped from 6.24 percent in the first quarter
last year to 6.20 percent in the fourth quarter, according to Marlin
retail-market share figures, the industry's leading retail-market source.
</P>
<P>
	   Yet Doral remained RJR's top-selling cigarette in 1999 and held the
second-best market share among all domestically sold cigarettes, behind Philip
Morris' premium brand Marlboro.
</P>
<P>
	   Advertisements for the new Doral cigarettes will roll out on store fronts
and counters March 1. RJR said the campaign complements Doral's "Imagine Getting
More" theme introduced in 1998.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-15-00 2103 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000215.0266 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-15 21:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 2 Rwanda Massacre Suspects Arrested  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS (AP) -- French police on Tuesday arrested another suspect in connection
with the 1994 bloodbath that left a half-million people dead.
</P>
<P>
	   The Interior Ministry said that police in south central France, accompanied
by investigators of the International Tribunal for Rwanda, arrested form Rwandan
soldier Francois-Xavier Nzuwonemeye.
</P>
<P>
	   He is the second person arrested in France in three months in connection
with the slaughter of minority Tutsis in Rwanda. Information on his alleged role
in the slaughter was not immediately available.
</P>
<P>
	   Former senior Rwandan official Jean de Dieu Kamuhanda was arrested in
November and extradited to Tanzania earlier this month to stand trial on charges
of genocide.
</P>
<P>
	   A Paris court will decide whether Nzuwonemeye will be extradited to
Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
	   An estimated 500,000 minority ethnic Tutsis and Hutu opposition members were
killed in three months of genocide led by members of the Hutu regime. The
slaughter ended when Tutsi rebels came to power.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-15-00 2106 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
