<HEADLINE> Congo Accused of Executing Soldiers  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- The U.N. human rights expert on Congo accused the
government Tuesday of breaking a 6-week-old moratorium on death sentences by
executing 19 soldiers in the capital, Kinshasa.
</P>
<P>
	   Roberto Garreton said he was deeply dismayed that the day before the
executions started on Jan. 28, Congo's human rights minister reaffirmed the
moratorium in a meeting with him at the United Nations, according to a U.N.
press statement.
</P>
<P>
	   He accused Congo of a ``lack of respect'' for its international commitments.
</P>
<P>
	   The Congo's U.N. Mission said it had no immediate comment on the report.
</P>
<P>
	   Congo has been devastated by a 1 1/2-year-old civil war. The six nations and
three rebel groups involved in the conflict signed a peace accord in Lusaka,
Zambia last summer but intermittent fighting has continued.
</P>
<P>
	   On the issue of executions, the United Nations said Garreton received
information that 19 soldiers accused of murder, armed robbery or revolt were
executed hours after being sentenced to death by Congo's Military Court between
Jan. 28 and Feb. 2.
</P>
<P>
	   Sixty-one other people sentenced to death by the court could also be
executed soon, the U.N. statement said.
</P>
<P>
	   According to Garreton, the sentences cannot be appealed and are ``unfair and
incompatible'' with provisions of the International Covenant on Civil and
Political Rights which Congo has signed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
