<HEADLINE> Records: McCain Family Kept Slaves  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Sen. John McCain's ancestors owned as many as 52 slaves on
their plantation in Mississippi, campaign officials confirmed Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I did not know that,'' McCain said, after being shown documentation by
reporters for Salon, an online magazine.
</P>
<P>
	   The magazine gathered documents from the Carroll County, Mississippi area,
including slave schedules from 1860 that list ``W.A. McCain'' as the owner.
</P>
<P>
	   Campaign press spokesman Todd Harris confirmed McCain's comments Tuesday
night.
</P>
<P>
	   McCain, a decorated Vietnam War veteran and former prisoner of war, declared
the information ``fascinating'' and a surprise because he had always pursued his
family history through the military.
</P>
<P>
	   He said he knew, for example, that William Alexander McCain had fought in
the Civil War.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I guess when you really think about it logically, it shouldn't be a
surprise,'' McCain told the magazine. ``They had a plantation and they fought in
the Civil War, so I guess it makes sense.''
</P>
</TEXT>
