<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-15 21:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Private Co. To Help Keep Mir Alive  </HEADLINE>
   By MARA D. BELLABY Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   LONDON (AP) -- A Bermuda-registered company said Tuesday it has reached an
agreement to lease Russia's Mir space station in a last-ditch effort to keep the
orbiting platform alive.
</P>
<P>
	   MirCorp, which was formed in December, already has paid $20 million to $30
million to the station to keep it up in space at least through the summer, said
its president, Jeffrey Manber. He said another $40 million would need to be
raised to keep the station afloat through the end of the year and beyond.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We think that we can come up with clever imaginative ways to use a manned
orbiting platform,'' Manber said in a telephone interview from Alexandria, Va.
``God bless NASA and all the government space agencies, but we want to unleash
the full imagination of the private sector.''
</P>
<P>
	   No Russian officials were immediately available for comment.
</P>
<P>
	   Mir has been flying without a crew since August, and heavily indebted Russia
had said it would abandon the station next month unless private investors came
up with funding.
</P>
<P>
	   But in January, the Russian government approved a new mission that sent up a
cargo ship earlier this month and is set to blast off with Russian cosmonauts on
March 31. The turnaround came after RKK Energia, which operates the station,
said it had received some foreign funding. No other details were disclosed.
</P>
<P>
	   MirCorp said in a statement that as part of a new agreement, due to be
signed Thursday in London, it would help fund that mission.
</P>
<P>
	   Under the lease agreement, Energia will continue to operate the station.
Energia is 38 percent owned by the Russian government and a majority shareholder
in MirCorp, Manber said.
</P>
<P>
	   MirCorp will seek additional sponsors by offering the use of Mir for
advertising purposes, space tourism and private scientific and pharmaceutical
research, Manber said. He also said the station could be used by private
companies to broadcast live images of the Earth and to repair or manufacture
space satellites.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We believe that Mir is worth $2 billion to $4 billion dollars because it
is in space and it works,'' Manber said. ``It sounds basic, but anything already
in space is priceless compared to planning something on the ground.''
</P>
<P>
	   In addition to appealing to corporate sponsors, Manber said he also hopes to
attract people who see the romantic side of the Mir story -- a space station
created by the former Soviet Union being saved by an international investor for
commercial use.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-15-00 2120 </TRAILER>
