<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-15 21:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Angry with Bradley, abortion rights group pledges to help Gore  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   WASHINGTON (AP) - Angry with Bill Bradley for making abortion rights an
issue in his campaign against Al Gore, leaders of a major abortion rights group
said they would place ads, make phone calls and walk door to door to convince
voters to support the vice president.
<P>
	   The National Abortion and Reproductive Rights Action League, which never
before endorsed a presidential candidate during the primaries, pledged Tuesday
to put its more than 300,000 members and its resources behind Gore now - and in
the general election if he wins the nomination.
</P>
<P>
	   "We reject attempts to use this issue as a political wedge to divide
pro-choice voters," said NARAL President Kate Michelman. "We are unhappy and
very disappointed that the Bradley campaign is using it in this fashion. It is
wrong to do so. It is too important. ... And I must say, personally, it's very
upsetting to see a pro-choice candidate use the issue in this way."
</P>
<P>
	   NARAL doesn't take issue with Bradley's position on abortion. "It's his
tactics that are unacceptable, and I think very harmful," Michelman said.
</P>
<P>
	   Bradley, who spoke with reporters after addressing Jewish leaders in New
York, said he was stunned by the decision. He noted that NARAL gave him a 99
percent rating for his abortion rights voting record when he represented New
Jersey in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
	   By raising the issue, Bradley has tried to point out that while Gore now
supports abortion rights, that wasn't always the case, particularly early in his
political career.
</P>
<P>
	   "For me this is an issue of core conviction on an issue I have believed in
from the beginning of my political life and I will always believe it, so I was
very surprised," Bradley said.
</P>
<P>
	   By comparison, Gore voted in favor of abortion rights only 23 percent of the
time when he was a Tennessee congressman from 1976 to 1982, said Bradley
campaign spokeswoman Kristen Ludecke. She defended the campaign's tactics,
saying Bradley wants the public to know Gore hasn't always supported abortion
rights.
</P>
<P>
	   "Bill Bradley knows that Al Gore had an anti-choice record. Kate Michelman
knows that Al Gore had an anti-choice record. The only person who doesn't seem
to know that is Al Gore. It has been a record which he has failed to
acknowledge, let alone explain," Ludecke said. "This endorsement has very little
to do with the issue of choice and a lot more to do with politics."
</P>
<P>
	   Gore, who appeared with Michelman, said he was grateful for the endorsement.
</P>
<P>
	   "We cannot play political games with an issue as fundamental as a woman's
right to choose," he said. "As president, with your help, I will make sure that
that right to choose is never threatened, never weakened and never taken away."
</P>
<P>
	   Michelman said she is confident in Gore's support.
</P>
<P>
	   "Al Gore is solidly pro-choice, has been a fighter for reproductive rights
and will continue to be," she said. "We had to step out at this moment in time
to set the record straight."
</P>
<P>
	   Bradley said he does not fear a backlash from abortion rights supporters
"because women know where I stand on that issue and they also know what my
record is."
</P>
<P>
	   Gore says he's always supported a woman's right to an abortion and always
believed the procedure should be legal, saying he only had reservations about
government funding of abortions for poor women in Medicaid. But he was forced to
admit to a changed position as details of his record emerged.
</P>
<P>
	   In 1987, he wrote a constituent that abortion was "arguably the taking of a
human life." In 1984, he voted to include "unborn children from the moment of
conception" in the definition of "person" under four existing civil rights laws.
</P>
<P>
	   Michelman said Gore did not seek the endorsement and didn't know the group
was thinking of making one. NARAL decided to back Gore to turn attention to the
anti-abortion records of the leading Republican candidates, Texas Gov. George W.
Bush and Sen. John McCain of Arizona.
</P>
<P>
	   "We need to get the focus where it belongs, which is that both Republican
presidential candidates would use the power of the presidency to end legal
abortion and take away a woman's right to choose," Michelman said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
