<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-15 21:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NATO's Top Official Visits Moscow  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW (AP) -- Calling for a new chapter in Russia's dealings with the West,
NATO's top official arrived in Moscow on Tuesday night for talks aimed at
smoothing relations between Russia and the alliance.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I see this as turning a page on past disagreements and turning to new
chapters of dialogue and cooperation on matters of mutual interest,''
Secretary-General Lord Robertson told reporters upon arrival.
</P>
<P>
	   Robertson said he had brought a document proposed for signing during the
trip but declined to detail its contents.
</P>
<P>
	   Russia's ties with NATO, already strained by the alliance's expansion into
eastern Europe, have been nearly frozen in response to NATO's bombing campaign
in Yugoslavia last year. The two sides have also clashed over Russia's military
campaign in breakaway Chechnya, with NATO accusing Russia of using excessive
force.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We shall be glad to welcome NATO's new secretary-general in Moscow ... but
the Russian position on Chechnya shall not be changed especially on the occasion
of his visit,'' said presidential aide Sergei Yastrzhembsky.
</P>
<P>
	   The visit, he added in comments cited by the Interfax news agency, will help
Robertson ``understand that the criticism directed at Russia does not correspond
to the present realities in Chechnya.''
</P>
<P>
	   Foreign Ministry spokesman Alexander Yakovenko said Robertson would meet
Wednesday with Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov and Defense Minister Igor Sergeyev.
There was no indication that Robertson would be meeting with acting President
Vladimir Putin.
</P>
<P>
	   Robertson has said he is eager to discuss Moscow's new national security
doctrine, which broadens the Kremlin's authority to use nuclear weapons.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
