<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-15 21:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jones Sues Tycoon Over Offer  </HEADLINE>
   By DAVID A. LIEB Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) -- Paula Jones is suing a New York tycoon for the $1
million he had offered her to settle a sexual harassment lawsuit against
President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
	   The lawsuit against Abe Hirschfeld contends he broke a signed contract to
pay Jones after she settled with Clinton for $850,000 in November 1998, said
Jones' attorney Gregory Kitterman of Little Rock.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Paula would not have settled with the president had she not had Abe
Hirschfeld's written promise to pay her,'' Kitterman said.
</P>
<P>
	   The lawsuit was filed Feb. 7 in Dallas County, Texas.
</P>
<P>
	   Hirschfeld said he had not received a copy of the lawsuit and would not pay
Jones.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I don't owe her nothing,'' Hirschfeld said in a telephone interview from
his New York home. ``She didn't want to take my money. I gave her the check, she
gave it back to me.''
</P>
<P>
	   Hirschfeld offered Jones the money in October 1998, but he later sought to
attach conditions to the payment and the offer appeared to fizzle out.
</P>
<P>
	   Lawyer John Whitehead of the conservative Rutherford Institute, which was
providing legal help to Jones, said at the time that the conditions would have
made Hirschfeld's money meaningless.
</P>
<P>
	   But Kitterman said that the signed agreement should still stand.
</P>
<P>
	   Jones contended that Clinton made an unwelcome sexual advance in 1991 in a
Little Rock hotel room while he was Arkansas governor and she was a state
employee.
</P>
<P>
	   A federal judge dismissed the lawsuit, but Jones asked the 8th U.S. Circuit
Court of Appeals to reinstate it. She reached the settlement -- in which Clinton
offered no apology nor admission of guilt -- while the appeal was pending.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
