<HEADLINE> Anti-Chavez Attacks Intensify  </HEADLINE>
   By BART JONES Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) -- Three of the former military officers who helped
President Hugo Chavez stage his famous coup attempt eight years ago stepped up
their attacks against him Tuesday, saying he has betrayed the goals that
prompted their rebellion.
</P>
<P>
	   The former coup leaders charged that Chavez is crushing democratic debate
and running his government and Fifth Republic Movement political party with the
same old-style, backroom politics that have turned the oil-rich nation into a
bastion of poverty and corruption.
</P>
<P>
	   The Chavez government ``doesn't represent in reality the hopes of the people
... for profound change,'' retired Lt. Col. Yoel Acosta Chirinos told a
nationally broadcast press conference in Maracaibo in western Zulia state. He
resigned as general coordinator of the Fifth Republic Movement last week.
</P>
<P>
	   The conflict between Chavez and the three former coup leaders has created
the biggest political crisis of his year-old government and threatens to divide
his governing coalition. The three include Chavez's former intelligence chief,
retired Lt. Col. Jesus Urdaneta, and retired Lt. Col. Francisco Arias Cardenas,
who is now governor of powerful, oil-rich Zulia.
</P>
<P>
	   Chavez's supporters say the three are jealous of the president's political
success and simply want a bigger share of power. Chavez has announced a full
investigation into allegations of corruption in his administration, and says he
has nothing to hide.
</P>
<P>
	   On Tuesday the dispute spilled over to the secret police, where infighting
among Chavez backers led to the house arrest of the head the investigations
unit, Luis Pineda.
</P>
<P>
	   The new police head Eliezer Otaiza said Pineda had refused to accept his
dismissal and was wandering the headquarters without authorization.
</P>
<P>
	   Pineda was appointed by Urdaneta, who charged that the house arrest was
another attempt by Chavez and his supporters to block investigations into
government corruption.
</P>
<P>
	   l
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
