<HEADLINE> ABC Pays Damages to Psychic Network  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    LOS ANGELES (AP) -- ABC paid more than $900,000 to a Psychic Services
Network worker who claimed a secretly made videotape shown on "PrimeTime Live"
ruined his reputation.
</P>
<P>
	   Mark Sanders received a check from the network last week, his attorney,
Neville Johnson, said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
	   A 1993 lawsuit filed by Sanders claimed an "ABC spy" secretly taped him and
his co-workers at the psychic telephone counseling firm with the intent of
portraying such services as "a scam and illegitimate."
</P>
<P>
	   The footage aired on the news magazine "PrimeTime Live" in February 1993. In
1994, a jury awarded Sanders $335,000 in compensatory damages and $300,000 in
punitive damages. ABC appealed, but the verdict was upheld.
</P>
<P>
	   With interest and fees, the total payout rose to $933,992, Johnson said. ABC
spokeswoman Eileen Murphy in New York confirmed the amount paid but said the
network had no comment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
