<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Post Reporter Wins Broun Award  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    WASHINGTON (AP) -- Katherine Boo of The Washington Post won the 1999 Heywood
Broun Award for distinguished journalism for her stories on rapes, physical
abuse and forced labor of retarded people and city officials who profited from
the situation.
</P>
<P>
	   The contest judges also awarded special commendations to Ellen E. Schultze
of The Wall Street Journal for coverage of the push to "modernize" pension plans
and Jason DeParle of The New York Times for his stories about the
welfare-to-work movement and its effect on people.
</P>
<P>
	   The six-member panel of Broun Award judges also noted Boo's extraordinary
perseverance, passion and outrage, qualities the judges said were in the best
tradition of Heywood Broun. The annual award, which carries a $5,000 prize, is
sponsored by The Newspaper Guild-CWA, an affiliate of the Communications Workers
of America.
</P>
<P>
	   Boo was honored for her series called "Invisible Lives" and "Invisible
Deaths," which examined the conditions at group homes for the retarded and later
looked at the deaths of people at group homes.
</P>
<P>
	   In the wake of Boo's reporting, District of Columbia officials closed group
homes, fired several top managers and indicted others.
</P>
<P>
	   Broun, a newspaper columnist in the 1920s and 1930s, was The Newspaper
Guild's founder. The award in his name has been made since 1941.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
