<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 2 More Officers Claim Diallo Threat  </HEADLINE>
   By TOM HAYS Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- Echoing their fellow defendants' accounts, two of the
four New York City police officers on trial for killing an unarmed immigrant
testified Tuesday that the man appeared to draw a gun and take a ``combat
stance.''
</P>
<P>
	   Kenneth Boss, 28, and Richard Murphy, 27, described a frantic search inside
the vestibule of Amadou Diallo's Bronx apartment building for a gun the African
immigrant never had.
</P>
<P>
	   Boss told the jury hearing the four officers' second-degree murder trial
that he was ``destroyed'' when he learned the black object in Diallo's right
hand was a wallet.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I kept praying the weapon would be in there, that it was somewhere,'' Boss
said.
</P>
<P>
	   The four white plainclothes officers had been searching the neighborhood for
armed criminals on Feb. 4, 1999. They saw Diallo at the rear of the 5-by-7-foot
vestibule with his right arm extended, Boss said. He ``was crouched like in a
combat stance. ... The same one I was taught in the police academy,'' Boss said.
</P>
<P>
	   Boss said he saw Officer Edward McMellon fall back off Diallo's doorstep and
thought his colleague had been shot. When the gunfire ended, Boss said, he
grabbed McMellon and ``started feeling his chest, going `Where are you hit,
where are you hit?' ... He said, `I'm not hit.'''
</P>
<P>
	   In a recording of a radio call played for the jury, a frantic-sounding Boss
is heard saying, ``I need a bus forthwith, and a boss'' -- police parlance for
an ambulance and a supervisor.
</P>
<P>
	   The four officers fired 41 shots at Diallo, who was hit 19 times.
</P>
<P>
	   Murphy, who fired four times, testified that he was certain Diallo was
armed.
</P>
<P>
	   ``There was not a doubt in my mind that he had a gun. I had a sick feeling
in my stomach that I was going to be hit at any second. That's why I fired,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
	   McMellon, 27, and the fourth defendant, Sean Carroll, who turned 37 Tuesday,
took the stand Monday to explain why they each fired 16 shots.
</P>
<P>
	   All four officers emphasized similar points: that it was dark; that Diallo
ignored orders to halt for questioning; that he remained on his feet throughout
the gunfire. Each officer denied shooting the victim after he was down.
</P>
<P>
	   The prosecution contends the officers never yelled a warning before
cornering Diallo and opening fire. Autopsy findings supported the prosecutors'
contention that several of the bullets hit Diallo while he was going down.
</P>
<P>
	   Family members and supporters of the officers sat in the Albany courtroom
Tuesday while the men testified. Many wore buttons reading: ``Free the Bronx
Four.''
</P>
<P>
	   The trial was moved to Albany after the shooting sparked protests and
allegations of widespread police abuse of minorities.
</P>
<P>
	   Testimony was expected to continue through the end of this week. If
convicted, the four could be sentenced to 25 years to life in prison.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
