<HEADLINE> Tuesday's Canada News Briefs  </HEADLINE>
   By The Associated Press Note: All dollars are Canadian unless otherwise noted
<TEXT>
<P>
	   ------
</P>
<P>
	   Toronto Co. Wants Warrant for ID
</P>
<P>
	   TORONTO (AP) -- An Internet company says it will hand over the identity of a
possible suspect in last week's Internet hacking bonanza if it's presented with
a search warrant.
</P>
<P>
	   Internet Direct of Toronto confirmed Tuesday someone using the handle
``mafiaboy'' was on an Internet provider, called Delphi Supernet, that the
company purchased last year.
</P>
<P>
	   Authorities say an Internet user with the same handle is a suspect in the
sabotage, which wrecked a number of major U.S. and other Internet sites last
week.
</P>
<P>
	   Company vice-president Colin Campbell said at a news conference Internet
Direct doesn't know whether its client is the one the FBI is seeking. The client
was allegedly kicked off Montreal-based Delphi Supernet in 1998 for abusing the
system.
</P>
<P>
	   Campbell added the client's identity will be made available if authorities
obtain a search warrant.
</P>
<P>
	   ------
</P>
<P>
	   Abbott Ejected From Commons
</P>
<P>
	   OTTAWA (AP) -- The political dispute over federal job-creation grants turned
personal Tuesday, as Reform MP Jim Abbott was ejected from the Commons for
accusing Human Resources Minister Jane Stewart of lying.
</P>
<P>
	   The exchange was sparked when Stewart maintained that individual Reform MPs
have been contacting her office to press for grants in their ridings -- while
their colleagues simultaneously denounce such spending as a waste.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The Reform party says it wants to kill these programs,'' Stewart told the
House.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Except when we have individual members who know that the Transitional Jobs
Fund, the Canada Jobs Fund ... and other programs make a difference to
individuals in their ridings.''
</P>
<P>
	   She identified three British Columbians -- Abbott, Mike Scott and Reed Elley
-- as Reformers who ``keep calling my office saying can't you please hurry up
and approve the application.''
</P>
<P>
	   Abbott objected that he had never personally called Stewart's office and
characterized the minister's words as lies -- a use of unparliamentary language
that got him turfed from the chamber by Speaker Gilbert Parent.
</P>
<P>
	   Stewart later clarified her statement to explain it was a member of Abbott's
staff who had called her office. Scott also had a staff member do the phoning,
while Elley sent a personal letter to the minister.
</P>
<P>
	   All three Reformers insisted, in separate interviews, that they disagree in
principle with government handouts for business. But all said they felt a duty
all the same to companies in their ridings that had applied for federal money
under the Canada Jobs Fund.
</P>
<P>
	   ------
</P>
<P>
	   Thomson To Sell Most Newspapers
</P>
<P>
	   TORONTO (AP) -- Thomson Corp., once Canada's dominant newspaper chain, plans
to sell all its papers except the Globe and Mail in Toronto as it focuses on
expanding its specialized information services businesses.
</P>
<P>
	   Thomson said Tuesday it expects the sale of 55 daily and 75 non-daily papers
in Canada and the United States -- valued at $1.3 billion -- to close in the
second half of the year.
</P>
<P>
	   The five Canadian dailies being sold are the Winnipeg Free Press and Brandon
Sun in Manitoba, the Lethbridge Herald and Medicine Hat News in southern Alberta
and the Thunder Bay Chronicle-Journal in Northern Ontario.
</P>
<P>
	   Thomson's properties will be eyed by various other newspaper chains,
including Conrad Black's wide-reaching Hollinger Inc., printing giant Quebecor
Inc., and southern Ontario-based Torstar Corp.
</P>
<P>
	   But Prime Minister Jean Chretien told the House of Commons on Tuesday that
his government may have to intervene if the proposed sale results in too much
concentration in the industry.
</P>
<P>
	   ------
</P>
<P>
	   Justice Cites 'Gun Epidemic'
</P>
<P>
	   TORONTO (AP) -- The Ontario government should abandon a challenge of new
federal gun laws and instead take its own steps to curb the province's ``gun
epidemic,'' a provincial Liberal justice critic says.
</P>
<P>
	   Michael Bryant outlined a five-point plan of action Tuesday that includes
taking U.S. gun manufacturers to court to recoup health costs, a tactic already
in use there.
</P>
<P>
	   Bryant also wants Premier Mike Harris to require trigger locks on new guns
sold in Ontario, start incentive-based swap programs and set up a provincial gun
registry, should the Supreme Court allow it.
</P>
<P>
	   ``It's time for the government to pass legislation that will actually do
something about the gun epidemic in Ontario,'' Bryant said.
</P>
<P>
	   Ottawa's gun control law, drafted by the federal Liberals and passed in
Parliament in 1995, requires every gun owner to be licensed by Jan. 1, 2001 and
to register every firearm they own by Jan. 1, 2003.
</P>
<P>
	   ------
</P>
<P>
	   Weed Said Threat to Great Lakes
</P>
<P>
	   OTTAWA (AP) -- A nasty foreign weed is moving inexorably northward from the
United States posing a major threat to Canadian lakes, an international
conference on nuisance species heard Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
	   Hydrilla has been devastating waterways from Florida to Connecticut and has
the potential to cause heavy ecological and economic damage in Canada, John
Madsen of the U.S. Army Corps of Engineers said.
</P>
<P>
	   The plant can completely cover the water surface in shallow waters,
preventing sunlight from reaching other species underneath, Madsen said in an
interview from the Toronto conference.
</P>
<P>
	   It is impossible to predict when the plant will reach the Great Lakes
because it has been progressing in unpredictable jumps.
</P>
<P>
	   Hydrilla, believed to have originated in India and Korea, can thrive in
almost any fresh body of water and would likely do well in the Great Lakes and
in nearby cottage country, said Madsen.
</P>
<P>
	   ------
Woman Will Admit Guilt on Immigration
</P>
<P>
	   BURLINGTON, Vt. (AP) -- A Montreal woman linked by prosecutors to Algerians
thought to be plotting a bombing has agreed to plead guilty to two immigration
charges, U.S. court documents indicate.
</P>
<P>
	   Lucia Garofalo, 35, agreed to plead guilty to conspiring to transport an
alien within the United States and attempting to transport an alien within the
United States, said the documents filed today in U.S. district court.
</P>
<P>
	   Garofalo was arrested Dec. 19 at the Quebec-Vermont border with an Algerian
Manitoba
</P>
<P>
	   ``The defendant represents that she intends to plead guilty because she is,
in fact, guilty of the crime with which she is charged,'' says the plea
agreement.
</P>
</TEXT>
