<HEADLINE> Japan Stocks Fall  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    TOKYO (AP) -- Japanese stocks fell moderately Wednesday morning on
profit-taking following recent gains. The dollar edged higher against the yen.
</P>
<P>
	   The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average shed 46.67 points, or 0.24
percent, to 19,321.16 at the end of the morning session. On Tuesday, the average
closed down 188.63 points, or 0.96 percent.
</P>
<P>
	   The dollar bought 109.25 yen, up 0.09 yen from late Tuesday in Tokyo and
also above its late New York level of 109.05 yen.
</P>
<P>
	   On the stock market, the Nikkei moved slightly higher early in the session,
but traders said it later moved into negative territory as the market
consolidated after closing above 20,000 points for the first time in 31 months
last Thursday.
</P>
<P>
	   A report Wednesday in the Nihon Keizai Shimbun financial daily that the
ruling Liberal Democratic Party's tax panel is considering a new tax system from
fiscal 2001 caused concern in the market, traders said.
</P>
<P>
	   The system would tax companies on the basis of sales or amount of capital,
rather than income, the report said.
</P>
<P>
	   "Such a system would increase the tax burden on corporations and slow down
the economic recovery," said Hidenori Karaki, general manager at
Tokyo-Mitsubishi Personal Securities.
</P>
<P>
	   In New York, the Dow Jones industrial average rose 198.25, or 1.9 percent,
to 10,718.09 at Tuesday's close.
</P>
<P>
	   The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the first
section was down 29.78 points, or 1.76 percent, to 1,660.36. The TOPIX closed
down 27.27 points, or 1.59 percent, the day before.
</P>
<P>
	   In currency dealings, the dollar moved narrowly against the yen as investors
looked for new trading incentives. Market players were also waiting for
congressional testimony by U.S. Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
	   In other currencies, the euro was quoted at 107.25 yen, up from 107.19 yen
late Tuesday in Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
	   The yield on the benchmark 10-year Japanese government bond fell to 1.7900
percent from Tuesday's finish of 1.8000 percent. Its price rose 0.09 point to
99.23.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
