<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wal-Mart Finds Sales, Charity Link  </HEADLINE>
    By KRISTEN EVERETT Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) -- With its year-end sales figures, Wal-Mart Stores
Inc. released data Tuesday indicating that the stores that sold the most also
gave the most to charity.
</P>
<P>
	   The 100 stores with the highest sales contributed three times as much to
their communities as the 100 stores with the lowest sales in the fiscal year
that ended Jan. 31, Wal-Mart officials said.
</P>
<P>
	   "I think there is definitely a connection and it has been proven year after
year," said Betsy Reithemeyer, director of the Wal-Mart Foundation and the
company's community affairs office.
</P>
<P>
	   Bentonville-based Wal-Mart said Tuesday that its annual sales were up 26
percent over last year; the amount given to communities in 1999 was up 28
percent.
</P>
<P>
	   Wal-Mart gives each of its stores money it can use in the community, with
the amounts based on store size, Reithemeyer said. She said money is given to
stores because company officials in Bentonville don't know what's needed in
communities in other states.
</P>
<P>
	   But the stores also chip in money for their communities, she said.
</P>
<P>
	   Last year, Wal-Mart raised and donated $164 million nationally. Of that, $80
million was allocated from Wal-Mart headquarters to each store.
</P>
<P>
	   The Wal-Mart stores that gave the most to charity among other stores in
their divisions were: Bentonville; Jasper, Ala.; Santee, Calif.; Bangor, Maine;
Bloit, Wis.; and Mocksville, N.C.
</P>
<P>
	   For Sam's Clubs, the Jacksonville, Fla., store was the top giver.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
