<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-15 22:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Obituaries in the News  </HEADLINE>
   By The Associated Press Dean Davenport
<TEXT>
<P>
	   PANAMA CITY, Fla. (AP) -- Retired Air Force Col. Dean Davenport, co-pilot of
the bomber ``Ruptured Duck'' during the daring Doolittle Raid on Japan early in
World War II, died Monday. He was 81.
</P>
<P>
	   Lt. Ted W. Lawson, Davenport's pilot, wrote a book about the Doolittle Raid
titled ``Thirty Seconds Over Tokyo.'' Davenport served as technical adviser when
the book was made into a movie starring Spencer Tracy as Gen. James ``Jimmy''
Doolittle.
</P>
<P>
	   The Ruptured Duck was one of 16 B-25 Mitchell bombers launched from the deck
of the USS Hornet about 650 miles from Tokyo on April 18, 1942. All but seven of
the 80 crew members survived and returned to the United States, even though most
had to bail out or crash-land before reaching landing strips in China because
they had run out of fuel.
</P>
<P>
	   Davenport was injured when the Ruptured Duck ditched into the South China
Sea after the Tokyo raid. Davenport eventually made his way to Egypt where he
took a commercial flight to Miami.
</P>
<P>
	   He later flew 86 combat missions during the Korean War. He retired in 1967.
John Clint Dennis
</P>
<P>
	   CAPE GIRARDEAU, Mo. (AP) -- John Clint Dennis, a Democratic sheriff and
state senator from southeast Missouri for 40 years, died Tuesday. He was 82.
</P>
<P>
	   Dennis was Scott County sheriff from 1951 until 1976, when he was elected to
the first of four terms in the Missouri Senate. After 16 years as a senator,
Dennis didn't seek re-election in 1992.
Leonard Phelps Good
</P>
<P>
	   CHICKASHA, Okla. (AP) -- Leonard Phelps Good, an artist, historian and
former head of the art department at Drake University, died Sunday. He was 92.
</P>
<P>
	   Good taught art in public schools in Texas and Oklahoma from 1927 to 1930.
He was a member of the faculty at the University of Oklahoma School of Art from
1930 to 1950.
</P>
<P>
	   Good became head of the art department at Drake in Des Moines, Iowa, in
1952. He served in that position until 1968 and remained at the school until
1977 as a professor and emeritus professor.
</P>
<P>
	   His art work is in galleries across the United States.
John C. Kuehne
</P>
<P>
	   ROCKPORT, Texas (AP) -- John C. Kuehne, who played music with The Monkees,
Linda Ronstadt and James Taylor, died Saturday. He was 58.
</P>
<P>
	   The cause of death was not released.
</P>
<P>
	   An accomplished bass player, he attended San Antonio College and won musical
competitions along with Michael Nesmith.
</P>
<P>
	   When Nesmith was chosen for a starring role with The Monkees, a 1960s
television sitcom about a pop music group, Kuehne became a backstage player with
the show. Under the stage name John London, Kuehne did musical work with the
group and played small roles in some episodes.
</P>
<P>
	   He later was a studio musician for Ronstadt, Taylor and others. Kuehne left
California and returned to San Antonio in the early 1970s.
</P>
<P>
	   Kuehne worked in advertising sales for both the San Antonio Express-News and
the San Antonio Light. After the Light closed in 1993, Kuehne and his family
moved to the Gulf Coast, where he joined the Corpus Christi Caller-Times.
G. Leon Netterville
</P>
<P>
	   BATON ROUGE, La. (AP) -- Former Southern University President G. Leon
Netterville, who oversaw the historically black school during times of student
unrest in the early 1970s, died Saturday. He was 93.
</P>
<P>
	   A longtime Southern University administrator, Netterville became the
school's president in 1968.
</P>
<P>
	   The shooting deaths of two students during a protest on campus in 1972
weighed heavily on him and he resigned later that year, according to Clayton
Lewis, retired University Relations director.
Elmer Redd
</P>
<P>
	   HOUSTON (AP) -- Elmer Redd, the longtime University of Houston Cougars
assistant football coach who assisted Bill Yeoman through some of the program's
glory years, died Friday. He was 71.
</P>
<P>
	   Redd retired from Houston in 1986 after 17 seasons with the Cougars. During
that time, the team entered the Southwest Conference and immediately became a
power in the league.
Vitamin T. Smith
</P>
<P>
	   LAKE DALLAS, Texas (AP) -- Vitamin T. Smith, a running back for the 1951
National Football League champion Los Angeles Rams who once held the single
season record for kickoff returns for touchdowns, died Monday. He was 76.
</P>
<P>
	   Smith joined the Rams in 1949.
</P>
<P>
	   He led the team and the league in receiving and kick and punt returns. In
five seasons, Smith accumulated 1,025 receiving yards and 12 touchdowns;
returned 75 punts for 814 yards and one touchdown; and returned 57 kickoffs for
1,453 yards and three touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
	   Smith led the league in punt returns in 1949 with 427 yards and one
touchdown and led the league in kickoff returns in 1950 with 742 yards and three
touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
	   Smith's three kickoff returns for touchdowns stood as the NFL record until
Green Bay's Travis Williams returned four in 1967.
</P>
<P>
	   Smith retired from the NFL in 1953 to work in the oil industry.
William Oliver Swofford
</P>
<P>
	   SHREVEPORT, La. (AP) -- William Oliver Swofford, a singer who under the
stage name Oliver had late-'60s hits with the songs ``Good Morning, Starshine''
and ``Jean,'' died Saturday of cancer. He was 54.
</P>
<P>
	   In 1969, his recording of ``Starshine,'' from the Broadway musical ``Hair,''
climbed to No. 3 on the pop charts and the ballad ``Jean'' reached No. 2.
</P>
<P>
	   He toured throughout the 1970s, then left the music business in the 1980s
and worked in the home-construction and pharmaceutical industries.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
