<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-15 23:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Pulls Out of C. African Rep.  </HEADLINE>
   By JOSEPH BENAMMSE Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   BANGUI, Central African Republic (AP) -- United Nations peacekeepers
formally ended their presence in the Central African Republic Tuesday, fueling
public fears of escalating lawlessness and banditry.
</P>
<P>
	   In a quiet handover ceremony at a U.N. base in the capital, departing force
commander Gen. Barthelemy Ratanga shook hands with Secretary-General Kofi
Annan's representative, Baryu Adeyeni, who will lead a small team of 20
political observers who are expected to arrive in April.
</P>
<P>
	   A Senegalese peacekeeping contingent flew out of the capital over the
weekend, leaving Ratanga and a handful of officers the only remaining members of
the 1,350-member force.
</P>
<P>
	   The U.N. force replaced French soldiers who helped implement a peace accord
in 1998.
</P>
<P>
	   The government has welcomed the peacekeepers' departure, saying it was time
for them to go after a two-decade presence by troops from France, the country's
former colonial ruler, and other foreign countries.
</P>
<P>
	   Yet many civilians and opposition groups expressed dismay Tuesday at the
pullout which came during a rash of armed robberies and car hijackings.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We are attacked day after day in our homes and on the streets by men with
Kalashnikovs (automatic rifles). We will need U.N. soldiers for years to come,''
complained Mama Mariam, a civic leader in Bangui's middle-class Fondo
neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
	   Mutinous soldiers staged three major uprisings in the Central African
Republic since 1996 against President Ange-Felix Patasse, whose election in 1993
ended more than a decade of army rule. Patasse won re-election late last year
amid opposition claims of voting fraud.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-15-00 2317 </TRAILER>
