<BODY>
<HEADLINE> House Votes To Award Cardinal Medal  </HEADLINE>
   By SHANNON McCAFFREY Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The House voted Tuesday to award an ailing Cardinal John
O'Connor the Congressional Gold Medal, the body's highest civilian honor.
</P>
<P>
	   The longtime leader of the New York Archdiocese's 2.4 million Roman
Catholics recently turned 80 and had surgery last fall to remove a brain tumor.
He is expected to retire as soon as Pope John Paul II appoints a replacement.
</P>
<P>
	   The House voted 413-1 to give the award to O'Connor. Rep. Ron Paul, R-Texas,
was the lone opponent. Paul said he has great respect for the cardinal but
opposed the $30,000 it would cost to mint the medal.
</P>
<P>
	   Separately, the House voted 410-1 to give a Congressional Gold Medal to
``Peanuts'' creator Charles Schulz, who died in his sleep Saturday. The
77-year-old cartoonist's last strip featuring Snoopy and the gang was published
in Sunday's papers. Paul also cast the only dissenting vote for the Schulz
medal.
</P>
<P>
	   The Senate is expected to approve both honors next month.
</P>
<P>
	   House Majority Leader Dick Armey, R-Texas, told reporters that O'Connor was
being ``justifiably honored'' and insisted the award was not an attempt to
appease Catholics upset by a flap over the appointment of a new House chaplain.
</P>
<P>
	   House GOP leaders nominated the Rev. Charles Wright, a Presbyterian
minister, for the $138,000-a-year position even though the Rev. Timothy O'Brien,
a Catholic priest, was the top choice of a bipartisan committee of lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
	   Some Democrats have accused GOP leaders of being anti-Catholic, a charge
they deny. A vote on the nomination is pending.
</P>
<P>
	   Before Tuesday's vote, lawmakers extolled O'Connor's work on behalf of the
needy, inner-city children, AIDS patients and others. They also spoke of his
leadership in establishing diplomatic ties between the Vatican and Israel and
his years of service as a military chaplain.
</P>
<P>
	   ``John Cardinal O'Connor is a great man,'' said Rep. Vito Fossella, R-N.Y.,
who nominated O'Connor for the medal. ``Soldiers, priests and parishioners know
in their hearts that the cardinal has always been a man of the people.''
</P>
<P>
	   At the same time, O'Connor, the oldest active bishop in the United States
and a close ally of the pope, drawing criticism over the years for denouncing
homosexuality, premarital sex and birth control.
</P>
<P>
	   He also has not been averse to mixing politics and religion for causes he
believes in. In 1990, he wrote that anyone ``advocating legislation supporting
abortion, or by making public funds available for abortion ... must be warned
that they are at risk of excommunication.'' The warning was a slap at Catholic
abortion rights supporters such as Geraldine Ferraro and then-Gov. Mario Cuomo.
</P>
<P>
	   ``He has had many critics,'' acknowledged Rep. John LaFalce, D-N.Y. ``But
from the beginning of life to the very cessation of life, Cardinal O'Connor was
consistent in his belief that all deserved justice under the law and as much
human love as mankind was capable of.''
</P>
<P>
	   O'Connor served as a chaplain in the Navy and Marines for 27 years and saw
combat in Korea. He was named bishop in Scranton, Pa., in 1983 and has led the
Archdiocese of New York since 1984.
</P>
<P>
	   O'Connor offered his resignation on his 75th birthday, as the church
requires, but the pope did not accept it. Cardinals lose their power to vote for
a new pope when they turn 80.
</P>
<P>
	   After an absence last year due to surgery and radiation treatments, O'Connor
is back celebrating Sunday Mass at New York's St. Patrick's Cathedral. His frail
condition has made it hard for him to stand and he delivers the homily from a
chair.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-15-00 2342 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000215.0320 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-15 23:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Westminster Dog Show Opens  </HEADLINE>
   By MARGARET LILLARD Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) -- Gwen DeMilta's dog wasn't distracted by the noise and the
crowds at the Westminister Kennel Club Show. The Doberman had found something a
lot more interesting: the dried chunks of liver stuffed squirrel-like in
DeMilta's cheeks.
</P>
<P>
	   DeMilta used the meat-in-the-mouth trick to get Trevor's undivided
attention. And Trevor, the nation's top-ranked Doberman pinscher, was positively
hypnotized by the sight.
</P>
<P>
	   Some 2,600 dogs in 156 breeds and varieties competed Monday and Tuesday at
the nation's most prestigious dog competition. But it can be almost as
entertaining to watch the tricks performed by the humans to make their dogs look
their best.
</P>
<P>
	   In the staging area at Madison Square Garden, the air buzzes with the sound
of hair dryers and clippers. Handlers wield squeeze bottles of water and metal
combs to tame last-minute dog hair disasters.
</P>
<P>
	   Long-haired breeds such as poodles, shih tzus and spaniels are kept with
their hair tucked in curlers, pins or even doggy snoods until they head for the
competition ring.
</P>
<P>
	   Even there, handlers primp whenever the judges' backs are turned, using
silver show combs to capture stray hair, or a towel to mop up mastiff slobber.
</P>
<P>
	   When the handlers show off their animals, they match their strides to the
gallop of a Great Dane or the dainty trot of a Chihuahua.
</P>
<P>
	   And they console and cajole and bribe their dogs with treats and toys --
anything to draw out the sparkling personality that can set a dog apart from the
pack.
</P>
<P>
	   As DeMilta tried to calm Trevor with liver treats, her daughter had
different tricks to get her own Doberman, Edna, to pay attention.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Ee-ee-EE! Ee-ee-EE!'' Carissa DeMilta squeaked as the dog aimed her pointy
ears at the ceiling. ``Edna! Ee-EE!''
</P>
<P>
	   On Monday, Trevor won an award of merit, which is similar to an honorable
mention. On Tuesday night, the highest award -- best of show -- was presented to
Samantha, an English springer spaniel owned by Carl Blain and Fran Sunseri of
Sacramento, Calif. Samantha is the 5 1/2-year-old daughter of 1993 top dog
Salilyn's Condor
</P>
<P>
	   The dog handler's guidance is critical at a show like Westminster, where
there are big crowds and lots of distractions.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Sometimes it's hard if the dog hasn't been here before because it's very
chaotic with the people crowding in,'' 17-year-old Carissa DeMilta said. ``You
have to try to make the dog feel it's doing what it wants to do, trying to keep
its attention away from other things.''
</P>
<P>
	   Liver treats were popular among the Doberman handlers. Carissa DeMilta held
a bit of food in her hand to get Edna's attention. Other handlers flicked bits
ahead of their dogs or waved a treat in the air.
</P>
<P>
	   Most avoided Gwen DeMilta's in-the-mouth technique.
</P>
<P>
	   ``It's a nervous habit,'' said DeMilta, a professional trainer for 22 years
who lives in Downingtown, Pa. ``I need to get to it quick -- don't want it
getting stuck in my pocket. It tastes pretty awful.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-02-15-00 2342 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
